HONORATISSIMO
ATQVE CLARISSIMO
VIRO, GVILIELMO CECILIO,
Baroni Burgleiensi, nobilis Equestris ordinis
Garthery Sodali, summo Angliæ Thesau­
rario, & CANTEBRIGIENSIS
Academiæ Cancellario dignissimo.

SI quis fortè iniquus laboris nostri
iudex nobis exprobret, quòd post
tot veteres atq; novos scriptores
quadriennio à me impressos, hodi­
erno primùm die nostri characteres
te (Vir illustrissime) salutare aude­
ant, si æqua trutina libraverit, quàm
illiberale sit, ne dicam morosum, de alieno liberalem,
de suo parcum esse, ac Aesopicæ velut corniculæ plu­
mis sese ostentare, Vti.

Laudat as extendit avis Iunonia pennas;

Idem nodum in scirpo quærere, ac nobis cauillari
desinet. Nam, cùm opera, quæ ex nostra officina hacte­
nus prodierunt omnia, vel auctorum solo nomine, aut
rerum pondere, contra omnium obtrectantium livo­
rem, satis sibi præsidij comparârint, nec quic quam ferè
mihi præter typos acceptum referre debuerint, ab omni
nuncupandi studio prorsus abstinendum putavi, ne no­
stram operam, quæ nulla esset, nugivendorum more,
vmbrâ impositurus, iactare, qut ex aliorum sudoribus
nobilium amicitiam venari, auramve popularem, am­
bitione non ferenda, captare viderer. Istud verò qua­
lecunq; fit, cùm me parentem suum porfiteatur, tan­
tumque absit, vt auctoris dignitate, aut rei novitate
commendetur, vt verendum potiùs sit, ne eo nomine





EPISTOLA

peiùs audiat, eò transferendum censui, vbi certas sedes
(simereatur) & patrocinium, aut nusquam gentium sa­
tis tutum inveniret: vt si minùs nostris, aut suis viribus,
patroni saltem validioris auctoritate se tueatur. Ieiuna
enim nomina & verba suis convinctionibus, tanquam
scopæ dissolutæ, spoliata, cui persuadebunt? cuius be­
nevolentiam conciliabunt? quem in suam sententiam
aut subsidium pertrahent? quod robur, quas vires ad ma­
levolorum ac invidorum insultus repellendos adfe­
rent? qui private quæstus gratia susque deque ferunt,
quorsum bonarum artium ac literarum studia eva­
dant. Quanquam verò cur sua meritissima laude frau­
darem? quæ Platonis verissima sententia (ὁ ἀν ἐιδη Τὰ ὀνό­
μαΤα, είτεται καί Τά ωράγμαΤα) ab omni contemtu vindi­
cabit. Sunt enim verba rerum notæ, vt scripta vocis, o­
rationes mentium sunt symbola, quibus artes omnes &
disciplinæ, tanquam in nuce nucleus, inclusæ delites­
cunt. Nec vnquam ἀκροάμαΤα illa Macedo historiis ce­
lebratissimus adultus intellexisset, si Acroaticis libris æ­
dita καΤηγρήμαΤα (id est, ὀνόμαΤα, καὶ ρ ὴμαΤα) καὶ στωδεσμγς,
ab Aristotele magistro in Exotericis libris tradita neg­
lexisset. Non deerunt fortasse, qui maledicendi confe­
cti morbo, aut Momi in morem omnia carpendi studio
rabidi, indignum clamabunt tanto viro, in clarissima
Reip. luce, ab aute & ære R. Maiestatis, hoc est, sum­
mo honorum fastigio constituto, nudas voces nuncupa­
re. At exemplo Iulii Pollucis me communiam, qui O­
nomasticon libris decem, intimis aulæ penetralibus, in
Commodi Imperatoris manus invexerat. Sed quò ali­
âs remittent? Fossuras credo aut araturas rus ablega­
bunt, vbi omnis verborum delectus, & ornata oratio
irridetur. Quò precor se priùs aut potiùs reciperent,
quàm in aulam? vbi aut situm aptiorem, aut vsum lepi­





DEDICATORIA.

diorem, aut compositionem concinniorem nancisce­
rentur? Cùm enim in aula lepos ac sermonis venustas niti­
dissimè resplendeat, non possunt perennes istæ non per­
placere scaturigines, vnde omnis venustas & comta fluat
oratio. Aut cui potiùs primitias nostrarum vigiliarum
consecrarem, quàm ei viro, quem Musæ Cantebrigien­
ses dignissimum præsidem iampridem delegerunt? qui
vt totius Academie labores, ita si quis ingenii mei foetus,
si quæ studiorum vsura aut in crementium, illus omne si­
bi suo quodam iure vindicare poterit. Sed frustra istos
scrupulos, apudrerum omnium sagacissimum, eleure co­
nor. Hem tibi (Musarum Patrone selectissime) simo­
lestum non sit, Novum Dictionarium, nullis adhus ma­
nibus tritum, & proinde nulla re alia quàm tuo nomine,
ac nostris (qualescunque illi fuerint) laboribus com­
mendatum. Quòd si in tuam tutelam suscipere, & quo
foles vultu scholastica munera, intueri non dedigneris,
ad maiota ac meliora animum reddes alactiorem.
Quid autem hoc opere prestiterim, cùm nec me modus
epistolæ, describere, nec te tuæ occupationes legere pa­
tianturm, in lectoris oculos & aures incurrere malim. Hoc
tantùm bona doctiorum venia affirmare liceat, præter
illa vocabula, quæ superiores adferunt, qui in hoc scri­
bendi genere suas symbol as contulerunt, nostrum plus
minus bis mille civ es lectissimos in vulgatissimis quæ
circumferuntur lexicis desideratos, in Latium invex­
isse, aut si mavis extorres & exules, tanquam postliminio
reversos, suæ pristinæ dignitati restituisse. Quod super­
est, Deum optimum Maximum obtestor, vt te Serenissi­
mæ Reginæ, roti Reip. nostræque Academiæ quàm diu­
tissimè conservet incolumem. Ex officina nostra tertio
Nonas Septemb. 1587.

Amplitudinis tuæ studiosissimus
Thomas Thomasius.





TYPOGRAPHVS LECTORI
S.D.P.

MIraberis fortasse (lector humanissime) & in tanta
Lexicographorum peritissimorum turba supervacuum
esse putabis, quòd in hanc arenam, quæ multorum
subiacet invidiæ, quasi cornicum oculos configere
noliar, discendere voluissem: verum si consily
nei rationem cognoveris, minus mirari nostrisve
conatibus obniti, aut hominum doctissimorum fi­
lem in dubium vocare perges. Illi enim cùm suos
thesauros e divite lectionis penu depromptos, multo auro, sed vix nisi mag­
natibus redimendos prostare voluerint, nunquam mihi invidebunt, si imi
subselly hominibus, aut teneris puerorum viribus consuluisse videar, qui

Læva suspensi loculos tabulamque lacerto
Ibunt octonis referentes Idibus æra.

Nam cùm locupletissimi atq, amplissimi Gymnasiarchis libri extiterint,
quibus Musæorum privatos, aut scholarum communes pluteos onerent, cur
discipulis ipsis sua enchiridia tam diu desiderata semper deesse debebunt,
quæ parvo ære comparata, sibiq, ad manum parata, levi onere circumfe­
rant? Ad me verò quod attinet, tantum abest vt aliquem sua laude pri­
vare velim, vt cùm omnium fere pagin, is non oscitanter hoc sesquiennio e­
volverim, vixtamen dicere queam

Iudiciumve priùs mirer, laudemne laborem.

Et nisi stultpudeat confiteri per quos profecerim, omnibus etiam me
devinctum non possum non profiteri: ex omnium ego facibus incendium
arripui, & in nostram faculam retuli. Precibus enim Ludimagistrorum
ac studiosorum victus, quibus accessit etiam amicorum frequens postulatio,
ex immenso Lexicorum pelago nostrum contraxi, quod trivialibus saltem
ludis inserviret: ita tamen, vt nullum, quod sciam, vocabulum, quod vspi­
am extaret, post Perottum aut Calepinum æditum, qui iam tandem in δι­
κάΤ γλιον excrevit, omiserim.

Primam autem illam & propriam singulorum significationem Anglicè
præmittere, deinde eas, quas aliunde haberent, subycere, aut si neutrum sa­
tis commodè fieri potuisset, insigni aliqua phrasi indicate placuit. In qui­
bus ad Lidium veluti lapidem exigendis, si à multis dissentiam, id nos ex
vetustissimorum Grammaticorum, & Adriana Iuny (quo nemo mihs
ὰκριζισΤερως saxum hoc volvisse videtur) sententia fecisse intelli­
gat. Peropportunè enim, per (inquam) opportunè, dum opus hoc meditarer,
ex insperato nihi ista adminicula sese obtulerunt, quibus cùm plæriq, om­
nes destituerentur, mirtum non est, sitemporum, quamvis non sua, culpa, ma­




PRAEFATIO AD

gni etiam nominis viri peccaverint.

Emerserunt superiori anno vetustæ latinitatis vindices dicam, an Iu­
dices, nescio, M. Terentius Varro, Verrius Flaccus, Pompeius Fe­
stus, Nonius Marcellus, Isidorus, & Veteres, quoiquoi de proprietate
& differentijs, sermonis scripserunt, Grammatici, prius vel temporum in­
iuria, vel librariorum incuria, mirum in modum mutili ac deformati, nunc
verò multò quàm antea emendatiores, industria Dionysii Gothofredi Iu­
risconsulti, adhibitis etiam in consilium criticis tam superioris seculi, quàm
iis quos hæc ætas magno literarum ornamento, & literatorum emolu­
mente adhuc superstites aluit. Quibus omnibus, & eiusdem Iunij No­
menclatore tertiò iam ædito, pertractatis, & diligentia, quanta potui
maxima, expilatis, magno vocabulorum numero Epitomen hanc immenso
quovis thesauro auctiorem reddidi. Quorum aliqua, satis licet antiqua, &
tanquam obsoleta, aliorum foribus exclusa, in nostrum grègem admisi, quòd
non ignorarem, quantum lucis antiquitatum studiosis, imprimis autem ad
Plauti Comædias, & Accij, Afranij, Ennij, Lucilij, Nævij, Pacuvij,
Titinnij, & aliorum veterum Poetarum reliquias intelligendas, essent al­
latura. Omnia omittere vt religio quædam mihi fuerit, ita etiam aliqua visa
quædam vtenda proponere. Sed bene habet quòd è suis fodinis, tanquam
mortuorum ossa ὰμάρΤυρα prodier noluerim, nec nisi suis authoribus comi­
tatos, in lucem & sanitatem extraxerim.

Idem quoque, in cæteris obnixè cavimus, ne alicui suus author deesset, sed
si quod tale occurreret, stellulâ, quasi ὰδ έσπο Τον notavi. Vnum tamen te la­
tere nolui, ea quibus nullus subycitur alius, Ciceroniana esse omnia: quæ
cùm ex Nizolio & alijs, non sine summo tædio hauserim, ne decies millies
idem nomen appingerem, ὰνΤονομαςιηῶς subticendum existimavi.

Cæterùm Genera, & Nominum tam analogas, quàm anomalas declina­
tiones, Genera item Verborum, & ex Præteritis, Supinis, & Infinitivo,
coniugationes monstravimus.

Singularum quoq, syllabarum, si quando in generales & notissimos ca­
nones non inciderint, quantitates exactiùs, staterâ, vt Varro præscribit,
aurea librantes, vsitatis notulis ob oculos posui.

Sed cùm ista aliorum iudicio deprehendi, quàm nostris verbis prædicari
mialui, longior oratione supersedebo. Si non omnes vocum nebulas alio­
rum scriptis nec nostris expulimus, at certè plurimas vulgò receptas nos
depulisse, & quàm potui paucissimas in nostra admisisse comperies. Quis
verò simul & semel omnia viderit? Argum esse oportuit, quem Plautus &
Apuleius Totum oculeum nominant, qui huic rei solus sufficeret. Sed
quum frustra ab inferis vivum revocet, quem tot retrolapsis sæculis à
Mercurio interfectus (sivera est fabula) poetæ autumant, quid mirum, si
aliquos nævos, quibus tu conniveas, aut quos ipse emacules, reliquerim? Tua­




LECTOREM

rum erit partium (amice lector) operam tibi amicè navatam, æquiboniq
consulere, & tui vultus hilaritate ad alia vel Latina vel Græca, tuis studys
non minùs istis profutara, excitare. Interea Vale, & fruere.

Cantebrigiæ ex nostris ædibus, carptim inter operarum
susurros, Tertio Nonas Septembres, Anno salutis per
Christum Dominum partæ, 1587.




DICTIONARIVM
LINGVAE LATINAE
ET ANGLICAE.


A B

A ET Ab præpositiones
sunt eiusdem significati­
onis, prior longa, poste­
rior breuis. Of, from, euer
since, against, after, with,
on, at, for: by or through: toward: out of:
in comparison of.

A vel ab, iunctum cum certis no­
minibus, ministros significat.

A litera, nora est prenominis, & so­
la, puncto postposito, Aulum significat.

A literam salutarem vocat Cicero,
quòd nota effet absolutionis: quem­
admodum C literam tristem, quòd
nota effet condemnationis.

Ab&abreve;c&emacron;s. Iabol. vasa quædam vilio­
ra, in quibus pretiosiora reponuntur.

Ab&abreve;c&ibreve;on. ij, n. g. dim. ab Abax: i­
dem quod Abaculus. Ammonius.

Ab&amacron;ctor, oris, m.g. verbale ab Abi­
go, Apul. A stealer of cattell or beastes.

Ab&amacron;ctus, us, m.g. Plin. Driuing
awaie by force of stealth.

Ab&abreve;ctus, a, um, Part. ab Abigor.
Caried away by force or by stealth.

Ab&abreve;cus, ci. m.g. A plaine place made
in a building of stone to sit on, as a seate or
bench of marble. also a counting table,
such as Arithmetricians or Astrono­
mers doe vse: a chestboord: a cupboord:
a dresser.

Ab&abreve;c&ubreve;lus, li. m.g. dim. à nomine
Abax. Plin. A littel bench or dresser: a
litle table to cast accomptes on.

Ab&abreve;c&ubreve;li, Counters to cast withall.

Ab&abreve;g&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. Varro. A vete­
ribus dicebatur pro eo quod nos vna
litera innutata, Adagionem dici­
mus. A prouerb.

Ab&abreve;l&ibreve;&emacron;n&amacron;t&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. verb. An ali­
enation, an estrangeing, separation, &c.

Ab&abreve;l&ibreve;&ebreve;n&amacron;tus, a, um. Part. Being e­
stranged, or put awaie.

Ab&abreve;l&ibreve;&emacron;no, as, are. To alienate, to
estrange, to giue ouer to another: to put
or turne away: to withdrawe a mans
minde from him.

Ab&abreve;l&ibreve;&ebreve;nor, aris, are, atus sum. Plau.
To be alienated, estranged, separated.

Abamb&ubreve;lo as, aui, atum, are. Fe­
stus. To walke awaie.

Ab&abreve;m&ibreve;ta, itæ, f.g. Iustinian. The
great grandfathers sister.

Abanec. dictio peregrina. A girdle
which Priestes did weare, so wrought
with colours of scarlet & purple, that
there seemed to be set in it floures and
pretious stones.

Abann&amacron;t&ibreve;o.* A banishment for one
yeare.

Abann&ibreve;ti.* Those that were yearely
banisht for committing murther.

Ab&abreve;phus.* Vndied, vncoloured.

Abaptistum, ti, n.g. Galen. An in­
strument which Chirurgeons vse, called
also Terebra.

Abaptistus, a, um. * That which can­
not be drowned, as Corcke.

Abarc&ebreve;o, es, ui, ere. Fest. To prohi­
bit, or put from a thing.

Ab&abreve;u&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. Iust. The great Grand­
mothers mother.




Ab&abreve;uunc&ubreve;lus, li. m.g. Iust. The
great grandfathers brother.

Ab&abreve;uus, ui. m.g. A great Grand­
father.

Abax, acis, m.g. Digest. Idem est quod
Abacus. Also the case wherein
plate is kept.

Abb&amacron;. A Syrian worde, and signifi­
eth Father.

Abb&amacron;s, tis. * m.g. An Abbot.

Abb&amacron;t&ibreve;a, æ f.g. An Abbey, or the
Abbotship.

Abb&amacron;t&ibreve;a, æ. f.g. Ieron. An Ab­
besse.

Abbr&ebreve;u&ibreve;&amacron;t&umacron;ra, æ. f.g. * An instrument
of a Notarie or Lawier briefly drawne.

Abbr&ebreve;u&ibreve;o, as. Veget. To abbreuiate,
or make short, to abridge.

Abderiticus, a, um. Foolish, dull,
mad.

Abd&ibreve;co, as. To reiect or refuse: to for­
sake: to expell or put out of fauour: to
resigne an office: to prohibite.

Abd&ibreve;c&amacron;t&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. verbale. Liu.
A refusing, a resigning, a forsaking.

Abd&ibreve;c&amacron;tus, a, um. * Forsaken, reie­
cted, cast of.

Abd&imacron;co, cis, xi, ctum. Augurale
est verbum. To refuse, to cast awaie.
Est quoque verbum Iuris, idem
significans quod decreto recusare,
aut litem contra aliquem dare, &
rem alicui abiudicare. Pompon.

Abd&ibreve;t&emacron;, aduerb. Secretly, priuily.

Abd&ibreve;tum, iti. n.g. Horat A secret
or vnknowne place.

Abd&ibreve;tus, a, um. part. ab Abdor,

kept secret.

Abdo, dis, didi, ditum, dere. To
hide, to kepe close.

Abdor, deris, dere, ditus sum, di­
tum, di, pass. Plin. To be hidden.

Abd&omacron;m&ebreve;u, ominis, n. g. The out­
ward and former parte of the belly, which
couereth all the intralles, and is between
the nauell and the priuie members. It
is also taken for the lowest parte of the
swines bellie, and is called Sumen. Plin.
and by a metaphor, for Gula, and for
gluttonie.

Abd&umacron;co, is, xi, ctum. To leade a­
waie, to leade out, to take aside, to pull
away, to withdrawe, to take with.

Abd&umacron;cor, eris, ctus sum, ci. Pass.
To be carried, or ledd awaie, either by
loue, or by force.

Abd&umacron;ctus, a, um, Part. Led or ca­
ried awaie, by loue or by force: remoued.

Abecedarium, ij. n.g. * The order
of the letters, or the crosse row.

Abecedarius, ij. m.g. Cælius. He
that setteth anie thing in order by let­
ter: He that teacheth children their
crosse row, or he that learneth his crosse
row, or A b c.

Ab&ebreve;do, abedis. ex Ab & Edo. Ta­
cit. To gnawe or eate vp all.

Abellina, æ. f.g. Looke Auellana.

Ab&ebreve;mo, ex ab & Emo. Plaut. To

Ab&ebreve;o, is, iui, ij, itum. To goe away,

Ab&ibreve;tus. Plaut.

Ab&ebreve;qu&ibreve;to, as, are. Liu. To ride away.

To forbid.

Ab&ebreve;runco, Loke Auerrunco.

deteyned against right.

Ablabia, æ, f.g. Harmelesnes,

Absinth&ibreve;um, i, n. g. Plin. Worme­

French wormewood: Ponticum or Ro­
manum, which hath a lesse leafe, and
sweeter odour, and may be called worme­
woode gentle.

of a mans throate.

Acanth&ibreve;ce, ces. f.g. p.b. Plin.
A cer­
taine gumme.

Acanth&ibreve;on, siue Acanthium, ij, n.g.
p.b. Plin. A bushe like vnto a white
thorne, with lesse leaues, mossie, and pric­
king: It may be called Otethistle, because
the seeds be like Otes: or Gummethistle,
or Cottonthistle, because it is gumme,
and the leaues haue a thing like cotton.

hogge.

Accendo, dis, di, sum, ex ad &
Cando. To kindle, inflame, set one fire,

Accendor. Passiuum.

Accensus, si, m.g. A Souldior ap­
pointed to be about great officers, for de­
fence of their body: also he that after the
death of a Souldior was put in his place,
or that accompaneth and goeth before
Souldiors that be sick, readie to be mone
of their places: also a Minister ready at
the commandement of the chiefe Officer:
a Sergeant: also a Crier to call men to
assemblies, a Bedell: It may be vsed for
him, that lawiers call Adiunctum.

Accept&ibreve;l&amacron;t&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. Digest.




A quittance of an Obligation made by
mouth: when the debtour demandeth of
the creditour, whether he be content of
that he hath promised him, and he an­
swereth, yea: as though he saide, I doe
accept it as paide.

Acr&emacron;d&ubreve;la, æ, f.g. p.l. A woode larke. 

Acribodicæi. Arist. Lawiers, which
neglecting the equitie of the lawe, doe
stike vnto the verie woords: and that
strict lawe is called Acribodicæum.

Acr&ibreve;fol&ibreve;um. n.g, p.l. vide Lotos.

and wit.

Acr&obreve;&amacron;ma, atos, n. g. p.g. A subtile

also the person that playeth, and by his
gesture delighteth the eie.

Acr&obreve;c&obreve;mus. One hauing long haire.

Acrocorium. Plin. Bulbi species.

fruites hauing hard rindes or shales: as

Acronyctæ. Cæl Rod. Stars that a­
rise in the night time, at the Sun falling.

Acropolis.* A tower placed in some
high place aboue the towne.

Acrostichis, dis. f.g. When the
first letters of diuers verses doe make a

Acrostolia, orum. Baysius. Cer­
taine garnishing of ships, which may ea­
sily be taken awaie.

Acroteria, orum, Bitru The extreme
partes of mans bodie. also Images &
pinacles set on buttresses: also the stemme
& decking of ships.

Acrothinia.* Primitiæ frugum,
quæ de summo aceruo solent tolli.

Acrothorax. *One halfe drunke.

cator.

Aggemo, vide Adgemo.

Agger, ris, m.g. A heape of stones
or turffes. a bulwarke: a countermure
to a fortres or campe: a rampire: a trench:
also a causey, or the high parte of the
waie like a causey: a banke to keep in
the water of Riuers: a wqater banke: a
sewal: a damme: sometime a ditch Also
a blockhouse. Sometime it is taken for the
matter, whereof it is made.

Agg&ebreve;ro, as, Colum. To heape: to
cast vp in a heape: to augment, to ag­
grauate.

Agg&ebreve;ra, is, ex Ad & Gero,Virg.
To lay on a heape: to bring to one. to beare
or carie.

An heape.

Agigardon.* A kinde of grape
without kernels.

Agnascor, eris, ex Ad & Nascor.
To be borne nigh by, or vnto that which

those that are borne after the wil is made
and the goods parted: or which one adop­
teth afterward for his sonne or daughter.

ficed, and prouerbiallie, they which
long consult, and yet doe nothing.

Agrestis, &  hoc agreste. p.b.
Wilde: ground without culture: that
which groweth in fields, and not in gar­
dens. Vngentle, rude, rusticall, clow­
nish, without nurture or ciuilitie, feirce,
in whome is neither loue nor humilitie.

Agrestis, substant. An vplandish
man, one of the countrie.

Agriaræ, f.g. Celsus. A kinde of
scabs, which breaketh out at certaine
times of the yeare, and is verie harde to
heale. Also an incurable sore.

Agricantha, æ, f.g. Diosc. A

A H

Ah, An interiection of sorowing,
or pitying, applied also to other affecti­
ons, as indignation, desire, rebuking,
correcting himselfe, wondring, dehor­
ting, reprehending an other mans word
& fact, chiding, denying, withstanding
or gainsaying.

Ah, ah, Plaut. An interiection of
sighing, when we sigh: as, ough, hoe.

Aha, interiectio, Plaut. A voice
when we be angrie with some bodie, and
blame him: etiam abnegantis. Plaut
Tush, noe.

Ahnen&ebreve;us, a, um. ab Aes, vnde
Aeneus, & Aheneus. Virg. Brasen,
of brasse or of copper, by a metaphor,
strong, hard.

Ah&emacron;na, p.b. * Vessels or caudrons
of hard mettall, at copper, or iron.

Ah&emacron;nus, a, um, p.b. idem quod 
aheneus, Horat. Made of brasse, or
copper.

Ah&emacron;nus, ni, n.g. Gell. A cau­
dron, or anie brasen vessell, wherein wa­
ter is made hotte to wash with, a great
vatte wherein purple is died.

Ahorta.* One of the principall
veines.

Ahertæ, arum. * Two veines grow­
ing from the nauill to the matrice, be­
neath the kidnies.

Ahu, interiectio, Terent. When a
man or woman is troubled with feare, or
otherwise.



A I

Aigl&emacron;uc&emacron;s. Plin. A kinde of wine
which alwaies seemeth to be new and
fresh.

Ain, pro Aisne. Savest thou?

Aio, ais, it, plu. aiunt. verbum defe­
ctiuum. To say: to affirme.

Aiens, aientis, part.*

Ajuga, vel Abiga. Plin. Herba que
camæpytos dicitur.

A&imacron;z&omacron;&obreve;n, aizoi, n.g. p.l. Plin. An
hearb which is alwaies quick & greene,
called Singreene or Housheke: whereof
there be two kindes, Aizoon maius,
Singreene. Aizoon minus, Vermi­
cularis, & Cauda, Muris, vulgò di­
citur Prickmadam. Some note the




third to be wild purslane.


A L

Ala, æ, f.g. p.l. The wing of a Bird,
or of anie other thing that flyeth: the
pinion or shoulder of a beast or foule.

Ala in homine, Plin. The nose: bril:
the arme-pit, or arme-hole. Alarum
caua in herbis, Plin. The hollownesse
betweene the bottome of the leafe and
the stalke. Alæ in exercitu. The wings
of an armie. Alæ in ædificirs, Vitru.
Walles erected in the sides of an edifice
like wings. Alæ navium, the sailes:
alæ sagittæ: The feathers.

Al&abreve;band&ibreve;ca. p.b. Plin. A rose with
whitish leaues, like a damaske rose.

with blewe, prouoking to bleede.

rule ouer salt.

Ala­
baster: a certaine kinde of hard marble,

birde that layeth her egges on the Sea
sandes. When she laieth, be the Sea ne­
uer so troublous, it becommeth calme so­
denlie, vntill the young be hatched and
brought vp, which is the space of 14.
daies, wherein the mariners feare no
storme. Shee is little bigger then a spar­
rowe: hir feathers of colour purple mixt
with white: hir neck long and small: hir
bill greene, long and slender. It is taken
for that we call the Kings fisher: but
that is not the right Alcedo.

Alc&emacron;d&omacron;n&ibreve;a, orum. plur. n.g. Plau.
Times of quietnesse, without trouble on
the Sea.

Alce, ces, or Alces, is, f.g.
Plin. A wilde beast in fashion & skinne like
a fallowe Deere, but greater, and hath
no ioynts in the Legges, and therefore
doth neuer lie, but leane to trees. It is
also the name of a dogge. Xenoph. Est
item animal Galliæ transalpinæ, fi­
gura, celore, & magnitudine mulæ
similitudinem prætendens, sed labi­
um superius adeo protensum habet,
vt nisi retrograde incedens, herbas
in terra carpere non possit. Plin.

Alchech, Arabicè, idem quod
Lynca: nascitur ex leone & pardo.

Alchymia, Firm. Alchimie. & Al­
chimista, qui eam artem exercet.

Alc&ibreve;b&ibreve;&abreve;d&ibreve;on, ii, n.g. Diosc. An
hearbe supposed to be a kinde of Bur­
rage.

Alcibion, Plin. Herba aduersus
serpentum morsus remed&imacron;um ha­
bens.

Alcida, æ, Diodo. Fera immensæ
magnitudinis, ignem ore vomens,
quo regiones omnes per quas faci­
ebatiter excussit.

lux.  Dogges gotten betweene a woulfe

Alopex marina.*  A sea fish, which

teth off the line about the tackling, and
to scapeth.

which maie not otherwise labour.

A M

Am, præpositio antiqua, Cato. A­
bout. In compositione freqqens est,
& composita cum dictione incipien­
te ab a, e, i, u, interponitur b, eu­
phoniæ causa: si verò cum c, h, f, q,
mutatur m in n: cum p, remanet in­
tegra.

Ama, æ, f.g. p.b. Vlp. A Sythe, or
a weeding hooke: also a night birde, as
the shrikehowle, or the batte: also a
wine vessel.

Am&amacron;b&ibreve;lis & hoc amabile, p.b. A­
miable: worthie to be beloued: that ma­
keth one loue it.

Am&amacron;b&ibreve;l&ibreve;or, amabilissimus. p.b.
More amiable, &c.

Am&amacron;b&ibreve;l&ibreve;t&amacron;s, atis, f.g. p.b. Plaut.
Amiablenesse, louelinesse.

Am&amacron;b&ibreve;l&ibreve;ter, aduerb. p.b. Horat.
Louely, amiably,

Am&amacron;bo, interiectio blandientis
& amantis, p.b. Terent. Of fellow­
ship: of all loue: I praie the as euer thou
wilt doe me good turne.

ro vocat Attici Bibliothecam, prop­
ter variam & magnam librorum bo­
norum copiam: & Amaltheæ cornu,
idem quod copiæ cornu. Philostr.

Herba est spicam veriùs habens,

nunquam marcescit. Hereof there be
two sortes, the one with a yellow flower,
called Maudlin, wort or Baltase: the
other with a purple flower like an eare,
called Flowregentle.

Amb&ibreve;o, is, iui, ex Am & Eo, inter­

Amb&ibreve;t&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. verb. A cir­
cuite or compassing: earnest and impor­
tune, desire of honour, ambition, seeking
for the fauour of men, importune or ear­
nest request, suite or labour: an immo­
derate desire of honour, &c.

Amb&ibreve;t&ibreve;&omacron;sus, a, um, Ambitious, ve­
rie desirous of honour, that seeketh ouer
much to haue the fauour of men: of too
great ostentation and crake: that hath a
great compasse & circuite: feyned, with
a faire shewe and small effect: gorgeous,
sumptuous, cunning, made by suite and
fauour, guien by fauour, superfluous,
and seruing onelie for a shewe, affectu­
all. Dicitur etiam ambitiosus, qui
habitu, sermone, vultu, denique mo­
dis omnibus misericordiam captat,
Quint.

Amb&ibreve;t&ibreve;&omacron;s&emacron; ambitiousiùs, aduerb.
Proudelie, without much labour, verie
curiouslie, warelie, of ostentation: by
pursuite or purchase, with affectation.

Amb&ibreve;t&ibreve;&omacron;siss&ubreve;mè, aduerb.
Quint.

by ambition doth aspire to, &c.

tus ex colis constans.

Am&ebreve;thystus, sti, m,g.g. p.b. Plin.

which is made, or is of the colour of an

violamexit.

pretious stone.

Ampel&imacron;tis,* A kinde of tough earth,
like Bitumen, growing about Seleucia
in Syria, wherewith husbandmen doe a­
noint the vines, to kill the wormes. It
is also called Pharmacitis. Diosc.

Ampelodesmos, Plin. An hearb in
Sicilie, wherewith they make bandes to
tie vines.

Ampeloprason, Plin. An hearbe
commonlie called the Leeke of vines.

some for Brionia: an hearb called the

which Phisitians call the exquisite quar­

Amplector, eris, xus sum. To em­

Amplexus, a, um, part. ab Ample­

Amplexus, us, verb. ab Amplector.
Embracing: clipping.

A N

An, aduerb. interrogantis, & ali­
quando dubitantis. Whether? yea or
no? or, or else, either, if.

Anne,  idem quod An, An & Ne,
interpositis aliquot dictionibus. Cic.
An partus ancillæ, sitne, & c.

Ana, A barbarous worde vsed of Phi­
sitians for singulorum partes, also a
beast in the East part.

An&abreve;b&abreve;sis, p.b. Plin. An hearb cal­
led Horsetaile.

An&abreve;b&abreve;s&ibreve;us, p.b. Ierom. He that ri­
deth by post horses.

An&abreve;b&amacron;thrum, ri, n.g. p.b. Iuuen.
A pulpit or other like place, wherevnto
a man ascendeth by ladders or grieses.

An&abreve;b&obreve;l&abreve;g&ibreve;um, vel anab&omacron;ldium, *
A vesture that couereth the shoulders:
it maie be vsed for a womans raile.

Amabula, æ, Plin. A beast hauing
a head like a Camell, a neck like a horse,
and thighes like an Oxe.

Anacacabea, Ruell. An hearb cal­
led Lotus.

Anacacabos, Aetius. The fruite of
the hearb Lotus.

Anacampseros, otis, f.g. Plin. An
hearb, the touching whereof restoreth
loue betweene man and man.

Anacardium, Ruell. A tree in In­
dia, the fruit whereof is like the heart of
a litle birde, and hath a iuyce redde like
blood, out of the fruite whereof procee­
deth honie that exulcerateth.

An&abreve;c&ebreve;ph&abreve;læ&omacron;sis, p.l. Quint. A
briefe rehearsall, a recapitulation.

Anach&imacron;tes, Plin. A stone whole­
some against poyson, and driuing away
mad fantasies: the Diamond.

An&abreve;ch&omacron;r&emacron;sis, p.b. Cassian. A soli­
tarie place: an Hermitage.

An&abreve;ch&obreve;r&emacron;ta, æ, m.g. p.b. Cassia.
An Heremite, or Ankeresse.

An&abreve;cl&emacron;sis, p.b. * A reuerberation:
a calling back.

An&abreve;clint&emacron;r&ibreve;um, ij, n.g. p.b. Lamp.
A mattresse: a flocke-bed. vocantur
huiuimodi lecti, accubita, Stibadia,
& brabate.

Anacollia, A&emacron;t. Those things, the
gumme whereof is medecinable against
corrupt heares.

An&abreve;c&obreve;l&umacron;thos, p.b. * A vse in wri­
ting, when the wordes answere not one
to another.

Anacrisis, Bud. Examination of a
matter: question of the guiltie, whether
it be by torments, or otherwise: the exa­
mining of witnesses.

Anactorion, Diosc. An hearb cal­
led Gladiolus.

An&abreve;d&emacron;ma, atis, n.g. p.b. Lucret.
A garlande, or like ornament of the
head.

Anadendrades,* Vines that are
steyed vp with trees.

plaister made of the leaues of marsh ma­
lowes, called Althæa.

Anadendron, idem quod 
Athæa.

An&abreve;d&imacron;pl&omacron;sis,* Doubling of wordes.

Anadyomene, Plin. Rising or ap­
pearing out.

Anagallis, idis, Plin. An hearb
called Pimpernell: some take it for chick­
weede: the male beareth a redde flower,
the female a blue.

Anagallis aquatica,* called also
Sion, or Lauer: Brookelime.

Anaglyphum. n.g. p. & t.b. Vessell
or plate chaced and wrought with ham­
mer, not graued.

grauer.

An&amacron;gn&omacron;st&emacron;s, æ. m.g. p.b. One that
readeth while another writeth: a clarke.

Anagoge, es. f.g. * The high vnd
subtile vnderstanding of the Scrip­
tures.

Anagraphe, es, f.g. * A Regi­
stri of ng actes: it is also a commentarie,
or breefe of sessement. Vlpian calleth it
an inuentorie or repertorie.

Anagytis, Ruell. An hearb verie
faire to see to, but hauing a stincking sa­
uour.

An&abreve;lecta, orum, n.g. p.b. Mart.
Fragments of meate: crummes, and all
such thinges as fall from the table, and
are swept awaie.

An&abreve;lectes, æ, m.g. p.b. Sen. He
that sweepeth fragments together.

Analectice, es, f.g. * A forme of
diet to nourish him that is lately reco­
uered.

An&abreve;lectis, idis, f.g. p.b. Ouid. A
litle cushion: a stuffing or farcing that
women vse in their garments when one
shoulder is higher then another, lest it
appeare that they be crooked.

Analemma, atis, n.g. p.b. Vitru.
An instrument by the which is founde
the course and eleuation of the Sunne,
and other like matters.

Analesia, f.g. * A sicknes of the
head taking awaie sensiblenes from all
partes of the head.

An&abreve;l&obreve;g&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. p.b. Conueni­
ence, proportion, likenes.

An&abreve;l&obreve;gismus, à dialecticis voca­
tur firmissimum illud argumenti ge­
nus, quod à causa propinque duci­
tur.

Analogos.* Answering in propor­
tion.

Analphab&emacron;ti, Fulgent. They which
haue not learned the crosse rowe.

Analogistæ,* Tutors that are not
bound to make accounts towardes.

Analysis, ios, f.g. * Resolution.

Analyticum, i, n.g. * That which
resolueth.

Ananchitis, idis, Plin. A kinde of
pretious stone.

Anantopodoton,* Schema est,
quum scilicet oratio membro ali­
quo destituitur.

An&abreve;pæstus, sti, m.g. p.b. A foote or
measure in verse or prose consisting of
two short syllables and one long.

Anapæstus versus etiam dicitur,
& Anapæstum, n.g. A certaine kinde
of verse made of such feete or measures,
or of others in steede and place of the
same.

An&abreve;pæst&ibreve;cus, a, um. p.b. Made of
such feete.

An&abreve;ph&obreve;ra, æ. f.g. p.b. Firmic. An
ascension of the planets from the East
by dailie course of the firmament. Also
a figure called, Repetition.

Anarchia, æ, f. * When the people is
without a Prince: lacke of gouernment
or rule.

Anarchus, Amb. Without a Prince,
without beginning.

Anarrinon, quod & Antirrhinum,
Plin. Herba est amagallidi similis,
radice nulla aut perexigua, semine
vitulinas nares imitante. Galenus
Buchranion appellat.

Anas, &abreve;tis, f.g. p.b. A Ducke, or

or rotting of a vaine.

Anastr&obreve;ph&emacron;, es, f.g. p.b. Quint.
A figure of speech, when one worde is
put disorderlie before another.

uing of vsurie yearelie, when at the

pall, and taketh vsurie of the same next
yeare.

Anceps, ipitis, adiect. Doubtfull:
vncertaine: sometime double, also two
edged, or cutting on both sides: that hath
a handle on both sides, or two heades or
faces, daungerous.

Ancetum,* The wilde Cucumber.

Anchilops,* Superfluous flesh in
the great corner of the eye, wherevnto

Anchinum mel,* Honie made of
flowers onelie gathered in the Spring
time.

Anch&obreve;ra, æ, f.g. An anchor: also

Pertaining to the anchor.

Anchurisma, tis, n.g. The taking
awaie of windie matter dissolued.

Anch&umacron;sa, æ, f.g. Plin. An hearb

Anchyle,* An incision of the cordes
of the neck or ioynts, whereby the vse of

Ancile, is, n.g. A short scutchion
or shielde: a buckler.

or bondwoman.

Anchurisma, atis, n.g. * The taking
awaie of a windie matter dissolued.

Anclabra, or Antlabra,* Vessels
that Priests vsed in their sacrifice.

Anclabris,* A table vsed in sacri­
fice.

Ancon, &omacron;nis, m.g. * An elbow. Fuit
eriam Aucon apud Carthaginenses
obscurum domicilium, in quod de­

rannus.

Ancones in parietibus, Vitru. The
coynes or corners of a wall: also the bow­
ing that maketh the corner Angulus
rectus: also a certaine vessell a cubite
highe.

Anc&omacron;nisci,* Instruments vsed in
torture: also certaine coines or corners
standing out to beare a beame or rafter.

Anct&emacron;res, Cels. The partes of the
necke, where men be soonest choaked: al­
so bandes wherewith the vppermoste
part of the wound is tyed, that the scarre
may be the lesse.

Bud. To torment and vexe oftentimes.
Looke Ango.

Tormented, vexed.

arme.

The disease called, tongue tied, speech­

pretious stone hard and ponderous, bright
like siluer, and in forme of diuers litle

Androsæmon, ni, n.g. Plin. The

Androsaces, es, f.g. Plin. An hearb

Ang&abreve;rus, ri, m.g. A Poste or Car­

Ang&imacron;na, æ, f. Plin. A disease in the

Ang&ibreve;portus, us, vel Angiportus,
ti, m.g. &  Angiportum, n.g. A great
hole in the earth with manie turninges,
or that which hath no way out: also a
lane in a towne: a narrowe streete with
manie windinges, or that which lyeth on
a hauen, whereby marchandise is caried
to the water or recaried.

Ango, is, xi, sine supino vsitato. To throttle or strangle: to torment, vexe,
or trouble with care: to grieue as well
the bodie as the minde.

Angust&amacron;tus, a, um. Made straight

Angust&emacron;, Angustiùs. aduerb.

Angust&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. siue potiùs An­
gust&ibreve;æ, angustiarium. Narrowesse:
streights or narrowe places that maie
scantlie be passed through: shortnesse or
breuitie: distresse, perplexitie, or an­
guish: trouble and griefe of minde: scar­
citie: aduersitie or troublous state. Base­
nesse, not able to compasse or atchiue any
great enterprise.

declare a message: to shewe: to bring

Ann&ubreve;o, is, ex Ad & Nuo. To nodde
with the head: to affirme or promise: to
agree: with a becke to will one to doe a
thing: to assent or graunt: to signifie or
make semblance: to fauour, or further.

Appello.

Apepsia,* Ventriculi vitium est,
quod latini cruditatem appellant:
quuin scilicet cibi in ventribulo non
immutantur, sed tales ferè egerun­
tur, quales suntingressi.

Ardens, ntis, part. vel nomen ex
part. Hotte, burning: vehement: hastie
in doing: quicke: wittie, swifte: angrie,
earnest, greate, excellent, liuelie, shi­
ning, glistering.

Ard&ebreve;o, es, si, sum. To burne: to be on
a fire: to shine or glister: to be verie a­
ctiue, to be verie earnest and hot, to doe
a thing, to desire much or feruentlie: to
loue greatlie and impatientlie, to be in­
flamed and kindled: to rage, to be an­
grie, to hasten. To be rauished with loue:
to be greatlie troubled, or tormented: to
be guiltie or defamed.

Ardentia signa, Starres.

Ardenter, Ardentiùs, aduerb. Ve­
hementlie: hotlie: feruentlie: earnestly.

Ardent&ibreve;or. More vehement.

or glistering redde colour.

hastie and fierce: to be kindled and set
on fire: to be verie sharpe.

nest desire, exceeding loue: light or
brightnes, loue.

An hearb verie like wilde poppie, so cal­

disease in the eie, called Argema.

Arg&umacron;ment&amacron;t&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. verbal.

Arg&umacron;mentor, aris. To argue, reason,

Arg&umacron;ment&omacron;sus, a, um, Quint. Con­
teining high and great matters: that
is done with great aduise, witte, and
skil.

Arg&umacron;mentum, ti, n.g. A reason, a
proofe, or a reason to proue: an argument,
a matter to speak or write of, the sunime
of a matter written: or the argument
and effect of an oration: a coniecture,
presumption, cause, iust occasion, or sure
token: sometime it is taken for a cunning
deuise, workemanship, or historie.

Arg&ubreve;o, is, &ubreve;i, &umacron;tum. To reprooue: to

prohibite.

Arg&umacron;tus, a, um, tior, tissimus, adiect.
Subtile, wittie, that can sharpelie search

tatling curious: Shrill of voice or sounde,
making a great noise. also leane, slender,
small, picked, sharpe like a suger loafe.

Art&ibreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;t&emacron;, & Articulatim, aduer.
From ioynt to ioynt, or by the ioyntes,
ioyntmeale, in small peeces and morsells,
from poynt to poynt: distinctlie, treate­
ablie.

Item Articulus membrum est peri­
odi: & à grammaticis dicitur parti­
cula quæ in declinandis nominibus,
discernendi generis causa, præpo­
nitur.

nance, to set a good face on a matter: also

ther: to forge or counterfeite, to drawe

A T

At, particula principiis apta, præ­
sertim cùm aut indignationem, aut
dolorem exprimere volumus. quan­
doque rerum differentiam denotat
quando; est aduersatiuum, quan­
doque ponitur pro saltem. But, at
the least wise, yet, or, neuerthelesse. At,
pro At vero. But truly.

At enim. But.

At etiam, Indignantis. why?

Atat. interiectio, ex improuiso
aliquid deprenendentis, admirantis,
contetriti conturbatìque, paulatim
percepti atque intellecti mali, for­
midantis. Terent. Aha. Ah ha.

fathers father.

Igno­
rance, vnskilfulnes, lack of cunning.

Atque, coniunctio connexiua &
quandoque adverb. Terent. And: &
also, and yet, and that, but, that, as,
euen as, as it were, as though, then, and.
euen togither, foorthwith, and indeede,
after that.

Atque adeo. Yea, and that, rather,
and indeede.

Atque equidem. Terent. Notwith­
standing.

Atque etiam. And that more is.

Atqueita, Terent. And so, but on
this condition.

Atque verò. But.

Atque, si gemina fiat, auget, in­
tenditque rem. de qua agitur.

Atqui, coniunctio discretina. But,
but yet, yea but, albeit, surelie, neuer­
thelesse.

Atquisi. But surelie if.

Attendo, is, di, ex Ad & Tendo.

Attentus, tior, tissimus, part. ab
Attendo, vel nomen ex part. Atten­
tiue, diligent, fixed on a thing: earnestlie
bent to beare: giuing good eare. Some­
time couetous, bent to profitte: carefull to
get, wise, considerate, diligent about his
affaires.

Axare. Fest. To name or aske.

Axies* A companie of women doing

Axim, pro Egerim. Pacuv.

Ax&ibreve;&omacron;ma, atis n.g. Authoritie or ho­
nor by reason of an office, or any notable

grounde or rule of anie arte: a perfect
oration, which sheweth a thing to be
true or false.

Axionomantia, æ, f.g. Plin. A kinde
of diuination or witchcraft done by hat­
chers.

Axis, is, m.g. An extree of a carte,
the woode whereabout the wheeles doe
turne: the diameter of the world, that is,
an imagined line that reacheth from one
pole to another, the pole Artike, or ant­
artike: sometime heauen: also a hooke of a
dore or gate: the pole North or South. a
carte or wagon, the table wherein Solons
lawes were written: in plur. a wilde
beast in India. Axes, etiam pro Asse­
ribus. Gell. Shingle.

Ax&ibreve;t&ibreve;&omacron;si, Fest. Companions, when ma­
nie men doe anie thing togither.

Axona,* A thing in the ioynt of the
neck which moueth not, but is stil like an
Axeltree.

Axungia, æ, f.g. ab Axis, & Vngo.
Plin. Swines grease, bacons grease.

Bacch&amacron;nal, vel Bacchanale, lis, &
Bacch&amacron;n&amacron;lia, um, & orum, n.g. plur.
num. The place where Bacchus feastes
were kepte: sometime the feast: also the
dates wheron they solemnized Bacchus
feasts in riotte, dronkennes, & lecherie.

Plin. An hearb called our Ladies gloues.

button, and the Apothecaries Marru­

Bacch&amacron;tim, aduerb. Apul. Dron­
kenlie, like a madde man.

Bacch&amacron;tio, onis, verb. à Bacchor.
Drunken, banketting, drunkennes, the
deede of a drunken man.




Bacch&amacron;tus, a, um, Virgil. Raging,
running like a mad bodie. Legitur &
bacchatus in passiua significatione,
pro eo quod est à bacchantibus fre­
quentatus aur peragratus. Virg.

Bacchor, aris, depon. To keepe Bac­
chus feastes: to liue in sensualitie and ri­
otte, to liue dissolutelie and drunkenlie,
to keepe the countenance, and doe the
feates and deedes of a drunken man, as
to runne madlie, to beate, to smite, to
plaie the deuill: to rage like a mad man,
to be moode angrie, to bluster tempestu­
ouslie. also to be inspired with a furie &
to foretell things co come.

Bacch&emacron;is, idos, adiect. f.g. Stat.
Middle, furious, belonging to the filthie
feastes, and vnchast reuels of Bacchus.

um. possessiv. à Baccho, per tres syl­
labas, Virgil. Pertaining to Bacchus.

tion or banishment, that whosoeuer fin­

ti dicebantur, qui carebant iure to­
ge quib. aqua & igne interdictum erat.

speach.

loquence: vnciuill: in old time all sauing
Greekes were called Barbari.

B&ebreve;n&ebreve;f&ibreve;cent&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. Liberalitie: lar­

waie.

B&ebreve;n&ebreve;f&ibreve;c&ibreve;&amacron;r&ibreve;us, rij, m.g. Plin. Iun.
He that receiueth a good turne of ano­
ther: he that is not charged with watch
and warde, and other labours of the field
in warre: that hath the benefite of an of­
fice without charge of doing that apper­
taineth to it: also a vassaile, a Tenant
that holdeth by faith and homage & be­
neficiarius fundus. Land giuen by fee
simple or fee tayle, to be holden fo the do­
noure by some seruice.

B&ebreve;n&ebreve;fic&ibreve;um, cii, n.g. A benefit, a
pleasure, healpe, a good turne, fauour,
grace, kindnesse.

Beneficium in iure ciuili, pro iure
quodam præcipuo alicui concesso,
quod & Priuilegium dicitur.

Berbena, idem quod Verbena.

Berberion, vel Berberi, Barbal.
A shell fish, wherein pearles do breede.

like a triangle, at the taile of a Lyon.

Bes, bessis, siue  Bessis, is, m.g. A
weight of eight ounces: two partes. Vsu­
ra ex besse. of eight: in the hundred. al­
so a geometricall measure, conteining
eight parts of an acre deuided in twelue.

Besasa, æ, f.g. * The seede of Rue.

or inches.

Best&ibreve;&obreve;la, æ, f.g. dim. A litle beast.

B&emacron;ta, æ, f.g. Beete. Betæ quoque à

molles & cinædi. Vnde & Bætizare

minari. Cæl.

Beticus color. vide Bæticus.

ito.

Betonomantia, æ, f.g. vide Boto­

Bet&obreve;n&ibreve;ca, æ, f.g. Plin. An hearb
called Betonie. Est & altera Betonicæ
species, teste Aegineta, herba vni­
caulis, ramulos habens pulegij, sed
tenuiotes & gustu fatuos, quæ à su­
periore specie differt, non effectu. Est
& alia species, vetonica coronaria,
seu vetonicum altile, vulgo Florea
tunici, aut garyophilli. Ruell.

ble: beneuolent: peaceable, liberall: great,
easie to speake too: treateable: apt or fit:
sometime cunning, learned, skilfull, not
vile or base, not counterfeyted or subor­
ned: florishing, strong and lustie, well
in reparations: profitable: thriftie.

B&obreve;o, as, Plaut. To lowe or belowe
like a cowe: to roare like an Oxe or Bull.

B&obreve;o, is, ire, Var. Idem.

Boos,* A serpent liuing by the milke
of rudder beastes.

certaine starre in heauen following
Charles waine.

Bosmorus. Strab. Frumenti reli­
giosi genus est tritico minus, apud

quodexcusum protinus torretur iu­
ramentoque adiguntur messores,
non asportaturos priusquam coepe­
rant, ne semen in alias terras trans­

casus appetentiæ, ex frigiditate ex­

Bupodes,* Great feete.

Buprestis, is, f.g. Plin. A flie like

if he eate him. it is also the name of an
hearb.

meth to be a carpe.

Cadmia, æ, f.g. Galen. Corpus
est metallicum, cuius duo sunt gene­
ra: alterum, quod in riuis & monti­
bus reperitur earum regionum, in

lapidosa vocatur: alterum. quod in
æraijs officinis reperitur, &c.

Cadm&imacron;tes.* A stone hauing blewe

C&abreve;do, is, c&ebreve;c&ibreve;di, c&amacron;sum, dere. To
fall, to slide, to fall grieuouslie or to fall
downe headlong, to die, to be slaine: to be
sacrificed, to happen, to chaunce, to be­
long or agree with: to sincke in, to be cut
downe, to decaie, to perish: to end or fi­
nish: to fall or go downe, as starres doe:
to loose, to faile, to returne, to runne, to
powre downe, to be laide or assuaged, to
wax long, not to be liked, not to declare
in due forme, to be in vse, to fall or ende,
to be deriued.

Caduarij,* Men hauing the falling
sicknes.

rodde.

C&abreve;d&umacron;c&ibreve;ter. Aduerb, Non. Rashly:

C&abreve;d&umacron;cus, a, um. Fraile: brickle:
mooueable, mortall, corruptible, ruinous,
fallen, like to fall, decaie, or perish: some­
time dead, or deceased: that is not able to
beare vp it selfe. Caduca hæreditas, &
caduca bona, fallen in exchete for lack
of an heire. Caduca auspicia, quum
aliquid in templo excidit, veluti de
manu Virgæ. Caducæ literæ quæ ob­
scuriores sunt, & visum propemo­
dum fugiunt. & Morbus caducus,
The falling euill.

Cancelli, orum, m. g. Lattises, se­
cret places to looke out at, windowes
made with crosse barrs of timber or iron:

pro Cancellarium esse.

Cancello, as, Colum. To make in

cundæ semen est: Also a pill in medi­

ratio quedam perficiendi, vt culices
è grossis enati ad ficus aduolent, hu­
moreque earum lacteo consumpto,
ad maturitatem eas perducant. Id
autem solet fieri duobus modis: aut
enim circum ficeta ita solebant dis­
poni caprifici, vt ventorum flatu
culices è grossis enati ad ficus ferr&emacron;­
tur, aut grossi aliunde petitæ, & col­
ligatæ in arborem inijciebantur

Capr&ibreve;f&ibreve;co, as, &  Capr&ibreve;f&ibreve;cor, De­
pon, Pli. Ficuum proprium est, quum
culices ex caprifici fructu (quas
Grossos appellant) ad ipsas aduo­
lantes lacteum humorem in eis
contentum absumunt, easq; ad ma­
turitatem perducunt.

Capt&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb à Capto.

Capto, as, Frequent. à Capio, &
propriè est, illecebris, donis, obse­
quio, & maiorum spe aliquid aucu­
pari. To go about or endeauour to take,

Causa, æ, f.g. A cause, a beginning,
a controuersie in sute: a matter to be spo­

in ones affaires: an excuse: a reason: a

full cause: a souldier that hath his passe­
port, or is essoined.

Caus&amacron;r&ibreve;us, a, um, Liv. that is es­

cause. Causarij milites, Souldiers for
sicknes, or other reasonable causes di­
missed out of the armie. Causarij, me­
taphoricè, Plin. Sick or maymed, that
they cannot get their liuing.

Causateus, a, um, * That is cause
of the doing of a thing.

power and vertue to burne.

burned, or that maie be burned.

Caut&emacron;, adverb. Wiselie, circumspe­
ctlie, subtillie, warilie, aduisedlie, well.

Caut&emacron;la, æ, f.g. Digest. A prouision,

to cautell.

selfe or an other be not deceiued.

Cautus a, um. Prouidence, circum­

C E

Ce.* It is a syllable added vnto words
and it is ioyned vnto such wordes as doe
end in C. or S. as Hicce, Hisce, &c.

C&emacron;c&ubreve;bum, bi, n.g. Mart. A kinde
of wine profitable to the digestion of
meate.

C&emacron;dens, ntis, part. à Cedo, Virg.
Giuing place: chaunged, decayed or lost,
falling.

C&emacron;do, is, ssi, ssum. To giue place, to
depart, to leaue, to yeelde, to goe, retyre,
or giue backe: to goe or passe awaie, to
voide, to withdraw: to parte from, or to
giue ouer: to renounce, to haue the worse,
not to be able to, or to be behinde in, &c.
to obey, to graunt, to giue, to succeede,
to stand in staede of, to agree to one in
what he will: to happen, chaunce, or fall
out or vpon: to be ouercome with: to goe.
Cedere dicitur dies, when the daie of
paiment draweth nie.

C&emacron;d&ibreve;tur, Impers. They be inferiour,
or giue place.

C&ebreve;do, verb. defect. plu. cedite, &
cette pro cedite. Nev. Say, giue, tell,
or shew: appoint, let him come, &c.

C&ebreve;lebro, as, To frequent, to haunt,

Cens&ebreve;o, es, &ubreve;i, &emacron;re, To suppose: to

uill law might be bought and solde.

Census, a, um, Deliuered by denum­

Census, us, m.g. verb. à Censeo,




 It is when the Romanes did bring their
number before the Censours: the riches,
substance, or reuenues of some man:
yearely reuenues, goods, or substance: al­
so the valuation of goods, a subsidie, a
ceassing, mustering, or valuing of the
people.

Centaur&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. siue Centauri­

Cento, &omacron;nis, m.g. Cæs. A fashion
of rough and hearie couering or garment
made of sundrie woll, or peeces, which
poore men vsed, and wherwith tentes
were couered when it rayned: any thing
made with sundrie peeces of cloath and
diuers coloures: of some it is taken for a
quilte, or iack stuffed with linnen, flax,
or cotten: also a worke compiled of di­
uerse fragmenes of verses gathered out
of Authors.

Centonalis, Diosc. Ruta sylvestris.

Centr&amacron;lis, le, Plin. Of the centre:

middest of anie round thing: the cen­

peice of timber or stone, which marreth
the saw of the Carpenter, or the hammer
of the Mason. Est item Centron chry­
stalli quoddam vitium, durum &
fragile, quod & salem appellant. Plin.

An hundred: sometime it is taken in­
definitelie for manie.

Cent&ubreve;r&ibreve;&amacron;tus, a, um, part. à Cen­

Centuriatæ leges, Lawes made by the

of noble men: sometime bookes, letters,
tables.

Cerno, is, cr&emacron;vi, cr&emacron;tum, cernere,
To see, to perceiue, to know, to striue, &
contend for something, to crible, to sifte,
to fight and strike battaile, to seuer or se­
perate, to iudge or determine, to trie out,
to range flowre of corne, to deuise togi­
ther, to enter vpon, or to possesse, to loose.

Cert&amacron;m&ebreve;n, &ibreve;nis, n.g. A conflict, a
bickering, contention or variance, de­
bate, fight, warre, strife, the price wher­
of men doe striue, who shall get it, a
game, or exercise, where one endeuoreth




to passe another, triall, businesse, tumult,
labour and paines.

Cert&amacron;tim, adverb. Enuyingone an
other who shall winne, or get it from the
other: in contending and striuing who
may doe best.

Cert&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. à Certo.
Debate, strife, studie, contention, ende­
uour.

Cert&amacron;tur, Impers. There is contenti­
on, or diuersitie in, &c.

Cert&amacron;tus, us, m.g. verb. Idem quod
Certamen, Stat.

Cert&emacron;, adverb. Certainlie, surelie,
without dout, without faile, truely, vere
ly, yea verelie, indeede, at the least wise.

Cert&ibreve;f&ibreve;co, as, * The same that Cer­
tioro.

Certifio, To be certified.

Cert&ibreve;&omacron;ro, as, Digest. To certifie, to
aduertise of.

Cert&ibreve;&omacron;ror, passi. Vlp. Certisso, as,
Pacuv. To be certified, or sure.

Cert&ibreve;t&umacron;do, inis, f.g. * Certaintie,
suretie.

Cert&omacron;, adverb. For a suretie, certain­
lie, surely, assuredly, manifestly, clearely.

Certo, as. To contend with one, to
striue, to fight with, to try, to prooue ma­
steries, to sue one an other, to endeuour,
to enforce him selfe all that he can, to
studie earnestlie, to compare with.

Certum est. I am fullie minded, or
determined.

Certus, a, um, Certior, Certissi­
mus. Certaine, sure, approued, true,
without doubt, that cannot be auoided,
necessarie, that neuer faileth, hardie,
stedie, stout, firme, trustie, faithful, vn­
fained, appointed, determined, strong,
constant, motorious, manifest, cleare,
knowne, quiet, or calme. Interdum cer­
tus dicitur constitutus, hoc est, tan­
tus & talis quantum ac qualem vo­
lumus.

Cerva, æ, f.g. Plin. A hinde.

Cesso, as, To cease, to leaue worke, not
to goe forward, to be vndone, to be wan­

nish.

C&emacron;stus, i, f. & quandoque, m.g.

with. Lotum etiam, aut opus inter­

ornamentum fæmininum, Ceston
Græci vocant.

Chære, Mart. All haile, God speede.

Chærephillum, li, n.g. Colum. An

lassitudine, nimiove labore, aliave
ex causa evenit, vt laxatis vinculis,
membrum excidat.

Ch&abreve;assis, is. * A kinde of white gar­
ments: after some the knot wherewith
womens garments were tyed on the
shoulders.

Chalasium or Chalasia, *A disease
in the eye, hauing a little white pimpell
like a hayle stone.

Chalastricum, or Chalastreum ni­
tium, Plin. Pure salt peeter, like salte.

Ch&abreve;l&amacron;za, æ, f.g. * A gathering vnder
the skinne: a waxe kernell.

A stone like




to hayle, and so colde, that no fire can
heate it.

ras, or vitrioll.

building.

Ch&abreve;lybs, ybis, m.g. Virg. Steele, a

Ch&abreve;mæ, Plin. A kind of shel fishes,

Ch&abreve;mæcissus, si, f.g. Plin. Of some,

Chamæsice, Diosc. The same that
Astralagus.

Ch&abreve;mæ&amacron;ct&emacron;, es, f.g. Plin. Latinè E­
bulum. Walwort.

Ch&abreve;mæc&emacron;r&abreve;sus, si, f.g. Plin. A litle
shrub, like the yong shootes springing
out of a plumme tree.

Ch&abreve;mæcyp&abreve;rissus, si, f.g. t.b. Plin.
An hearbe, which beeing drunke in
wine is holsome against the poyson of ser­
pents: it is taken of some for lauender
cotten. turner saith, it is rather another
hearbe more like to Cypres: heath Cy­
pres, dwarfe Cypres.

Ch&abreve;mæd&amacron;phn&emacron;, es, f.g. Plin.
Per­
winckle, Lawreall.

Chamædracontes, Isid. A kinde of
serpent.

Ch&abreve;mædrys, ys, f.g. Plin. Called also
Triffago, the hearb Germander, or En­
glish treacle.

Chamælæa, æ, f.g. Plin. An hearbe
hayuing leaues like oliues.

Ch&abreve;mæl&ebreve;on, &omacron;nis, f.g. Plin. A hearb
whereof be two kindes, the one white, &
the other blacke. The white is ful of
prickes, in manner of litle thistles grow­
ing by the ground without any long
stalke, commonlie called Chamæleon­
ta. The blacke is the common thistel,
with a greate long stalke, wherewith
they doe curde the mylke, to make cheese
withal, commonlie called Chamæleon­
ta nigra.

Ch&abreve;mæl&ebreve;on, ontis. A little beast that
doth easilie chaunge it selfe into al co­
lours, that it sitteth vpon (besides redde
& white) and is nourished onelie with
the aire.

Ch&abreve;mæl&emacron;uce, es, f.g. Plin. Called al­
so, Bechion, Tussilago, & vngula ca­
ballina: the hearb called coltes hoofe, of
some asses foote, growing commonlie
with vs, as wel in corne fieldes, as other
where, with a broade leafe like a po­
plar.

Chamælopardalis,* A beast as
greate as a Camell, of skinne like the
Panther.




Ch&abreve;mæm&ebreve;lus, li, n.g. Plin. The
hearb Camomil. Chamæmelum lute­
um, The same that Chrysanthemon.

Ch&abreve;memyrs&imacron;n&emacron;, es, f.g. Plin. Of
some it is taken for the bush, whereof
they make brushes, called Ruscus, of
some called Hollie, houlme, wild meurt.

Ch&abreve;mæp&ibreve;tys, yos, f.g. Plin. An
hearb called Ajuga, or Abiga, or Thus
terræ. Of it be three sortes: one is com­
monlie called hearbe Iuie: the second
smal Cypres set in pottes: the third is
thought to be Saint Iohns wort.

Chamæplatani,* vocantur humi­
les platani, & coactæ brevitatis.

Ch&amacron;mær&obreve;p&ebreve;s, vel potiùs Camer­
riphes, & Chamæripes, Plin. Arbo­
res sunt ex specie dactylorum, quæ
in Creta & in Sicilia nascuntur.

Chamæropis,* The same that Cha­
mædrys.

Chamærops, Plin. An hearbe, some
thinke it to be Germander.

Chamæsyce, Plin. A kind of hearb.

Ch&abreve;mæt&ebreve;ræ, & Chamæterides,
Plin. Litle images set by great images.

Ch&abreve;mæz&emacron;l&obreve;n. Pli. An hearb, which
some thinke to be gnaphalium, others
Quinquefolium.

Chamulci, Marcell. Engynes wher­
with ships be drawne to the shore.

à circumstantibus, donec ab eo pre­
hensus quispiam, eius vices subeat.

Chytropus, &obreve;dus. m.g. A skillet, or
chafer, or pot hauing feete.

C&ibreve;b&amacron;lis, le, Lactant. Of or belonging
to meate, or the passage whereby meate
goeth into the stomach.

C&ibreve;b&amacron;r&ibreve;a, &omacron;rum, n.g. Foode, meate,
nourishment, sustenance, vittailes, fod­
der.

C&ibreve;b&amacron;r&ibreve;um, rij, n.g. Plin. The meale
after flower is boulted out.

C&ibreve;b&amacron;r&ibreve;us, a, um, adject. Pertaining
to meate or vittaile, fit to be eaten: also
vile, base, simple, ranged or course.

meat.

Cibo, as, Colum. To nourish, to
feede.

C&ibreve;b&omacron;r&ibreve;um, rij, n.g. Horat. The

made like the leafe of it. Porphi. Also
a litle coffer, or vessel to drinke in.

C&ibreve;bus, bi, m.g. Meat, al kind of vi­
tailes or meat: foode, sustenance, nouri­
shment.

holsome for one, and hurtful for an other.

Cibutum, Isid.  Idem quod Arca.

C&ibreve;c&umacron;ta, æ, f.g. An hearbe much like

leaues, some vse it for hemlocke: the iuice

and therefore the Athenians vsed it to

hemlocke, or cane.

siluer.

Circ&amacron;, præp. seruiens accus. A­
bout, nigh to, by: sometime it signifieth a­

Circ&amacron;n&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. A bird that in his

Circenses Iudi, vel Circenses, sine
adjectione, Virg. Games or plaies of
wrastling and running, kept among the
Romanes, in a large place of the fielde:
running with great horses at lifts, bar­
riers, iusts, or tornement. Horum 7. erant
curricula solennia, Gell. Circense
tomentum dicitur, quod fit ex sum­
mitatibus palustium arundinum
mollibus, lanæ similibus, Mart.

Circensis, se, adject, à Circus. Bud.
Of or belonging to round running: which
goeth and commeth to and fro.

Circ&emacron;rus, Non. A great shippe vsed
in Asia.

Circuncurro, is, * To runne all about,

Circuncurrens ars, Quint. An art
not restrained or tied to any certain mat­

about hither and thither.

Circus, ci, m.g. A rundle, or circle:
Also, a place in Rome, where the people
sat and beheld the plaies and games. those
games were called Circenses. Also,
a kinde of hawke verie swift, and an e­
nemie to Pigeons, Plin.

co mam nutriunt, quam Veneri con­
secrent detonsam.

Cirrus, ri, m.g. Var. A tuffe or locke
of haires curled: the creast or feathers
that be vppon the toppe of birdes: Others
thinke it to be the haire of the heade pol­
led, Cato. also a t hing growing on the
hearbes.

ces.

out of their places, of those vessels which
doe nourish the stone of man.

Cirsos,* A disease in the cods.

vil.

C&ibreve;to, as, Frequent. à Cieo, To call
or summon, to appeare, to alledge and
name, to hast, to stirre vp, to prouoke: also
to set a daie of compearing: to assemble
or call togeather, to recite, or rehearse,
to praise, to tell, to cal or bring forth as
witnes.

C&obreve;hors, ortis, f.g. A band of men,
whereof the Romane legion contai­
ned tenne. The first bande, wherein the
standard was, had 1105. footemen, 132.
men of armes, & was Cohors millena­
ria. the seconde band called Quingen­
taris, had 555. footemen, 66. men of
armes. The other bandes had the same
number, so that they made vp, 6100.
footemen, 736. men of armes, which was
the Romaine legion. A bande of men of
armes, of souldiers: a companie, an
assemble of what people soeuer. Also
those that did accompanie and garde the
Magistrate that went into a Prouince.
A traine or companie of servants at­
tending vpon any noble man. Also, a
barton or place inclosed where pultrie is
kepte. Colum.

C&obreve;l&omacron;ni, &omacron;rum, m.g. A certaine num­

C&omacron;l&obreve;n&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. Oppidum in quod

xerant, vel quod sine traductione
Coloniarum jure donatum erat. A
place vnhabited, whither people are
sent to dwell: sometime the people sent to
inhabite anie such place: a citie the
people whereof once came from ano­
ther Citie, or countrie that was before it:
an vnder Citie or toune: Also, the house,
or dwelling place of a husband man.
Plaut. Also, a grange, or farme where
husbandrie is kept, Paul.

Who parteth the profit of his lande with
his landlorde. Colonus perpetuarius,
Gratian. Who for a peece of monie hath
hyred his lande for euer, or for his life
time.

Commendo, as. To commit, or to put
in trust with, to commend, praise, or set
forth, to make more esteemed, commen­
ded, acceptable, & worthie praise, to able
to aduaunce the dignitie of a thing: to

Comment&amacron;r&ibreve;&obreve;lum, li. n. g. dim. à

Comment&amacron;r&ibreve;um, n. g. & commen­
tarij, orum, m. g. Abridgement, or
booke conteyning thinges breifelie writ­
ten: a booke of notes or remembrances, a
register, a briefe history conteining the
actes of any person: a briefe note of instru­
ction: a Comment or exposition. Sometime
it is taken for him that maketh a com­
mentarie.

Comment&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f. g. verb. à
Commentor. A meditating, a deuising
of a thing, a debating or reasoning of: a
musing, intreating of: a description or
setting out in writing. A deliberation
for the inuenting of any thing.

Comment&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Mused
on, invented, deuised, imagined, written,
thought vpon before: disputed or deba­
ted.

Comment&ibreve;or, &imacron;ris, Apul. To lie or
feigne.

Comment&imacron;t&ibreve;us, a, um. Fained, deui­
sed for a time, counterfeit, newely deui­
sed or invented.

Commentor, &amacron;ris, &amacron;tus sum, &amacron;ri,
Frequent à Comminiscor To muse or
thinke on, to deliberate, to cast in his
minde: to make mention, to debate and
talke of, to dispute, common, or reason of:
to make or write commentaries, or books
of remembrances: to deuise, to inuent, or
imagine a false tale, to counterfeite one,
to compounde.

Commentor, &omacron;ris, m. g. verb. à Com­
miniscor, Ovid. An inuenter or deuiser.

Commentum, ti. n. g. A comment
or exposition, a sodaine deuise, a fained
matter, a lie, a false taile, an inuention.

Commentus, a, um, part. à Commi­
niscor. That commenteth, imagineth, or
deuiseth: also inuented, fained, forged.

ther, to goe with, to goe and come.

Commercor, &amacron;ris, Plaut. To buie

An assembling or gathering togither: a

Conc&ibreve;l&ibreve;o, as. To accorde or make

vour, to reconcile, to ioyne or knit togi­

ble, to allure, to purchase, to make, to




worke, to praise, commend, or make e­
steemed, to gather. Conciliare etiam
pro lenocinari, Suet. Dicitur etiam
de fullonibus, quando telam Ianem
rudem subigunt pedibus subsultan­
do identidem, Iun.

Iasionis, Plin.

Cong&ibreve;us, gij, m.g. Plin. A kinde of
liquid measure, after Budey, the eight
part of Amphora, containing sixe Sex­
taries: Euerie Sextarie being foure and
twentie ounces, that is, a wine pinte and
a halfe: So that Congius is of our mea­
sure a gallon and a pinte. If you doe take
Sextaries for eighteene ounces, as Phisi­
tions doe, or for twentie ounces, as Agri­
cola doth, then is it but a pottell, a quart,
halfe a pinte, and foure ounces, or other­
wise according to the rate: it is vsed for
our gallon.

Constans, tis, & Constantiss&ibreve;­
mus, a, um, adiect. Constant, firme,

Constant&ebreve;r, adverb. Constantlie,

Constant&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. Constancie, stead­
fastnesse, stablenesse, hardinesse, perse­
uerance in doeing, &c. grauitie.

Constat, It is euident, manifest, plaine,
and certaine: agreed of, or wel knowne,
there is no controuersie in it: (Ratio­
nem constare significat æquam le­
gitimamque rationem aut ostendi,
aut apparere ostendi, posse, Vlp.)
Also, it costeth, it is solde.

Const&amacron;t&umacron;rus, Plin. That wil cost.

yearely chosen to gouerne their citie: a
Consull: sometimes it is vsed of Poets for a
yeares space, because euerie yeare new
Consuls were created.

Cons&ubreve;l&amacron;ris, adiect. Of or pertaining

vir Consulatis. Which hath beene Con­

diction of the Consull. Foemina consu­

sull.

prooue or assaie, to sue for.

Cont&ibreve;nens, ntis, part. & nom. ex
part. à Contineo, Continentissimus.
Ioyning or next to, continuall, without

rupted or staied: continent, sober, tempe­
rate, chast in forbearing women, and o­
ther pleasures: not covetous, not vsing
extortion or polling: comprehending or
contayning: Also the principall poynt of
a matter in controversie. Continentes
causæ, which containe their effectes in
them. Continens terra, & Continens,
Plin. The firme or maine lande, that is no
Isle, nor separated by sea. In continenti,
Vlp. Incontinent, forthwith, by and by.

ciari.

C&obreve;r&ibreve;&amacron;g&imacron;n&omacron;sos, a, um, Veget. Sick
of the hidebound.

C&obreve;r&ibreve;&amacron;go, &ibreve;nis, f.g. Colum. The sick­
nes of Cattell being clung, or hidebound,
when the skinne doth so cleaue fast to
their sides, that they cannot stirre.

non, Diosc. The hearb called Coriander.

Corimbi, Isid. sunt annuli, qui pro­
xima quæque ligant & comprehen­
dunt, ne longiùs laxati palmites ven­
torum flatibus dissipentur.

Corn&umacron;, n.g. indecl. & cornus, Prisc.
Plurali, cornua, um. A horne: a corner

disputationis, The principall arguments.
 Cornua antennarum, the two endes
of the sayle yeardes. Cornua piscium,
idem quod citri, Iun.

C&obreve;ralla, æ, f.g. dim. à Corona,Plin.
A litle crowne or garland.

C&obreve;roll&amacron;t&ibreve;um, rij, n.g. The addition
or aduantage aboue measure: the ouerplus:

C&obreve;ron. Diosc. Herba eadem est
cum sylvestri ruta.

C&obreve;r&omacron;na, æ, f.g. A crowne, a Chaplet:
a garland: a companie of men standing
round togither about one: a circle about
the moone: also a signe in heaven vpon
the shoulder of Atrophylax, Virg. also
a garment that bondmen wore when they
were solde, Cæs. Also the water tables or
copings of wals, Vitruv. Also, The begin­
ning or ioyning of the hoofe: in hearbs a
litle garland: the brimme of a pot, Iun.
Corona pactilis, Plin. Platted about
with floures. Sutilis, Plin. Sewed togi­
ther with threeds binding the flowers
fast. Collaris, Iun. which compasseth
the neck. Corona terræ, Iun. grounde
Ivie. Fuerunt etiam apud Romanos
varia Coronæ genera. I. Corona ca­
strensis sive Vallaris, giuen to him that
first invaded the enemies campe. 2. Co­
rona muralis, Sill. given to him that
first scaled the walls. 3. Corona civica,
vide Civicus. 4. Corona navalis vel
rostrata, Virg. giuen to him which first
boorded a shippe. 5. Corona Obsidio­
nalis, Liv. giuen to a captaine that ray­
sed a siege. 6. Corona triumphalis, O­
vid. sent to the Emperour in honour of
triumph. 7. Corona Ovalis, sive myr­
tea, Agell. giuen to a Prince or captaine
for a victorie without slaughter of men.

Coronæ, vide Coronices.

C&obreve;r&omacron;n&amacron;lis, Iun. One of the ligatures
of the skull, so called, because that there
the garland is set on the head.

C&obreve;r&omacron;n&amacron;mentum, ti, n.g. Plin. Flow­
ers & such like things to make garlandes
of.

Coronarium, Iun. A present giuen to
a Prince at his Coronation, or after some
great victorie, &c.

Cum, præp. seruiens ablat. With.

Cum, siue Quum, adverb. When,
where, whereas: seeing that, for as much
as, albeit, as, although, & moreouer, ouer
and besides.

Cum & Tum eleganter se invicem
in eadem clausula subsequuntur: 
quæ licet idem significant, diverso
tamen modo ordinantur: nam in
Cum est quiddam minus, in tum est
quiddam maius. Et hoc duobus mo­
dis fit: vt aut generale aliquid præ­
cedat & sequatur speciale, aut am­
bo sint specialia: As, so much more, or
so especiallie: both, and, or and especially.

Cum alter, pro cum altero, Fest.

Cum partim, pro partim, Cato.

Cum primis, adverb. Chieflie, the
first of al. Cum plurimùm, adverb.
Plin. For the moste parte, or at the most.
Cum minimum, Plin. At the least. Cum
maximè. As much as euer: neuer more
then, &c.

Cyn&obreve;c&ebreve;ph&amacron;l&emacron;a, p.b. Plin. an hearb

ovum.

Cynozolion, Plin. A stinking weede

eares.

f.g. p.b. Isid. A Cypres tree.

gallingale.

D&emacron;c&umacron;r&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. Fiue bands of souldi­
ers were appointed among the Romaines
to be assistent to Iudges or Magistrates
sitting in matters of life and death: euery
band was deuided into ten partes, and
thereof was called Decuria: or else be­
cause euery band contained 1000. men,
which is ten hundred. Also the Sena­
tours and Iudges were deuided into
bandes called Decurias, and the chiefe
of each companie was called Decurio. Bandes
of tenne men: any company of
men great or smal.

D&emacron;c&umacron;r&ibreve;&amacron;t&ibreve;o, onis, & Decuriatus,

men.

men at armes: also a petie Captaine of
tenne. Decurio cubiculariorum.
Suet. high or great Chamberlaine.

or companies.

one ende to the other: Also, to saile, to de­
scriue, to declare or passe ouer.

D&ebreve;cuss&amacron;tio, onis. f.g. Vitru. A diui­

D&ebreve;cussis, is, m.g. Vitruvi. Ten whole

representing the letter X: which parted
in the middle maketh an other figure
Quincunx, V.

D&emacron;f&ibreve;c&ibreve;ens, Part. Fayling, fainting,

D&emacron;f&ibreve;c&ibreve;o, is, &emacron;ci, ctum, &ebreve;re, quando
pro Relinquere & deserere accipi­
tur, habet passivum, quando pro De­
fetiscor, neutrum est. To lack or faile,
to cease, to forsake, to leaue, not to be like
himselfe: to rebell, to departe from him
that entertaineth one, to goe from one
captaine to an other, to reuolt: to be wea­

to be in the eclipse or to loose his light.

D&emacron;f&ibreve;c&ibreve;or, passi. To want, to loose.

D&emacron;f&imacron;go, is, xi, xum, &ebreve;re. To sticke or

D&emacron;fin&ibreve;o, is, &imacron;vi, &imacron;tum, &imacron;re. To bound,

D&emacron;f&imacron;n&imacron;t&emacron;, adverb. Expresselie,
namelie, preciselie, particularlie, deter­
minatelie, shortlie: measurably, or in a
certaine measure, with limitation: at
a fewe wordes.

D&emacron;fin&imacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. A defini­
tion, which in fewe wordes expresseth
what it is that is spoken of: a declaring
or specifying.

or wantonnes. Also, waywardnes and
importunate desire of a thing vnreaso­
nable and vnhonest. Delicias facere,

and daintie.

D&emacron;n&amacron;r&ibreve;us, rij, m.g. An olde pennie
worth tenne peeces of syluer: it is also an
other pennie or coyne worth three shil­
lings six pence, or after others worth 8.
pence: and we commonlie vse it for a
pennie of English coyne.

D&emacron;n&amacron;r&ibreve;us, a, um, Plin. That contai­
neth the numbe rof tenne, tenth: Dena­
riæ fistulæ, Plin. Of tenne foote long.

D&emacron;n&amacron;r&ibreve;us numinus, Liv. & simpli­
citer, Denarius. The Romaine pennie,
worth 4. festerios, and went in paie for
10. Asses: of it were three sortes: one,
the sixt parte of an ounce, and was more
by the thirde parte, then the Greeke
Drachma: an other was the seuenth
parte of an ounce, weighing a dramme
and the seuenth part thereof, and twen­
tie and foure went to a pound: the thirde
was the eight parte of an ounce equal to
the Greeke Dramme, and in value a
sterling groate, when eight went to an
ounce.

Dens, tis, m.g. A tooth: also euerie o­
ther thing wherewith any thing may be
holden or plucked out: sometime a combe.
Dentes primores, incisores, vel tomi­
ci, iun. The foreteeth. Dentes canini
vel columellares, Iun. The sharpe or
eie teeth. Dentes molares vel mixilla­
res, Iun. The eie teeth, or grinders. Den­
tes gemini vel intimi, Iun. The iaw or cheeke teeth. 
Dentes exerti, Plaut. Gag
teeth. Dentium crepitus. The chatte­
ring or crashing of the teeth. Dentium
stupor, Iun. A bluntnes of the teeth,
when with eating of sharpe and sowre
things they be out of edge.

Dens leonis, & dens caninus. Iun.
The hearbe dandelion, dogges teeth, or
common cicorie.

Dens Saturnini, Virg. A sickle.

Dens vncus, Virg. & dens aratri.
Colum. The plough share.

gathering thick together, a thickning.

togither.

Dens&ebreve;o, es, &ebreve;re, Plin. To waxe thick
or to congeale.

Dens&ibreve;tas, &amacron;tis, f.g. Plin. 
Thicknes.

Denso, as, Virg. To thicken, to
make or grow thick: to close fast togither.

Densus, a, um, & Densior, Virg.

Densissimus, Ovid. Thick, harde clo­
sed togither, compact, plenteous, abun­
dant, often, continuall, full of.

Dent&amacron;l&ebreve;, is, n.g. Virg. The woode
wherein the coulter is closed, the share
of a plough.

Dentarpaga. Varr. A paire of pin­
sers to pluck out an hollow tooth.

Dent&amacron;tim, adverb. * In order like
teeth.

Dent&amacron;tus, a, um. That hath great,
strong, or maine teeth: toothed: that
hath teeth longer or greater then ordi­

and taunting.

Dentex, Aelian. A certaine fish
which hurteth much with his teeth.

Dent&ibreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;tus, a, um, Plin. That
hath little teeth, or that hath teeth like

Dent&ibreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;tim, adverb. * Like teeth.

Dent&ibreve;c&ubreve;lo, as, * To thrust in his

Desultores, Liv. Certen men of warre

two horsers, and oftentimes to take the
backe of the fresh horse, when the other
was wearie and tyred.

ours horse as was easie to take and would
stand by without a bridle.

&  Dictamus, vel  Dictamnus, f.g. An

Dict&amacron;tor, &omacron;ris, m.g. He that pronoun­
ceth to an other a thing to be written: Al­
so a chiefe officer among the Romanes,
which for halfe a yeare had a kings pow­
er, never chosen but in some great daun­
ger or trouble of the common wealth, and
at the halfe yeares ende vnder paine of
treason yeelded vp his authoritie.

Dicto, as, frequent. à Dico. to tell,
appoint, or rehearse to one what or how
he shall write: to speake, to bidde or coun­
sell, to promise. Dictare actionem sive
judicium apud jurisc. significat actio­
nem adversario voce edere, quum a­
ctor adversario quam actionem in­
tenturus sit, denuntiat.

Diel cystinda, Iun. A kinde of plaie,
wherein two companies of boyes holding
handes all in a rowe, do pull with harde
holde one another till one side be ouer­
come: it is called Sunne and Moone.

D&imacron;es, &emacron;i, m. & f.g. in sing. in plur.
tantum masc. A daie, time or season.
Quinquennij die, pro quinto anno,
Procul. Die crastini vel septimi, pro
crastino vel septimo, Plaut. Diequar­
ti & diequartè (illud de præterito,
hoc de futuro intelligitur) pro die
quarto: & die pristini vel diepristinè,
pro die pristino, Macrob. Dies civi­
lis, Plin. A divill or artificiall daie con­
sisting of 24. houres. Comitialis, of ele­
ction or meeting, to consult of matters.
Fastus, Ovid. An hall, court, or plea­
ding daie, as in terme time, &c. Nefa­
stus, Wherein was no pleading,
nor sitting to heare or determine suites in
law. Lustricus, Suet. Of ones Christning
or baptisme. Dies vigiliarum, Iun. Ho­
lidaies eves. Dies justi. Daies of respit
or forbearance giuen by the law to them
that confessed a debt; to provide money,
in which dayes it was not lawfull to med­
dle with the debtour.

D&ibreve;escit,* It is daie, it waxeth day.

D&ibreve;esp&ibreve;ter, tris, Horat. Diei pater,
vel supiter.

Diesis, Vitru. The quarter of a tune,
or the halfe of halfe a tune.

D&ibreve;&ebreve;t&emacron;ris, Censorin. The space of two
yeares.

famed, that hath an ill name or report.

Diff&amacron;mo, as, Tacit. To defame, to
spread an ill report of, to publish.

at a diuorsement, as Confarreatio was

Differitas, pro Differentia, Lucret.

Diff&ebreve;ro, ffers, stuli, l&amacron;tum, ferre. To
bring from one place to another: to carie
a sunder, or into diuerse partes: to trouble
and with sodaine feare to bring to his
wittes end: to prolong, to deferre, put of,
or delaie: to report, sow, or spread abroad:
to rent or teare in peeces: to diuide or cut
a sunder, to scatter, to differ or be in dif­
ference, to varie, to be vnlike, to disa­
gree: to fitte in order.

Digitis micare, A plaie vsed in Ita­
lie, where one holdes vp his fingers, and
the other turning away, giues a gesse how
manie he holdes vp: it is called here, and
in France and Spayne, the play of loue.

Digitus aquæ, Paul. Sextadecima

D&ibreve;opt&ibreve;c&emacron;,* That parte of astrologie,
which by instruments searcheth out the
distances of the Sunne, Moone, or other
places.

D&ibreve;optra, æ f.g. Plin. A measure to
wey water: a geometricall instrument to

place a farre of by looking through litle
holes therein.

Dioryx, ygis, Pomp. Mela. A ditch
or trench made with hand.

Dioscuri, Iun. Two lightes appea­
ring in likenes of fire, and sitting vpon
the mastes or sayle yeards of, shippes, be­
tokening a luckie vyage to saylers: Ca­
stor and Pollux, or S. Helen.

Diospoliticon, ci, n.g. Galen. A

D&ibreve;&omacron;ta, æ, f.g. Horat. A vessell for

gypt made with the hande to deriue the




waters of Nylus into the fields.

D&imacron;phris, Plin. A pretious stone of 2.
sortes, white and black, male and female.

D&imacron;phrix, &ibreve;gis, Plin. Materia quæ­
dam terrea, quæ in metallis æris in­
venitur, aut in ipsis etiam conchis in
quibus æs expurgatur.

Diphthera,* A sheepheards pelt. I­
tem stragula quædam pellicea, quæ
in superiori navis pavimento exten­
debatur: & pellis Amaltheæ capræ,
in qua dicitur Iupiter res humanas
describere.

Diphthongus,* A diphthong, two
vowells contract into one bodie or forme.

Diple, A note or marke in the mar­
gent to signifie that there is somewhat to
be amended.

Dipletrum, tri, n.g. * The third parte
of stadium.

Diplinthij parietes,* Walles wher­
in be two rowes of brick.

Diplois, dis, f.g. Iun. A lined gar­
ment, now taken for a doublet: a souldi­
ers coate for warmth.

uident.

Dr&abreve;b&emacron;, Ruell. An hearbe growing
halfe a cubite high, and hauing a tufte
like elder at the toppe.

Dracæna, æ, f.g. Iun. The female or
the Dragon: a Quavyuer.

sterling groat of 8. to the ounce. Drach­

ma Attica, Iun. Seven pense. Drach­
ma auri, * Twelue silver drams, that is,
an ounce and an hafe of siluer.

Plin. A fish called also Araneus.

ius varia sitin modum colubri, simi­
litudinem que draconis imitetur; vel
quòd eam herbá vipera timeat, Isid.

Dr&abreve;cont&ibreve;um, tij, n.g. Plin. Dragon­
