handfull.

Dr&amacron;ma, &abreve;tis, n.g. When in a Come­
die or tragedy diuers persons are brought
in, some tarying, and some departing.

Dramaticum, Iun. A base kinde of
poetrie which endeth troublesom matters
merilie. Dramaticus stylus. Which is
not mixt, and where the Poet himselfe
doth neuer speake.

Drenso, as, Philom. To sing as a
Swanne.

Dr&ebreve;p&abreve;nis, Plin. A sea swallow.

Dr&obreve;mas, &abreve;dis, vel Dromon, &  Dro­
meda, m.g. Liv. A kinde of Cammells
with two bunches on the backe, maruei­
lous swift, and maie abide three daies
iourney without drinke. Also, a runner
or poste, Ovid. Also, a Caravel, or swift
Barke that scoureth the seas, Iun. also,
a kinde of fish verie swift, Plin.

Dromos,* A course, or the place
where men doe runne horses, to trie their
swiftnes.

Dr&omacron;pax, &abreve;cis, m.g. Mart. A mede­
cine or oyntment wherewith the hairie
places of the bodie are made smooth and
balde for a time.

Droselitus lapis, Isid. varius, quia
si ad ignem applicetur, velut sudo­
rem mittit.

Drofomeli, Iun. Honie dewe.

Drupæ, arum, f.g. Plin. Olyues, or
oyle beries betweene green and ripe wax­
ing blacke.

Dry&obreve;ph&obreve;non, p.b. Herba est dry­
opteri similis, &c. Officinæ nemora­
lem myrtum appellant.

Dryophytæ, Plin. A kinde of frogges.

Dryopteris, p.b. Plin. An hearbe
called Vsemond royall, Okeferne, petie
ferne.




Dryos hyphear. genus visci est, co­
piosissimè in quercu inascens.

Dryperæ, p.b. * Olyues ripe and rea­
die to fall of the tree.

Drysmus, mi, m.g. * A verie vene­
mous worme in the roote of an Oke.

D&umacron;co, is, xi, ctum, &ebreve;re. To lead, guide,

out or awaie, to goe, to bring or induce,

steeme or set by, to regard, to iudge or

etiam instrumenta, quibus funes in­

adplumbata, eo ordine, vt terni &
quaterni simul aquam eodem ex pu­
teo haurire possint, funiculo per ro­
tum dimisso, Vlp.

Epitoniorum manubria, Iun. The
keies of the organes, whereupon the fin­
gers runne to and fro in playing.

Epitragi,* Wormes which doe much
hurt to vines.

Epitragia,* A certaine fish.

Ep&ibreve;tr&abreve;p&emacron;z&ibreve;a, &omacron;rum, n.g. p.b. * All
manner of vessels belonging to the table.

Ep&ibreve;tr&imacron;tus, p.b. Isid. A foore consi­
sting of 4. syllables whereof one doth al­
waies differ from the other three. Also a
proportion, containing some number, &
the third part thereof.

Epitrochasmus, Aquila. A figure,
whereby we doe speedily runne over ma­
nie differing things, that sowe maie a­
maze and trouble our adversarie.

Ep&ibreve;tr&obreve;p&emacron;, es, p.b. Rufin. A figure,
when as we permit one to doe that he
would, and yet thinke nothing lesse.

Ep&ibreve;tyrum, p. & t.b. Cato. A kinde
of sauce or seasoning made of Olives.

Epizeuxis, Isid. A figure, doubling
a worde in one sense, and having no other
word betweene it.

Epizygis, Vitruv. The hole wherein
the nut of a steele bowe lieth.

Epoche, es, f.g. A witholding of his
assent.

Ep&omacron;dus, di, m.g. p.b. Quint. A kind
of verses having the first verse longer
then the second.

Epomis, idis, f.g. Iun. A hood, such as
be of the liveries of their companies doe
weare on their shoulders: a mourning
hood.

Epops, vid. Vpupa.

Epoptæ in sacris dicebantur my­
stæ, qui totum iam annum initiati,




ad spectanda sacra admittebantur.

Eporhedicæ, arum, * Good breakers
of horses.

Epos, odos, n.g. Horat. A kinde of
verse or song containing things touching
both God and man.

Epostracismus, Iun. A kinde of sport
or plaie with an oister shell or a stone
throwne into the water, and making cir­
cles yer it sinke: it is called a duck and a
drake and a halfe penie cake.

Ep&obreve;to, as, p.l. Liv. To drinke vp all.


Ep&omacron;tus, a, um, part. p.l. Ovid. Drun­
ken, swallowed, or soked vp.

Epula, æ, pro Epulum. Fest.

Ep&ubreve;lat&omacron;rius, a, um, p.b. Apt to be ea­
ten at a feast or banket.

Ep&ubreve;læ, &amacron;rum, f.g. p.b. Meates what­
soever are to be eaten: foode, pasture or
meate for beastes: also delicates or dain­
ties. also, a plentifull instruction in mat­
ters of, Plin. Epulæ ferales, vid. E­
pulum.

Ep&ubreve;landus, a, um, part. ab Epulor,
p.b. Ovid. That is to be eaten.

Ep&ubreve;l&amacron;ris, re, p.b. Belonging to, or
meete for a feast or banket. Epulares e­
tiam dicebantur, qui in sacris epula­
bantur, Varr.

Ep&ubreve;l&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. p.b. Co­
lum. A feasting or banketting.

Epulatorius, a, um, * Which is fitte
to be eaten at bankets.

Ep&ubreve;l&amacron;tus, a, um, part. p.b. That
hath feasted or made good cheere.

Ep&ubreve;lis, &ibreve;dis, f.g. Paul. Aegynet.
Flesh growing about the gummes of a
mans teeth.

Ep&ubreve;lo, &omacron;nis, m.g. p.b. One of the
Triumvitri, whose dutie it was to furnish
banquets for Iupiter and the rest of the
gods. Also anie guest at a feast.

Epulonus, Fest. Idem.

Ep&ubreve;lor, &amacron;ris, depon. p.b. To eate
at bankets, to banket: to take his meate
or his repast.

Ep&umacron;l&omacron;t&ibreve;ca, p.b. Medicamenta à
medicis appellantur, quæ cicatri­
cem obducunt.

Ep&ubreve;lum, li, n.g. p.b. A great feast
solemnelie made to a multitude, either by
those that did triumpth, or at the funerall
of some great man, or at the dedicating
of a Church. Epulum funebre vel fe­
rale. A funerall feast or banket.

Equa, ad, f.g. p.b. A mare.

Equapium, pij, n.g. Iun. The hearb
Alisander or loueage.

Equ&amacron;r&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. p.b. Varr. An heard
of horses & mares.

Equarius, rij, m.g. Iun. A ferrier
or horseleech, a curer of horses.

Equarius medicus, Val. A horseleach.

Equ&amacron;r&ibreve;us, a, um, p.b. Varr. Pertai­
ning to an horse.

Eques, &ibreve;tis, com. g. p.b. A horse­
man: a man of armes: among the Romains
a gentleman, a knight, a squire: also
a Iudge, Suet. and a horse, Virg. in cards
the knave or verlet. Equites cata­
phracti, Liv. The hard horsed men that
breake the aray.

Equestre, Iun. the race of a horse
halfe a mile or 4. furlonges.

Equestria, Senec. erant 14. ordines
graduum in Orchestra. Places or seates
appointed for gentlemen to sitte in, to be­
holde solemne sightes or plaies.

Equ&ibreve;dem, conjunct. p.b. Verilie,
trulie: sometime it signifieth nothing, but
supplieth the number.

Equ&ibreve;f&ebreve;rus, ri, ex Equus & Ferus,
p.b. Plin. A wilde horse.

Equ&imacron;le, is, n.g. p.b. Varr. A stable
for horses.

Equ&ibreve;mentum, ti, n.g. p.b. Varro.
The hire for a stalion to cover a mare.

Equ&imacron;nus, a, um, p.b. Of an horse.

When a mare desireth to be couered of a
horse.

Equ&imacron;r&ibreve;a, orum, n.g. Ovid. p.b. A run­
ning with horses: a play dedicated to
Mars.

Equitine, Fest. A swearing by Qui­
rinus.

Equiselis, Iun. An hearb like a horse
maine.

Equ&ibreve;sessor, &omacron;ris, m.g. p.b. * A man
on horseback.




Equ&ibreve;s&emacron;tum, ti, n.g. p.b. Plin. An
hearbe called horsetaile.

Equ&imacron;so, &omacron;nis, m.g. p.b. Var. An horse
rider, a colie breaker, a horsemaster.

Equ&ibreve;t&amacron;b&ibreve;lis, le, p.b. Liv.
Easie to be
ridde vpon, or that may be ridden vpon:
also where horses may easilie walke.

Equ&ibreve;t&amacron;t&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. verb. ab Equi­
to, p.b. Plin. A riding.

Equ&ibreve;tatus, us, m.g. verb. p.b. An
host or company of horsemen: the acte of
riding.

Equ&ibreve;t&ibreve;um, tij, n.g. p.b. Digest. An
hearde of horses, a company of horses.

Equ&ibreve;to, as p.b. To ride.

Equitor, aris, Plin. To be ridde vpon.

Equ&ubreve;la, læ, f.g. dim. ab Equa, p.b.
Var. A mare colt, a fillie.

Equ&ubreve;l&ebreve;us, lei, m.g. p.b. A horse colt,
also an instrument made of burning plats
liek to an horse, in which men were tor­
mented. vide Eculeus.

Equ&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. dim. ab Equa, p.b.
A nagge, a little horse: a colte, called al­
so equus novellus, or pullus equinus.

Equus, qui. m.g. p.b. an horse: also a
rocke from whence Daphytas was cast
downe headlong. Also a certaine starre in
the skie: an engine in warre called Aries:
a certaine fish in the sea. Equi vestigi­
um, Plin. An horse shoe. Equus agmina­
lis, Vlp. A warre horse, seruing to carie
necessaries belonging to the campe. Re­
fractarius, vel duri oris. Iun. Stubborn,
that will not be ruled, headstrong. Suf­
piriosus, vel anhelus, Iun. Short or
broken winded, or that bloweth much.
Meritorius vel conductitius, Iun. A
liverie or hired horse, a hackney. Tortor,
Non. &  crucians, Auson. Trotting. De­
sultorius, Iun. A low horse, from whose
backe it is easie lighting: or a horse with­
out saddle or furniture. Halcyarius,
Mart. A drag horse. Pavidus. Iun. A
skittish or feareful horse. Pumilus, Iun. A nagge, Scutulatus, Pallad. A dapple
graie horse, or hauing furniture of watch­
et colour, Cespitator, vel suffossus,
Virg. A stumbling iade.

Era singulorum annrum constitu­
ta est à Cæsare Augusto, quando pri­
mum censum exegit, ac Romanum
orbem descripsit. Dicta autem. Era ex
co, quod omnis orbis æs reddere
professius est reipulicæ, Isid.

Err&amacron;bundus, a, um, Liv. That wan­

Ervilia, æ, f.g. Iun. Graine which
some cal tares: some suppose it to be french

Ervingina, æ, f.g. Iun. A certaine

Erumna, vide Aurumna.

Erumpo, is, &umacron;pi, ptum, &ebreve;re, p.l. To
burst, breake, or issue violentlie out, to
leape out, to assaile, to set violentlie vpon:
to flie out swiftlie: to cast out, to come a­
broad to mens knowledge: to vtter or
shewe.

Erunco, as, p.l. Colum. To weed out,
or to pul vp weedes.

Er&ubreve;o, is, &ubreve;i, &ubreve;tum, &ebreve;re, p.l. To draw
out with force, to plucke vp by the rootes:
to get and come to the knowledge of
things by labour and studie, to searche or
finde out, to bring forth: to digge vp, to
subuert or ouerthrow.

Er&ubreve;pt&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. ab Erum­
po, p.l. A violent issuing or breaking
forth: a violent assailing.

Erupt&umacron;rus, a, um, p.l. Which wil
come, burst, or fal out.

Eruthrimus, Plin. A rotchet, or rou­
get.

Er&ubreve;tus, a, um, part. ab Eruor, p.l.
Pulled, picked, or weeded out: cast vp, sub­
uerted & ouerthrowne, set or searched out.

Ervum, vi, n.g. Plaut. A kind of pulse
somewhat like Vetches, called also Oro­
bos: Of it be both white and redde, both
kindes bigger and bitterer then a Vetch.

Erygion. Aloe, Diosc.

Eryng&emacron;, es, f.g. Eryngion, ij, n.g.
Plin. A kind of thistles with long leaues,
hauing also a stalke with a round knop
ful of long prickes, in forme of a starre, the
roote whereof beeing condite in honie
with Cinamon and Cloues, comforteth na­
ture, and styrreth courage: Sea holme, or
sea hollie.

Erysimon, Galen. A graine not much
vnlike to Sesama, but not nourishing:
Plinie calleth ir Irio. Others take it to be
a kinde of an hearb, Diosc. Others cal it
wilde cresses. &c.

Erysimum. Iun. Rocket gentle or roc­
ket gallant.

Erysipelas, atis, n.g. Iun. A swelling
ful of heat and rednes with paine rounde
about a sore or wounde, commonly called
S. Anthones fire.

Erysisceptrum, Diosc. The name of
diuerse hearbes.

Eryth&abreve;c&emacron;, es, f.g. p. & s.b. Varr. Bees
meate while they labour.

Erythinus, or Erythrynusm, or Ery­
thricus, Plin. A kind of seafish.

Erythra, Melissophillon, Diosc.

Erythranon, Bartoll. A kinde of
Ivie. Diosc. taketh it for Satyrium.

Erythios,* The hearbe redde Beets.

Erythræus lapillus, Stat. A pearle.

Erythrodanum, Iun. A kind of hearb
hauing a redde roote, madder, wherwith
woollen is dyed.

Erythr&obreve;s, p. & s.b. Plin. Frutex qui
& Rhus appellatur cuius folio coria­
rij in condensandis pellibus vtuntur.

Erythrotaton, Iun. A kind of fesant,
a bustard.

fishes or birdes with: meate for beastes:

tur caustica, que vim habent crustam

E T

Et, coniunct. And, as well, also, both.
Et pro id est, Plaut. pro Nam, vel quia,
Virg. pro Quamvis, and yet. pro
Tunc, Varr. pro Quod, si sequatur Si.
Et non, pro ne quidem. If so be that.

Etenim, p.b. For, because, that, and
also, semblablie: surelie: also, but, Ter.

Etenimvero, Plaut. For trulie.

Etesiæ, arum, m.g. Strab. Windes
blowing out of the East orderlie about the
Canicular daies.

Etesius, a, um, Lucret. Of or belon­
ging to such windes, Easterlie.

Ethale,* The smoke of Frankincense.

Ethanion, Athæn. A certaine ves­
sell of brasse, vsed among the Egyptians.

Ethesius, Plin. A morter stone.

Ethica, orum, Arist. A booke entrea­
ting of morall Philosophie.

Eth&ibreve;c&emacron;, es, vel Ethica, æ, f.g. p.l.
Morall philosophie.

Eth&ibreve;cus, a, um, p.l. Morall, belon­
ging to manners or behaviour, or that re­
presenteth and setteth them forth.

Ethmoides, Galen. The holes or is­
sues of the nose: the nosethrilles.

Ethmus, mi, m.g. * The midle bridge
of the nose.




Ethnearches,* A ruler of people.

Ethnearchia,* Principalitie.

Ethn&ibreve;cus, a, um, Ieron. A Gentile,
or Ethnike.

Eth&obreve;l&obreve;g&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. p.l. Quint. The
feate of counterfeiting mens manners.

Eth&obreve;l&obreve;gus, gi, m.g. p.l. He that with
voice & gesture expresseth mens maners.

Eth&obreve;poe&ibreve;a, & Ethopoeius, p.l. Aqui­
la, Idem quod Ethologia & Ethologus.

Et&ibreve;am, conjunctio, p.b. Also, more­
over, yea: yea further, yei: why, &c.

Etiam atq; etiam. Earnestly, diligently.

Etiamudum, Terent. As yet.

Etiamne. Therefore.

Etiamnum, Plaut. Yet, vntill then.

Etiamnunc. As yet, even to this time,
even now.

Etiamsi. Although.

Et vero etiam. i. atque etiam.

Etiam tum. Euen then, or euen to that
time.

Etsi, coniunct. Albeit, although, &
yet, suppose.

Etym&obreve;l&obreve;g&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. p. & s.b. True
saying, true exposition or reason.

Etymologicus, a, um, Gell. Pertai­
ning to, &c.

Etymologus,* He that searcheth out
the true interpretation of wordes.

Etymon, mi, n.g. Varro.  Idem quod
Etimologia.

open to all chaunces: at all aduentures, or
laid out that it may perish, be slaine, and
come to naught. Puer expositus, Plaut.
A foundling.

leape for ioye: to bubble, to boyle, or play at
a pot seething: to rise with sourges.

also that defameth.

Fasti, orum, m.g. Bookes or Calenders

rib. licebat tria verba fari, Do, Dico,
Addico, Ovid. Court, law, or lette daies:
daies wherein sutes are heard in West­
minster hall, &c.

Fatua, Macrob. The name of a god­
desse among the Romaines, to whome the
matrones did sacrifice in the night time
in a secret place: but the men were so
carefully kept there from, that it was pre­
sent death for them, but euen to looke or
peppe into the house.

Fax, f&amacron;cis, f.g. A torch, candle, fire­
brand, or other thing, which burning gi­
ueth light, a starre, a fagot. Also, a chiefe
authour, moouer, or further: one that
incenseth, stirreth, or raiseth: the affecti­
on, lust, or appetite of: vehemencie of mo­
tion, or spurre of: also, mariage, Sen. Fa­
cem in numptils præferre solebant,
sive ad observandum antiquam con­
suetudinem, quod non nisi noctu du­
ci novas nuptas à sponsis mos erat:
sive in honorem Cereris, quæ facem
in quærenda Proserpina gestaverat:
sive vt nova nupta ignem & aquaui,
quæ duo sunt in vita maximè neces­
saria, cum viro communicare videre­
tur. Etenim aqua quoque aspergi so­
lebat. vt casta puraque ad sponsum
duceretur.

F E

Febr&ibreve;c&ibreve;tans, tis, part. Colum. Sicke
of a feuer or ague.

Febr&ibreve;c&ibreve;to, as, Cels. To be sick of a fe­
ver.

Febr&ibreve;c&ubreve;la, æ, f.g. dim. A little or ea­
sie fever, or ague.

Febr&ibreve;c&ubreve;l&omacron;sus, a, um, Gell. That hath
or that is subiect to a great fever or heat.

Febriens, tis, part. Colum. Sicke
of a fever or ague.

Febrilis, le, Apul. Of or pertaining
to a fever.

F&ebreve;br&ibreve;o, is, &imacron;re, Cels. To haue a fever.


Febr&ibreve;f&ubreve;ga, æ, Iun. Feverworte.

Febris, &ibreve;s, f.g. A fever, an ague Fe­
bris intermittens, Iun. which goeth &
commeth. Quotidiana, Terent. A quo­
tidian. Tertiana, A tertian. Quarta­
na, Saturni filia, vel quadrimi circui­
tus, Iun. A quartane. Continua vel
continuata, Cels. Continuall. Conti­
nens, Iun. A continual, hot and burning
fever, whereof there be three kindes: the
first is Hymotonos or Acmasticos,
which is alwaies at one staie, when the
heate remaineth all alike in the course of
a fever. 2. Epacmasticos, or Anabati­
cos: which by little & little encreaseth,
the heat waxing greater. 3. Paracmasti­
cos, wherein the heate by little and little
deminisheth, vntill it ceaseth. Ardens,




Iun. vid. Caustus. Colliquans, Iun.
A verie hot burning fever, which voi­
deth the flesh, the fat, and the sound sub­
stance of the bodie melted with his heate
by the bellie. Typhodes, Iun. A burning
fever, rising of the inflaming of the liver
or the veines. Lipyria, Actuar. When
the outwarde partes are colde, and the in­
warde in a greate heat. Epiala, Iun. Fleg­
matike or rising of fleame that is sowre
and like glasse, wherein at one time hot
and cold is felt in euery parte of the body.
Hectica, Iun. Which is an vnnaturall
heat in the sound and firme partes of the
bodie, which hath gotten a resting place
in the substance of the heart. Radicalis,
vid. Marasmus. Horrida, semitertia­
na, vel hemitritæus, Iun. A halfe ter­
tian fever, a shaking ague, so called, be­
cause the greatest part of the fits thereof
is spent in shivering, on that daie speci­
allie, when the tertian and quotidian doe
meete togither.

Febr&ubreve;a, &omacron;rum, n.g. Iun. Sacrifices or
ceremonies for purging of soules: the feast
ordaie of all soules.

Febr&ubreve;&amacron;tus, a, um, * So purged.

Febr&ubreve;mar&ibreve;us, rij, m.g. The moneth
which is called Februarie.

Febr&ubreve;o, as, Varro. To purge soules by
sacrifice or prayer.

Febr&ubreve;us, dictus est Pluto, vel Dis
pater, inferorum deus, quòd ei men­
se Februario sacrificaretur, Macrob.

F&ebreve;c&ibreve;&amacron;les, lium, m.g. Varro. An he­
rold or officer at armes to denounce warre
or peace: an ambassador for that purpose,
which might be either a priest or an ora­
tour.

Fecialis, le. * That which was done
and ordeyned by those officers: pertaining
to herrauldes.

Fedus, pro Hedus, Fest.

F&ebreve;ro, fers, t&ubreve;li, l&amacron;tum, ferre. To beare,
carie, suffer, sustaine or abide: to breed or
bring forth: to leade vnto, to escape: to say,
shew, tell, or report: to receiue or take, to
haue, to giue, to make, to offer or pre­

to report, publish, or spread: to referre, to
propose: to serue, require, agree, or stand
with. Fertanimus, Ovid. It pleaseth me,
I am disposed, my minde desireth.

Feror, ferris, &c. To be caried or ledde,
to fall or be bent to, to runne, to goe, to be
troubled or dismayed, to be destracted.
Esse ferendo, Liv. To be fit and able to
sustaine and beare.

togither, that the skarre maie not growe
wide afterwardes: also, the lesser bone of
the shinne, Iun. and the nut of a steele
bow or crossebow, Iun.

F&imacron;do, is, sus sum, &ebreve;re. To trust, to
beleeue, to put ones hope or confidence in
a thing.

F&imacron;duo&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. Trust, confidence, af­
fiance, boldnes, hope, moste commonlie in
the good part, sometime in the euill, &c.
Fiduciam accipere, vpon ones faith &
promise so to receiue possession or charge
of a thing, as he will after restore it to the
partie againe, when it shall be required.

increase, to become notable.

Flor&ebreve;us, a, um, Plaut. Made, or full
of flowers.

Fl&omacron;r&ibreve;d&ubreve;lus, a, um, dim. Catull. A
litle flourishing, somewhat beautifull.

Flor&ibreve;dus, a, um, & Floridor. Gar­
nished with floures, fresh, lustie, flouri­
shing, liuelie, iollie.

Fl&omacron;r&ibreve;fer, & Floriger, a, um. That
beareth flowers.

Fl&omacron;r&ibreve;s&ebreve;r&ibreve;um, Fest. A holidaie among
the Romanes, so called, because on that
daie they caried eares of corne to the sa­
crifice.

Fl&omacron;r&ibreve;l&ebreve;gus, a, um, Ovid. That ga­
thereth floures.

Fl&omacron;r&ubreve;lentus, a, um. * Full of floures.

Flos, fl&omacron;ris, m.g. A floure, a budde,
bloome, or blossome: beautie, the moste
florishing, liuelie, and lustie time: the
chiefe or most principall: the sweet sent
or savour: also, Virginitie, Catull. also
Figures and ornaments of rhetorick. Vir­
gil vseth it for Lanugo. Also, simnel
meale, fine floure, Iun. also, the yellowe
seeds of a rose, Iun. Flos Adonidis, Iun.
The redde flower growing among corne,
some call it wilde poppie. Flos amoris,
Iun. Floure gentle. Flos Indieus, Iun.
Flower of Indie. Flos lactis, Iun. Creame.
Flos Liberi, Plaut. Fragrant wine Flos
Zachariæ, Iun. The blew bottle.

Flosc&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. dim. A litle flow­
er, beauty, ornaments of stile or rhetorick.

Flucti, pro Fluctus. Alciat.

Flucticulus, dim. à Fluctus, Apull.

Fluct&ibreve;fr&abreve;gus, a, um, Ex Fluctus &
Frango, Lucret. That breaketh the
waues.

Fluctigerus, a, um, quod fluctu ge­
ritur.

Fluct&ibreve;v&abreve;gus, a, um, ex Fluctus &
Vagor. Wandring on the water or sea:
tossed by the waues.

Fluct&ubreve;ans, tis, Floting, restlesse, vn­
certaine what to doe, doubtfull, loose.

Fluct&ubreve;matim, adverb. Non. In maner
of waues, flotingwise.

Fluct&ubreve;&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. Floting,
swimming, doubting, wauering, vncer­
taintie.

Fluct&ubreve;&amacron;tus, a, um, adject, Plin. Sha­
ken, tossed, mooued by the waues.

Fluct&ubreve;o, as, To rise in waues and sur­
ges, to be boisterous and rough, to waue
vp and downe as water doth, to thinke
now one thing, now an other: to be tossed,
troubled, or disquieted in minde: to wa­
uer, to lie in vncertaine state and conditi­
on: to behaue himselfe vnconstantlie, to




flote on the water.

Fluctuor, depon. Idem Curt.

Fluct&ubreve;&omacron;sus, a, um, Plin. Troublous,
vnquiet.

Fluctus, us, m.g. verb. à Fluo. A
floud or waue of water stirred by tempest:
a tempestuous storme, a raging sourge, bu­
sines or trouble of adversitie, a troublous
stirre, passion, or pang: disquietnes of
minde thorough anie affection, a violent
course or assault: a great multitude. Flu­
ctus decemanus, Iun. The tenth waue,
that is, a mightie, huge, violent, and great
waue or sourge.

Fluctus cæcus, Liv. A sudden or still
waue: a waue whose course is not seene or
knowne.

Fl&ubreve;ens, tis. Which floweth, flowing
or gushing out, spreading broad and in a­
bundance, running, loose, hanging downe:
also, giuen to sensualitie and pleasure.

Fl&ubreve;ent&ibreve;sonus, a, um, Catull. Where­
on the water roareth or maketh a great
noyse.

Fl&ubreve;entum, ti, n.g. Virg. A riuer or
streame.

Fluesco. To be resolved or relented.

Flu&ibreve;dus, a, um, Plin. Flowing: re­
lented, resolved, that is nothing strong,
without stifnes or strength, feeble, weake,
tender, soft and waterish: moist and thin.
Fluidus cruor, Ovid. Running or goare
blood.

Fl&ubreve;&ibreve;tans, tis, adject. Floting hither
and thither: hanging loose, variable, mu­
table.

Fl&ubreve;&ibreve;to, as, frequent. To flowe often,
or continuallie: to flote, hover, or swimme:
to waver.

Fl&umacron;men, &ibreve;nis, n.g. A great riuer,
a course, streame, or water. Also, an a­
boundant, plentifull or readie flowing of,
&c. Flumen vivum, vel perenne, Iun.
A running streame or water, having a
continuall course. Flumen item voca­
hulum est Iurisconsultorum in servi­
tutis constitutione.

Fl&umacron;m&ibreve;n&ebreve;us, a, um, Ovid. Of the wa­
ter or riuer.

Fl&umacron;m&ibreve;n&omacron;sus, a, um. Full of rivers.

Fl&ubreve;o, is, xi, ctum, &ebreve;re. To runne as
water doth, to proceed, or come of a thing:
to grow plentifullie or ouer rankelie: to
spread fare abroade: to slippe or slide, to
fall out, to passe awaie, to be of no conti­
nuance, to hang downe loose: to decaie, to
be flagging or feeble: to chaunce or come
to passe: to be full of, to be vtterlie giuen
to, or to swimme in. Also, to haue their
flowers, monethlie tearmes, or issue, Plin.

Fluoniam,  Iunonem mulieres co­
lebant, quòd eam sanguinis florem
in conceptu retinere putabant, Fest.

or a&emacron;ris, Arnob. The winde.

in the sea, or rather water that ebbeth and

Fl&umacron;ta, æ, f.g. Iun. A lamprey.

Fl&ubreve;v&ibreve;us, vij, m.g. A floude or riuer.

Flux&umacron;ra, æ, f.g. * Letcherie.

Flux&umacron;rus, a, um, part. Colum. That
will flow.

Fluxus, a, um, part nom. Loose, han­
ging wide and long, not trussed, large,
wide, flowing, vnconstant, vnstable, du­
ring but for a while, flitting, fraile, vn­
certaine, wavering, doubtfull. Also, a­
bandoned to all delitiousnes & lust, Suet.
Fluxus aeris, Iun. The winde.

mufler: also a garment to sit by the fire
in, Sen.

mould, a paterne or platte of an house or
other thing, is cheese vatte: also the stamp

beareth, &c. Forma calcei, Iun. The
last of a shoe, vide Ichnographia.

pith and grace. Also, dead. Varr.

Funct&ibreve;o. &omacron;nis. f. g. verb. à Fungor.
The exercise or executing of some charge
or office. Recipere functionem in suo
genere dicuntur res quadam. Paul.
When a man maie render and paie either
the same kinde, or the value of it, and not
the very same particular thing that be re­
ceived.

Functus, a, um, part. Which hath
exercised, or executed some office or
charge: ended, that hath bin, &c. and
now is past them.

Funda, æ, f. g. Virg. A sling, a casting
net, a satchell or purse like a nette to put
monie in, a bouget: a circle of gold where­
in stones are so set, that they maie be seene
both aboue and beneath. Funda balea­
ris, Virg. A sling.

Fundo, as. To found, to establihs, to
laie the foundation, to begin to build, to
make or build, to staie.

Fundo, is, f&umacron;di, f&umacron;sum, &ebreve;re. To cast
mettall: to powre out, shed, throw downe,
bring forth, yeeld, spread, scatter, or
stretch: to discomfite or vanquish, to giue
abundantlie, to speake much, to vtter &
shew: to slea.

Fund&ubreve;lus, Iun. A Gudgion.

Fundum, di, n.g. The bottome of a
thing, the floore.

Fundus, di, m.g. Lande or soyle: a
platte of ground with an house on it, a
farme in the countrie, a foundation: the
chiefe authour in doing of a thing. Fun­
dus ollæ, Iun. The bottome of a pot.

F&umacron;n&ebreve;bris, bre. Pertaining to funeralls
or mourning for the dead: funerall, mour­
ning, cruell, deadlie.

Funeralia, Iun. Funerall rites or ce­
remonies.

F&umacron;n&ebreve;ræ, arum, f.g. Serv. Women
mourners at burialls.

Digest. Pertaining to a buriall or fune­
rall.

F&umacron;n&ebreve;r&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Horat. Buri­
ed, or readie to be buried: killed.

F&umacron;n&ebreve;r&ebreve;us, a, um, Mart. Pertaining
to the dead bodie: funerall, vnfortunate,
vnluckie.

F&umacron;n&ebreve;ro, as, Plin. To burie.

F&umacron;nesto, as. To pollute with a deade
bodie.

F&umacron;nestus, a, um. Defiled or polluted
with touching of a dead bodie, pertaining
to deade bodies, that mourneth for the
dead, lamentable, mourning: mortall, cru­
ell, deadlie, abhominable, detestable, vn­
luckie.

F&umacron;n&emacron;tum, ti, n.g. Plin. A winding of
diuerse twigges of a vine one about a­
nother like a cord.

Fung&ibreve;b&ibreve;l&emacron;s res,* Things which be
numbered, weighed, or measured.

Fung&imacron;nus, a, um, Plaut. Of a mu­
shrome.

Fungor, &ebreve;ris, ctus sum, gi. depon.
To exercise an office or dutie, to execute,
to doe, to haue, or be in. Also to paie or
giue that which is due.

Fung&omacron;s&ibreve;tas, &amacron;tis, f.g. Plin. The hol­
lownesse of a mushrome or spunge: thin­

Fung&omacron;sus, a, um, Plin. Like a mu­
shrome or sponge: thinnesse and light­
nesse.

Fungus, gi, m.g. A tadstoole or mu­
shrome: also that which gathereth togi­
ther about candles about the snuffe: a
kinde of blasting or meazell in trees hap­
ning by heate or scorching of the sunne:
Also a dulhead, a dolte, a foole, Plaut.

40 Plin.

F&umacron;n&ibreve;r&emacron;pus, Politian. Fumipeus,
Apul.  vide Funambulus.

F&umacron;nis, is, m.g. Gell. A rope or corde. 
Funis anchorarius, Iun. An anchor
rope, the gable rope of an anchor. Funis
arborum, Iun. Ropeweede, weedebind.
Funis ductorius, Iun. The line corde or

F&umacron;nus, &ebreve;ris, n.g. A funerall, a buriall:
funerall exequies, solemnity of burying, a
dead corps, perishing, decaie. Funerum
arbiter vel destinator, Iun. The ma­
ster of funerall ceremonies, he that seeth
an order kept at burialls, euerie one goe­
ing in his due place. Iusta funerum. Ob­
sequies done for deade men: the duties of
burials, the necessary seruices thereto be­
longing.

Gest&ibreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. Suet.
A gesturing, a representing anie person

Gest&ibreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;tor, &omacron;ris, m.g. verb. Col.

Gesticulosus, a, um. Full of mouing,
busie in mouing.

Gest&ibreve;ens, tis, part. à Gestio. Leap­
ing and skipping for ioy, in gesture shew­
ing his ioy.

Gest&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. à Gero. An
exploiting or doing of a thing.

Gest&ibreve;o, is, &imacron;vi, &imacron;tum, &imacron;re. To shew af­
fection of minde by gesture of bodie, to ge­
sture, to leap or skippe for ioy, to triumph,
to desire gladlie, to delight much.

Gest&ibreve;to, as, frequent. à Gesto, Plaut.




To beare or weare oftentimes.

Gesto, as, frequent. à Gero, Plaut.
To beare long, to carie, beare, or weare.

Gestor, &amacron;ris. To be caried.

Gestor, &omacron;ris, m.g. verb. à GEro,Plau.
A porter, a bearer of burdens. Gestores
linguis, Plaut. Talebearers.

Gest&ubreve;&omacron;sus, a, um, Gell. Full of ge­
sture and busie moving.

Gest&umacron;rus, a, um, part. Suet. About to
beare, or put in execution and practise: a­
bout to doe the deede.

Gestus, a, um, part. Borne, done, mi­
nistred, executed, employed.

Gestus, us, m.g. Gesture or counte­
nance with moving of the body, demenour,
behaviour, a making of signes. Gestus
tutelæ, Vlp. The gouernement of a warde.

G&emacron;sum, si, n.g. Liv. A kinde of wea­
pons or dartes for the warre, which was
proper to the Frenchmen: a sword or wood­
knife.

Gethyum, Plin. A kinde of onyons for
sauce, hauing no heade, but a long roote
onelie.

Geum, i, n.g. Plin. The hearb called
Avens, herbenet, or hearb blessed, hares
eye.


G I

Gibber, ris, Iuv. vid. Gibbus,
bi.

Gibber. ra, rum, Varr. That hath a
crooked back, or bunch in anie place of the
bodie, that hath a round figure of a thing
imbossed.

Gibb&ebreve;r&omacron;sus, Digest. & Gibb&omacron;sus, a,
um, Cels. That is crooked or camell bac­
ked: that is crumpshouldered.

Gibbus, a, um, Cels. Bossed: the same
that Gibber.

Gibbus, bi, m.g. Iuv. A great bunch
or swelling.

G&ibreve;gant&emacron;us, a, um, Ovid. Of or belon­
ging to giants.

G&ibreve;gant&obreve;m&abreve;ch&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. * A battell
which giants prepared against the gods.

G&ibreve;gas, tis, m.g. A giant, a man or
woman of a huge bodie & stature, and as
it were a sonne of the earth.

Gigeria, &omacron;rum, n.g. Lucill. A meate
made of the garbage of pullen, and other
thinges.

Gigno, is, g&ebreve;n&ubreve;i, &ibreve;rum, &ebreve;re. To in­
gender or get, to make, conceiue, breede,
or cause: to bring forth, to grow, to begin
and first to bring vp, to invent, to make
or fashion.

Gignor, &ebreve;ris, pass. To be borne, be­
gotten, bred, ingendred, or caused.

Gilvus, a, um, Virg. Carnation or
flesh colour, the colour of a bricke being
halfe burned.

Gingeria, vid. Gigeria.

Ging&ebreve;r&ibreve;ator, girenator, vel  gingri
nator, oris, m.g. Fest. A minstrell or pi­
per.

Gingiber, vid. Z&imacron;nziber. Gingiber
hortense, Iun. Garden ginger, ditante.

Ging&ibreve;d&ibreve;um, Iun. The hearb tooth­
pick: some take it to be chervil.

Ging&imacron;va, æ, f.g. Plin. The gumme or
iaw wherein the teeth be set.

Ging&imacron;v&ubreve;la, æ, f.g. Apull. A little
gumme.

Gingr&imacron;na, æ, f.g. Iun. A short pipe
with a small and dolefull sund, and tooke
it name of Adonis, who was called Gin­
gris, or for that it counterfaiteth the noise
that geese doe make, or because this pipe
was made of the bones of geese.

Gingr&imacron;o, is, r&ibreve;j, &imacron;tum, &imacron;re, Fest. To
gagle or creake like a goose.

Gipsum, Isid. A kinde of stone like
vnto lime.

Girgillus, li, m.g. Isid. A reele to
winde thred on.

Giruli,* Smal fishes called Menowes.

Git, vel Gith, indecl. n.g. Plin. A­
pothecaries call it Nigellam romanam
vid. Melanthium.

Githago, Iun. Cockle or corne rose
growing among corne.

Gl&amacron;bella, æ, f.g. Capell. The space
ouer the nose betweene the browes.

pilde, or smooth.

Gl&abreve;d&ibreve;&amacron;t&omacron;r&ibreve;us, a, um. Pertaining to

Gl&abreve;d&ibreve;&amacron;t&umacron;ra, æ, f.g. Tacit. The acte
or feate of fighting with a sword.

Gl&abreve;d&ibreve;&obreve;lus, li, m.g. dim. Plin. A little
sworde, a woodknife, a dagger, a poina­

hearbes, hauing leaues like sedge or gla­

graphiarius, Iun. A penknife.

Perficus, Iun. vide Harpe.

Gland&amacron;r&ibreve;us, a, um, Var. That belongeth
to a mast.

Gland&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. Sipont. Feeding
of swine with mast, called pannage: a ga­
thering of acornes.

Gland&ibreve;fer, a, um. Bearing mast.

Gland&ibreve;um, dij, n.g. Plin. The part of
a Bore next the necke, the necke it selfe,
as other thinke.

Gland&ubreve;la, le, f.g. dim. à Glans,Plau.
A little acorne or mast: also a parte of a
swines necke wherein many kernels are:
it is also the same that Struma.

Gland&ubreve;l&omacron;sus, a, um, Colum. Full of
mast or kernels.

Glanis, or Glanus, Plin. A certaine
craftie fish, which biteth away the bate
and medleth not with the hooke.

Glans, dis, f.g. Mast of oke or other
trees, an acorne: sometime the fruit of a­
ny tree: a plummet, or pellet of leade, or o­
ther mettall: also a kernel growing be­
tweene the skinne and the flesh, the nut of
a mans yarde: a suppositorie made like an
acorn, & put into the fundament to cause
solublenesse. Glans Aegyptia. vide My­
robalanus.  Sardiana glans, Iun. A
chestnut. Calyx vel putamen glandis,
Iun. The cup or shel of the acorne. Iligna
glans, Horat. Holme bearies. glans
Ioyis, Iun. The chesten. Glans vnguen­
taria. The fruite of a tree much like Mi­
rice, out of the kernel whereof commeth
an humour vsed in pretious oyntments.

Gl&abreve;phyrus, ri, m.g. s.b. Mar. Iocund,
pleasant, trimme.

Gl&amacron;r&ebreve;a, æ, f.g. Grauel, sand: round
pible stones, drift sand, or sand mingled
with smal stones, such as lyeth on the
shoreside.

Gl&amacron;r&ebreve;&obreve;la, læ, f.g. dim. Plaut. Smal
grauel.

Gl&amacron;r&ebreve;&omacron;sus, a, um, Plin. Grauelly, ful
of grauel.

Glastinus color, Iun. Skie colour.

Glastum, sti, n.g. Plin. An hearbe o­
therwise called Isatis, in English Wad,
wherewith cloth is died blew: It was vsed
of the old Britaines to make their face
terrible against their enemies in warre, as
Cesar writeth. Also amber, which is yel­
low and bright, wherof they make beades,
Iun. vide glessum.

Glaucia,* The hearbe Chelido­
nia.

Glauc&ibreve;nus, a, um, Mart. Of the colour
Glaucus.




Glauc&ibreve;um, cii, n.g. Pli. The iuyce of

diseases of the eies. Also a felfare, or (as

Glauc&ibreve;to, as, Philom. To crie like a
whelpe.

Glauc&ibreve;&obreve;lus,* An horse with a waul
eie.

Glausicus, Plin. A certaine fish.

Glauc&omacron;pis, Homer. A man or wo­
man hauing eies like a Cat, or like the eies
of a Lion or Owle.

Glaucus, a, um, Virg. It is commonlie
taken for blew and graie, like the skie
with speckles as Cæsius is: but I thinke it
is rather red with brightnes, or firie red­
nes, as in the eies of a Lyon, & of an owle,
or young weethie braunches, and so is also
Cæsius colour: in horses it is a baie. Also
a certaine fish, Plin.

Glaux, cos, Pli. An owle: also an hearb
named Trifoly.

Gracilitudo, Accius, Idem.

Gr&abreve;d&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. A forme of spea­

Gr&abreve;dus, us, (& uis, Non.) m.g.
A geese or stoppe, a staires, a round in a
ladder: a degree in consanguinitie: a de­
gree or estate of honour: an occasion,
meane, entrie, or waie to a thing: a pace
of two foote and an halfe. Formicinus
gradus, Iun. A short and thick pace like
a pismire. Testudineus vel lentus,
Plaut. A slow pase. gallatorius, Plaut.
A long striding pase, as it were vpon
stiltes.

getting or plaistering: morter.

Gyrgathus, Iun. A place or chamber

Hæmatites, tæ, m.g. Plin. A blud
stone, so called, not so much for that it stan­
cheth bloode, as that it seemeth to repre­
sent the fashion of a thing dried and con­
gealed: beeing burnt it is like simple or
red vermilion.

Hæmorrh&obreve;is, idis, f.g. Cels. A dis­
ease in the fundament like to teates or
wartes by the swelling of the vaines, out
of the which issueth bloode called hemor­
rhoides or piles: also a serpent, of whome
a man beeing striken bleedeth to death.

an 100. feete, &c. vid. Centipes.

& perturbatione. A voice of blaming,

countrie, and returned at night.

Herc&ubreve;l&amacron;nus, or Herculeus nodus. *
A strong knotte, hard to vndoe: also a
hard and subtile question, or intricate
doubt: a knot that maydens were girt
with, which the husbande did the firste
night vndoe in token of good successe in
generation of children.

Herculana pars, vel Herculeus
questus,* The tenth parte of ones sub­
stance in the olde time vsed to be offered to
Hercules.

H&emacron;r&obreve;&ibreve;na, næ, & Her&omacron;is, &ibreve;dis, f.g.
Iun. A Princesse, Dutchesse, Countesse, or

H&emacron;r&omacron;s, &omacron;is, m.g. A noble gentleman
that for the loue of vertue sustaineth
great labours and trauailes: he that doth
things for excellencie aboue mans condi­
ons: a passing excellent man in vertue &
noblenesse: halfe a God.




H&emacron;r&omacron;um, i, n.g. A monument or
tombe erected to the remembrance of
some noble mans excellent vertues.

H&emacron;r&omacron;us, a, um, Propert. Of or belong­
ing to a noble man.

Herpacantha, Iun.  vide Acanthus.

Herpes, Iun. A kind of S. Anthonies
fire, whose heat causeth little blisters or
wheales to arise, which creeping on doth
fret the skin: some call it the shingles, some
the running worme, some wildfire. Also a
kind of beast whereby those sores be hea­
led, Plin. Herpes exedens, Iun. An ea­
ting or consuming sore, quicklie pearsing
to the very bones, and devouring the bo­
die: the wolfe. Herpes miliaris, vel pu­
stulosus, Iun. Smal blisters not vnlike
millet seede, rising vpon the vppermoste
skin: wheales, pimples.

H&ebreve;rus, ri, m.g. A Lord or master.

smelling more in the night then in the day.
vide Viola lutea.

Hesp&ebreve;rus, ri, m.g. The euening starre:
the euening, or euentide.

Hesp&ebreve;r&umacron;go, inis, f.g. Sen. 
Idem.

Hexapala, or Hexaplum.* An ex­

Hex&abreve;ph&obreve;rum, ri, n.g. Mart. A litter

Hiacinthus, idem quod Delphi­
num, Diosc.

H&ibreve;ans, tis, part. sive nom. Gaping, o­
pening, greedie, desirous: vnpleasantlie
meeting in composition, not wel compact
or ioyned.

H&ibreve;asco, is, &ebreve;re, Cato. To gape, open, or
spread as a flowre doth.

H&ibreve;&amacron;to, as, Plaut. To gape much and
often.

H&ibreve;&amacron;tus, us, m.g. verb. A gaping or
wide opening of the mouth or of the earth:
an yawning: an vnpleasant open
sounde.

H&ibreve;b&emacron;r&imacron;s, idis, f.g. An hearbe, which
Ruellius thinketh to be Lepidium sil­
vestre, the herbarists call it Valeriana
pratensis.

Hibericum, vide Androsæmum.

Hiberna, vel hibernacula, Iun. Pla­
ces wherin souldiers do keep in winter for
the avoyding of extreame cold.

Hiberum argentum, Var. Fine, or ve­
ry good siluer.

H&ibreve;berus color, Iun. Swart, browne, or
murrey colour.

Hibiscum, n.g. vel Hibiscus, sci, m.
g. Plin. Galen calleth it wild mallows: it




is called also Althæa, marsh mallow, or
water mallow: Virg seemeth to take it
for a kind of bulrush or young shootes.

Hibris, idis, com. g. Pli. A wild hog
ingendered betweene a wilde bore and a
tame sowe.

Hic, hæc, hoc, pronomen demonst.
He, shee, this, that, such a one.

Hic, adverb. loci & temporis. Here,
in this place, here in this matter: also
then.

Hicce, hæcce, hocce, Terent. This
or that.

Hicc&ibreve;n&ebreve;, hæccine, hoccine. Is this
he here? Is this fellow he? this, that, such.

H&ibreve;&ebreve;r&amacron;c&ibreve;um, Iun. the hearbe called
hawkeweede, or sowthistle. Hieracium
minus, vide Ambubeia.

H&ibreve;&ebreve;ra picra, Isid. A certaine confe­
ction to purge choler.

An agreement made betweene two pri­

countrie. hospitium publicum, Liu.
An agreement made openly betweene
diuerse peoples or townes for mutuall en­
tertainement, or receiuing and lodging
either of other. It is also the same that
Xenodochium.

Hy&abreve;cinth&ibreve;a, p.b. Ieron. Were so­

Hy&abreve;cinthus, thi, m.g. p.b. Plin. A
pretious stone called a Iacinct: also a pur­

or hath leaues like a porret, an handfull
high, and a round roote, it groweth much
in woodes. Also the red, blew, or yellow
lillie, Iun.

Hyæna, æ, f.g. p.b. Plin. A beast of
all other the most subtil: it is like a woolfe
with a mane like an horse, which com­
ming in the night vnto sheepheards hou­
ses will counterfaite mans voice, and by
harkening learne ones name, and cal him
forth to the end to devour him: a certaine
beast supposed to be knowne by the smell
of his dung, commonlie called civet.

tenor in voce novissimus & accutissi­
mus.

Hyperm&emacron;ter.* A syllable abounding
in a verse.

Hyp&ebreve;r&obreve;cha, Scævol. An abundance
or overplus.

Hyperthyrum, Vitruv. The vpper
poste in a doore iust ouer against the
threshold: the brow peece: the transam or
lintell of a doore.

Hyphear, Pli. A kinde of clammy lime.

Hyphen,* When diuerse wordes be
pronounced vnder one accent.

Hypn&amacron;les, f.g. Isid. Adders, which
stinging a man do make him die sleeping.

Hyp&obreve;caustum, sti, n.g. p.b. A stoue
or hote house.

Hyp&obreve;chondr&ibreve;a. Iun. The forepart of
the bellie and sides about the short ribbes,
and about the navill, vnder which lieth
the liver and spleane.

Hyupochoriasis,* A disease in horse
eies by an humour falling out of the head.

Hypochryma,* A grate humour
couering the eie.

Hypochysis, sive hypochyma, Ae­
gin. A disease in the eyes called suffusio.

Hypocistis, Plin. Quiddam est ma­
li punici cytinis non dissimile, sub ci­
sto frutice nasceus.

Hypocr&ibreve;sis, is, f.g. Bud. Simulati­
on, hypocrisie, fained holines.

Hypocr&ibreve;ta, Bud. An hipocrite, he
that counterfaiteth an other mans person.

Hypod&emacron;sis, & Hypodema,* A shoe.

Hypodiaconus, Isid. A subdeacon.

Hyp&obreve;d&ibreve;dasc&abreve;lus, li, m.g. p.b. Non.
An vsher or substitute in teaching.

Hypodorius, Isid. est accentus vel
tenor in voce omnium gravissimus.

Hyp&obreve;dytes, t.l. Ieron. An inward
garment: proper to the high priests.

Hypogæum, gæi, n.g. Iun. A place
vnder the ground, arched over head: a
cellar, a vault.

Hypog&emacron;sum, vid. Sedum maius.

Hypoglossida,* Little pills made of




Phisitians to hold vnder the tongue to the
nether part of the mouth.

Hypoglossis, Iun. The little flesh
that fasteneth the tongue to the nether
parte of the mouth.

Hypoglossum, vid. hippoglossum.

Hypoglottion, vid. hippoglottion.

Hypomn&emacron;ma, tis, n.g. & Hypom­
nematum, ti. An exposition or com­
ment: a register or note of actes done.

Hypomochlium, Iun. A roller or
round trunchion laid vnder a great stone
or peece of timber the most easilie to liste
it with leavers from the place it lieth.

Hypopia, Iun. The bones that be vn­
der the eyes.

Hypopion,* Livor est sub oculis
contingens, à sanguine compressis
venulis exeunte, & sub cute per­
manente.

Hypopodium, dij, n.g. * A fooote­
stoole.

Hypopyon,* est oculi morbus,
quum pus sub carnea tunica colli­
gitur.

Hyposarca,* A kinde of the dropsie.

Hyposclinum,* The hearbe Love­
athe.

Hyposphagma. Galen. Where the
skinne of the eye by some stroke is so hurt,
that the blood sodenly spreadeth over the
eye.

Hypost&abreve;sis, eos, f.g. * A substance:
also residence in an vrine flitting toward
the bottome of the vrine.

Hyp&obreve;th&emacron;ca, cæ, f.g. p.b. A pledge, a
gage.

Hyp&obreve;th&emacron;c&amacron;r&ibreve;us, a, um, p.b. Digest.
Pertaining to a pledge or gage.

Hyp&obreve;th&ebreve;sis, is, vel eos, f.g. p.b. An
argument, matter, or cause wherevpon
one should argue or dispute.

Hypothicos,* A linnen rotchet.

Hypothyra vel hypothyrodes, *
The roome or place where the dore is.

Hypothyrum, Vitruv. A threshold
or groundsel: also the wide opening, or
open widnes of the dore.

Hypotrachelium, Vitruv. That part
of the shaft or maine bodie of the piller
which is vnder Astralagus.

Hypotrimmata, Iun. Conflicts, and all
kind of drie dainties made of sugar, such
as be serued at womens lying in.

Hypothytes, vid. Hypodites.

Hypozygia,* All drawing cattell.

Hypozeuxis,* A figure, when euery
clause hath his proper verbe.

Hysginus color, Iun. A colour like
vnto scarlet: a light red, in a horse it is cal
led a bright bay.

Hyssopite vinum, Plin. Wine made
with Hysope.

Hyss&omacron;pum, n.g. & Hyss&omacron;pus, pi, f.g.
Colum. The hearb Hysope.

Hyst&ebreve;r&abreve;. Latinè vocantur Secun­
dæ. Sunt autem folliculi quibus in­
fans involutus prodit in lucem, &
quicquid infantem ex vetero sequi­
tur.

Hyst&ebreve;r&ibreve;cæ. Dicuntur mulieres quæ
vteri suffocatione laborant, in qui­
bus sensum pulsumque per interval­
la nullum, aut cerrv`e perexiguum per­
cipere possumus.

Hysteralgia, æ, f.g. Paine of the belly.

Hysterologia, æ, f.g. An altering of
the order of speach, by placing that after
which should come before.

Hysteron proteron. Idem.

Hystrix, icis, f.g. Plin. A little beast
with specked prickes on his backe, which
he will cast of, and hurt men with them: a
porkepine.





I A

IImperativus verbi Eo, is, Te­
rent. Goe.

II&abreve;cens, tis, part. Lying, slow,
sluggish, sicke: situate: base, faint,
abiect, in pore estate, in aduersitie.

I&abreve;c&ebreve;o, es, &ubreve;i, &emacron;re. To lie, remaine, or a­
bide: to be situate, to extend out or be of
length: to lie vnknowen, to be dead or
calme: to be contemned and naught set by,
to be vile and of no price: to be confoun­




ded or conuinced: to haue no life or quick­
nesse.

Iacinthina vestis, est aerio colore
resplendens, Isid.

I&abreve;c&ibreve;o, is, &emacron;ci, iactum, &ebreve;re. To throw,
cast, hurle, or shoote: to speake, vtter, or
publish abroad: to lay, make, set moue, or
giue.

Iactans, tis, adiect. ex part. Horat.
Casting, boasting, cracking, auanting.

Iacanter, adverb. Tacit. Bragging­
ly, proudly, with ostentation.

Iactantia, æ, f.g. Quint. Craking,
bragging, auaunting, glorious praysing.

Iactantior, compar. à Iactans, Ho­
rat.

Iact&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. Liv. A swin­
ging or wagging, a tossing, tumbling, or
shaking, a mouing or gesturing, a casting,
a boasting, craking, or auaunting: a
spreading abroad.

Iact&amacron;tor, &omacron;ris, m.g. verb. Quint. A
craker or boaster, a glorious person making
auaunt of his owne praise.

Iact&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Tossed hither
and thither, driuen from coast to coast:
cast: conuersant, exercised.

Iact&amacron;tus, us, m.g. verb. Plin. A tos­
sing, casting, mouing, flickering or clap­
ping.

Iact&ibreve;to, as, Liv. To cast or spread: to
vaunt or brag often.

Iacto, as, Virg. To throw, to wagge,
shake, mooue, or tosse: to reuolue, to cast or
tosse in ones minde: to vexe: to brag and
glorie, to auaunt, to speake vainly: to send
or cast forth.

Iactor, aris. To be driuen, and tossed
to and fro: to be vexed and tormented, to
be commonly talked.

Iact&ubreve;&omacron;s&emacron;, adverb. Braggingly, boa­
stingly, insolentlie.

Iact&ubreve;&omacron;sus, a, um, vide Iactans.

Iact&umacron;ra, ræ, f.g. Salust. Losse, hurt, de­
caie: properly things cast away out of a
ship in time of tempest.

Iactus, a, um, part. à Iacior. Cast,
laid, throwne.

Iactus, us, m.g. verb. à Iacio. A
throw, hurle, or cast: a casting of wares
into the sea in time of a tempest: also a
cast or draught with a net.

I&abreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;b&ibreve;lis, le. Ouid. That may be
hurled or cast, fit to be throwne.

I&abreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;men, Iaculamentum,  vide
Iaculatio.

I&abreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. Quint. A
darting, a casting.

I&abreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;tor, &omacron;ris, verb. He that hur­

I&abreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;t&omacron;r&ibreve;us, a, um, Digest.That

I&abreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;trix, &imacron;cis, f.g. verb. Ovid. Shee

I&abreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Virg. Which

I&abreve;c&ubreve;lo, as, Claud.  vide 
Iaculor.

I&abreve;c&ubreve;lor, &amacron;ris, depon. Iuv. To shoote or
cast farre, to dart, to fling out.

I&abreve;c&ubreve;lum, li, n.g. Any thing that may
be shot or cast farre: a light Iaueling: also
a casting net, Plaut.

I&abreve;c&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. Plin. A serpent that
lieth vnder trees, and suddenly springing
out with a marueilous violence perceth
any beast which happilie passeth by.

Iam, adverb. temporis. Now, yet,
moreouer, ouer and beside this, further­
more: incontinent, forthwith, by and by,
ere is belong: now at the length, then:
hence forth, now hereafter: alreadie: euer­
since.

Iamdiu. Long agoe, now a long time: a
great while.

Iamd&umacron;dum. A pretie or good while
since: now late: long since.

Iamiam, Plin. By and by, forthwith,
now at this time: euen now: for this time.

Iam inde. Euen from, or since, now
from henceforth, lately.

Iam nunc. Euen now.

Iam olim. Long since.

Iampridem, Long since, lately: also
incontinent, by and by, Lucan.

Iam primum, Terent. Euen now and
neuer before: first and formest.

Iam tum. Euen then, or euen that
same.

Iam vero. Now as touching, that
now is.

Iam vsq; Euer since.




Iamb&emacron;us, a, um, p.b. Made of Iam­
bick feete.

Iambicus, a, um, Idem.

is called Iambus, for that it is fit and apt
for reuiling, and euill speeches.

Ianeus, Fest. pro Ianitor.

I&amacron;n&ubreve;&abreve;l, Fest. A kind of cake sacrifi­

nuarie.

Ianus, vid. Amphibrachis.

I B

Iber&ibreve;ca, cæ, f.g. p.l. Quint. An

Iberis, or Hiberis, Iun. An hearb

Ibex, p.b. Iun. A kinde of wilde
goate, and supposed to be that which they
call the evecke.

Ibi, aduerb. in loco, p.b. There: then:
when that was done.

Ibidem, p.b. There, in the same place:
in the same thing.

Ibis, is, vel idis, f.g. p.l. A birde in
Egypt which is high, and hath stiffe legs,
and a long bill: they porfit much the coun­
try in killing the serpentes which are
brought out of Libia by southeren windes.

Ibus, pro iis, Non.


I C

Ichneum&omacron;n, &obreve;nis, m.g. Plin. A
ratte of India of the greatnesse of a catte,
which creepeth into the Crocodiles mouth
when he gapeth, and eating his bowells
killeth him: it is also a kinde of waspes.

Ichneuta, Nican. Idem.

Ichnobates, Ovid. Treader or tra­
cer.

Ichn&obreve;gr&abreve;ph&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. Vitr. A

uerie roome.

Ichreiasinus,* The hearbe Mario­
ram.

Ichthylobalus,* A fisher.

Ichthy&obreve;colla, læ, f.g. s.b. Plin. A fish
of whose skin water glewe is made, water
glewe it selfe.

Ichthy&obreve;ph&abreve;gus, gi, m.g. s.b. Pli. He
that eateth onely fish.

Ict&ebreve;rus, ri, m.g. Plin. A bird, which if

Icunculæ, arum, f.g. Suet. Mammets

I D

Id, pronom. ab Is. That Id quòd, pro
ideo quòd.

Idcirco, vel Iccirco, coniunct.
Therefore, for that cause, for all that.

Id&ebreve;a, æ, f.g. p.l. The figure conceiued
in imagination, as it were a substance per
petuall, beeing as a patterne of all other
sort or kinde: as of one seale proceedeth
many printes, so of one Idea of man pro­
ceedeth many thousands of men.

Idem, eadem, idem, p.l. in masc. in
neutro breui. The same, the verie or
selfe same, all one, like. Idem est ac. It
is all one, or a like thing to, &c. and, &c.
it is euen as though.

Ident&ibreve;dem, adverb. p.l. Estsoones:
now and then among, euer now and then,
euer and anon: often, or diuerse times
with a space betweene, sundry times one
after another.

Id&ebreve;o, coniunct. p.b. Therefore, for
that cause. Ideo quòd. Because that.

Ideus dactilus. Isid. A stone in
Creta of an iron colour, like a mans
thumbe.

Idilion, Isid. A poets worke consisting
of few verses.

Idiographæ literæ,* A priuate
mans letter.

Idiographum, phi, n.g. * A priuate
writing.

Idi&omacron;ma,* A proper forme of speech.

Idiopathia, æ, f.g. * The proper passi­
on of a disease.

Idi&omacron;ta, vel Idiotes, tæ, m.g. A
man or woman vnlearned: one that is not
very fine witted, an ideot: also one out of
office.

Idiotismus, Sen.  vide Idioma.

Id&omacron;l&obreve;latra, æ, com. g. p.l. Isid. An
idol worshipper, an idolater.

Id&omacron;l&obreve;latr&imacron;a, æ, f.g. * Worshipping of
idols, idolworship, idolatrie.

Id&omacron;l&obreve;poe&ibreve;a,* A figure, whereas we
bring in a knowne person, but yet dead,
and not able to speake.

Id&omacron;l&obreve;thys&ibreve;a, siæ, f.g. p.l. * Offering
to images.

Id&omacron;l&obreve;thytum, ti, n.g. p.l. That which
is sacrificed, or dedicated vnto idols.

Id&omacron;lum, li, n.g. p.l. An idol, an image:
also a vaine vision, a false imagination,
Plin.

Id&omacron;n&ebreve;a, orum, Tacit. Fit places.

Id&omacron;n&ebreve;&emacron;, adverb. p.b. Aptly, conue­
niently, fitly.

Idoneior, compar. Vlp. More fit &
conuenient.

Id&omacron;n&ebreve;us, a, um, p.b. Apt, meete,
proper, conuenient, due: able, sufficient:
profitable.

Idulis, Fest. A sheepe offered to Iu­
piter in all the Ides.

Id&ubreve;o, as, Gell. To deuide.

Id&ubreve;s, &ubreve;um, &ibreve;bus, f.g. The ides of euery
moneth, so called because they deuide the
moneth: the eight day after the Nones: in
March, May, JUne, & October the eight
following the first seauen daies: in other
monethes the eight dayes following the
first fiue daies.

Id&ubreve;us, a, um, Gell. Deuided.

I G

Ig&ibreve;tur, conjunct. p.b. Therefore:

Ignaria Columba, Gaza. vid. Py­
ralis.

Ignarus, a, um. Which knoweth not,

Ign&amacron;v&emacron;, adverb. Cowardlie, lither­

Ign&amacron;v&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. Cowardnes, lither­

Ign&amacron;vus, a, um. Cowardous, idle,

vnprofitable, that hath no force or vertue.

Ign&ebreve;o, es, &emacron;re. To burne.

Ignescens, tis, part. Plin. Of the
colour of fire, beginning to kindle like a
fire, increasing or waxing hot.

Ignescitur, pro ignescit, Laber.

Ignesco, is, &ebreve;re. To be on fire, to
burne, to fire, to be inflamed: to cast a
brightnes and colour of fire: to waxe hot,
to be verie angrie.

Ign&ebreve;us, a, um. Fierie, bright or shi­
ning like fire: burning.

Ign&ibreve;&amacron;r&ibreve;um, rij, n.g. Plin. Any thing
out of which fire maie be quickly striken,
tynder or touchwood: a fire steele where­
with to strike fire out of a flint. Iguia­
rius lapis, * A flint stone to strake fire
withall. Fomes igniarius, Iun. The
match to keep in fire.

Ign&ibreve;c&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. dim. A sparke
of fire, an instinction, a motion, a pric­
king forward.

Ign&ibreve;fer, ra, rum. That beareth fire.

Ign&ibreve;fl&ubreve;us, a, um, Claud. Full of fire.

Ign&ibreve;g&ebreve;na, æ, com. g. Ingendred by
or in fire.

Ign&ibreve;pes, &ebreve;dis, Mart. That hath fie­
rie feete.

Ign&ibreve;p&obreve;tens, tis, adject. Virg. Migh­
tie by fire.

Ignis, is, m.g. Fire: loue, an harlot:
lightning: occasion or matter: Ignes
marini, Arnob. vid. Dioscuri. Ignes
missiles, Iun. Squibs, balls of fire, and
such like devises of fireworke hurled vp
in the aire or cast to and fro, in a triumph
or publique ioy. Ignis silvestris, Fern.
vid. Phlyctæna. Specularis, vel spe­
culatorius, Iun.A burning beacon or
the fire of a beacon. Trisulcus. Ovid.
Lightning. Sacer, Plin. vid. Erysipe­
las.

Ign&imacron;sp&ibreve;c&ibreve;um, cij, n.g. Plin. Diuina­
tion by looking in fire.

Ign&ibreve;t&amacron;b&ubreve;lum, li, n.g. Iun. A bedde
panne or a warming pan: a firepan made
of earth or iron, such as is vsed in barbers
shoppes and others, in colde weather.

and strong.

Immusculi, li, m.g. Fest. A kinde of
birde, called of some Regulus, of others
Ossifraga.

Immussulus, vel vt alij scribunt Im­
musulus, vel  immustulus, li, m.g. Fest.
A bird saith Fest of the kind of eagles: the
soothsaiers (saith Plin.) take it diuerselie:
some for the chicke of a Vulture, some for
a yong Eagle, before his taile be white:
this birde alway gaue signification of good
lucke: it is also called Sanqualis & Ossi­
fagra.

I N

In, præ. serviens ablat. casui. In: also
with, at, to, among, on, within: also be­
tweene, Virg. In promptu. Quickely,
manifest, open and euident. In propin­
quo, in proximo, Liv. At hand. In pub­
lico, & in publicum. Abroad. In re præ­
senti, Plaut. Now beeing present, in the
place. In triduo. Plaut. Within those
three daies. In vicino, Plin. Here by.

In præp. serv. accus. cas. In, into, a­
gainst, towardes, for, vpon, by, to, after,
euen to, instead of, as, vntill, whiles, ac­
cording to: In ante. Till. In diem, Ter.
for a great while to come, for a day space,
from hande to mouth. In immensum,
Plin. Exceedingly much, out of measure.
In obliquun, Liv. Travers, ouerthwart­
lie. In orbem, Liv. Round, by course, one
after an other. In pedes nasci, Plin. To
be borne with the feet forward. In poste­
rum, & in posteritatem. Hereafter,
henceforth, for the time to come. In prin­
cipibus. One of the speciall or chiefe. In
rem presentemvenire. To make or take
view of the place or land in controversie:
liuelie, plainelie, and perfectlie to make
to vnderstand, and as it were presentlie
to see it. In tantum, Plin. So often, so far,
or so much. In totum, Plin. Whollie. . In
viros. Plaut. To euerie man. In vngué.
Cels. Perfectlie, exactlie.

Inabruptus, a, um, p.b. Stat. Not
violated, not broken, or that cannot be
broken.

perfect.

In&amacron;nis, ne, & Inanissimus, a, um.

Indes, &ibreve;cis, com. g. He that accu­
seth or appeacheth an other man: also he
that to escape punishment or fore some re­
warde discloseth the conspiracie, where­
nvto he was made priuie: It is also the
forefinger, a touchstone to trie gold & sil­
uer also the table of a booke wherby cer­
taine chapiters or notes be found, a sum­
marie, an innentorie of ones goods: a to­
ken, signe, shew, vtter, or guide, the in­
scription or title of a booke. Index char­
ta, Lod. Viv. The triumph, the turned
carde trump. Victoriæ indices, Iun.
Letters of victorie obteined against the
enemie.

Insisto, is, st&ibreve;ti, stitum, ere. To staie,
leane, or insist von: to rest, stoppe, or stand
still: to pause as he would speake no more:
to persist, to continue: to enforce, to labour
earnestlie, to imploy, to settle himselfe, to
goe about, to pursue diligentlie, to abide
fast and firmelie: to endeavour, to prouoke
or solicite: to goe, to be earnest with or vp­

wholesomenes: furie or exceeding follie.

Intempestas, atis, f.g. Plin. Idem.

Intempest&imacron;v&emacron;, adverb. Vntimely,
vnseasonably: out of due time and season.

Intempest&imacron;vus, a, um. Out of due
time and season, vnseasonable, vnmeasu­
rable, disordered, vnruly: also that gi­
ueth a signe of some ill to come, Plin.

Intempestus, a, um. Quiet and still:
without noise or trouble.

Intendendus, a, um, Teren. That is to
be marked, intended, purposed, or bended.

Intendens, tis, part. sive nom. In­
tending, purposing, bending, indeuouring,
enclining or beginning to.

Intendo, is, di, sum, & tum, ere. To
bend, stretch, or retch: to streine, to knit or
tie streight: to take heede or see to, to looke
diligently and earnestly on, to marke and
obserue diligently, to set, settle, giue,
apply, or fixe: to enforce and straine to doe
the vttermost, to goe about or endeauour,
to intend, to faine, to thinke: to increase or
augment: to laie abroad, to sette nettes: to
pretend or purpose: to point with: to con­
tinue: to accuse or laie to ones charge, to
declare and shew: to goe.

Intens&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. verb. Colum. A
streining, retching, stretching, or bending:
diligence: a will, a meaning, a minde, an
intension, a phantasie, a purpose: the ear­
nest consideration of the minde: the ben­
ding or setting the minde of a thing: dili­
gent harkning, attentiuenes. Also the pro
position laying the fault to ones charge,
Quint. The action or demaund of the
plantife in iudgement charging the de­
fendant.

Intensus, a, um, part. sive nom. Set
or fixed, intentiue, diligently, bent or set
to a thing, earnestly fixed: readie and ap­
pointed, earnest and vehement, attentiue
and diligent: earnestly bent and occupied:
stretched, retched, wrested, bended, strai­
ned: inhaunced or augmented, set forth or
prooued to the vttermost.

Intentans, tis, part. ab Intento,
Suet. Stretching out, laying on.

Intent&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. Sen. A
menacing with the fingers holden as they
shoulde doe hurt.

Intent&amacron;tus, a, um, adiect. Virg. Not
assaied, not tried or prooued.

Intent&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Liv. Ready
drawne and bent to strike.

Intent&emacron;, intentiùs, intentissimè, ad­
verb. Liv. Diligentlie, with earnest con­
sideration, earnestlie.

Intentio, onis, f.g. verb. ab Inten­
do, vid. Intensio.

Intentissimè, adverb. Lamprid.

Intentissimus, a, um, Quint. Verie
earnestlie.

Intento, as, frequent. ab Intendo.
To manace or threaten, to stretch out of­
ten: to put or lay out as one doth his hand,
to shake at one, to charge.

Intentus, us, m.g. A spreading or
casting abroad, a retching.

Intentus, Intentior,  & c. vid. Intensus.

Int&ebreve;p&ebreve;o, es: & Intepesco, is, &ubreve;i, e­
re, Stat. To waxe luke warme.

Inter, præp. serv. accus. Betweene,
among: in, or within, at. Inter se. One a­
nother, or one from another, togither.

Int&ebreve;ralb&ibreve;co, as, Plin. To incline some­
what to the colour of white.

Int&ebreve;r&amacron;nea, orum, n.g. Plin. The bow­
els, entrales, or inwards of man or beast.




Int&ebreve;r&amacron;resco, is, ere. To be dried vp, or

Interb&ibreve;bo, is, bi, tum, ere, Plaut. To

Interb&ibreve;to, as, Plaut. To come in the

Interc&abreve;l&amacron;ris, re, & Interc&amacron;larius, a,
um. Put or set betweene. Dies interca­
lares, Plin The odde daies of the leape
yeare. Intercalaris annus, Plin. The
leape yeare. Intercalares calendæ. The
calends of March, because in the latter
end of Februarie, that is reputed as the
Calends of March; the odde daies of the
leape yeare were added. Intercalares
versus, Serv. The foote or refret of the
dittie: a verse often interlaced.

Interc&abreve;l&amacron;rium, rij, The time which is
set or put betweene, that the yeare may
agree with the course of the sunne.

Interc&abreve;l&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. Macro.
A putting between of a moneth or dayes,
as in leape yeare.

Intercalatus, a, um. Put or set be­
tweene: deferred.

Interc&abreve;lo, as. To set or put betweene,
as a day or yeare, to interlace, to deferre.

Interc&abreve;p&emacron;do, inis, f.g. A space or
pause, a space of time or place betweene:
a respit, a delay.

Intercarpens, tis, part. Lucan.
Holding or taking by the midale, or in the
middest.

Interc&emacron;do, is, ssi, ssum, ere, ex Inter
& Cedo. To goe, come, or passe betweene,
and is referred to time or place: to happen
or chance: to make intercession: to let, hin­
der, forbid, prohibite, or withstand: to be
suretie or vndertake to answere ones
debte.

Interceptio, onis, f.g. verb. ab In­

Interceptor, oris, m.g. verb. Liv.
He that preuenteth in taking, a forestal­

Interceptus, a, um, part. Preuented
or surprised, forestalled, encroched.

Intercess&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. verb. A pro­
hibition, withstanding, gainsaying by his
voice negatiue, or stepping in to let a
matter that it proceed not.

Intercessor, oris, m.g. verb. He that
letteth or withstandeth a matter that it

Intercessus, us, m.g. verb. Valer.

an intreating.

Interc&ibreve;do, is, &imacron;di, c&amacron;sum, idere, ex
Inter & Cado. To decay or perish, to

Interc&imacron;do, is, &imacron;di, c&imacron;sum, ere, ex In­

Intercilium, lij, n.g. Isid. The space

Intercinctus, a, um, Plin. Interla­

Interc&ibreve;no, is, &ubreve;i, entum, ere, ex In­

Interc&ibreve;p&ibreve;o, is, &emacron;pi, eptum, ere. To

intercept, to take vp before, by the way, or
in the meanewhile: to forestal, to encroch,
to dash, or put out of.

Interc&imacron;s&emacron;, adverb. By choppes or

sells: with short clauses.

Interc&imacron;s&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. verb. A cutting
of in the middes.

Interc&imacron;sus, a, um, part. ab Interci­
dor. Cut of in the middes, dissolued and
broken. Intercisi dies, Macrob. Certen
daies on which at some bowres it was law
full to sit in iudgement, and in some not:
we may vse them for halfe holy daies.

Inter&ebreve;qu&ibreve;to, as, Liv. To ride between

Int&ebreve;rest, impers. It is profitable, a­

he hath to doe: sometime to be at or pre­

incumberer: an interruptour.

Interpell&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Interrup­
ted, disturbed, incumbred, letted, hindered
discontinued.

Interpello, as. To interrupt, let, or
hinder one that is speaking or doeing any
thing, to disturb or trouble: to require, ask,
or demaund a thing, Vale. also to tel or
warne one, Non.

Interpens&imacron;va, &omacron;rum, n.g. Vitruv.
Certaine peeces of timber, clouen bourdes
or stones, which are set in from the cor­
ners of the wall to the ends of the rasters
to conueigh raine water into spouts: a man
ner of penthouses. Interpensivi parie­
tes. Hermol. Walles which rise vpon a­
nother wal or floore, and haue no founda­
tion in the ground.

Interpl&ibreve;co, as, Stat. To fold between.

Interp&obreve;l&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. Plin.
New dressing or polishing of things.

Interp&obreve;l&amacron;tor, &omacron;ris, m.g. verb. * A

Interp&obreve;l&amacron;trix, &imacron;cis, f.g. verb. Dige.
She that so doth.

Interp&obreve;lis. le, Plin. Renewed, refre­
shed, new dressed, new scoured or polished.

Interp&obreve;lo, as. To renew or refresh, to
polish, to trimme, to decke as it were made
newe: to refresh, to dresse new as fullers
doe: to new pariette or white lime, to paint
new where olde painting hath bene: to
purge or trie as frankensence is when it
is made.

ance: a mediatour, a meane, a trouchman:

Ir, Sipont. The hollownesse of the

Ira, ræ, f.g. p.l. Anger, stomake, di­

or troublesomnes of, &c.

Ir&amacron;cund&emacron;, adverb. p.l. Angerly, with

Ir&amacron;cundia, æ, f.g. p.l. Anger quickly

angrie.

Iracunditer, adverb. Non. Angerly.




Ir&amacron;cundus, a, um, f.g. p.l. Shortly or

displeased.

Irascere, pro irasci, Pompon.

Ir&omacron;n&imacron;a, æ, f.g. p.l. A figure in speaking

soneth contrarie to that he thinketh, to
mocke him whome he reasoneth with: a
mocker, or scoffer.

and hearbs by the rootes.

Ischias, adis, f.g. Plin. The disease

Ischuria, æ, f.g. Iun. A keeping of

pisse cannot passe out.

Isicium, cij, n.g. Iun. A certaine

Isis,* A certaine playster wholsome
against melancholie.

Isocinn&abreve;mon, Plin. An hearb called
also Daphnois: it hath a verie pleasant
smell, and commonlie groweth in those
places, wher Cynamon & Cassia groweth.

are like in length.

I T

Ita, adverb. p.b. Yea, so, euen so,
such, in such sorte: also therefore, some­
time it is a worde of wishing: being ioyned
with a negatiue it signifieth verie.

Itane? Indeed? is it so? is it as you say?

Itane verò, Plaut. Doest thou speak
as thou thinkest? why? will thou then
saie, &c.

It&abreve;q; conjunct. p.b. Therefore, then,
because that, and so.

Item, adverb. p.b. Also, so, and,
likewise, in like manner, and also.

Itemq; And moreouer, and also.

Iter, iteris, secundum, Prisc. & iti­
neris ab antiquo nom Itiner, n.g. p.b. A iourney, a way, a going, a passage, a
voyage: also a trade, course, or meane:
also a sayling or voyage by the sea. Ter.

It&ebreve;r&amacron;t&ibreve;o, onis, f.g. verb. ab Itero,
p.b. A repetition, a reiteration, a rehear­
sing againe, a doubling of: a renewing, a
beginning againe: also the second tilth
or earing. also, the secnd pressing of oliues,
or the oyle of the second pressing. Colum.

It&ebreve;r&amacron;t&omacron;, adverb. p.b. Iust. Againe,
eftsoones.

It&ebreve;r&amacron;tus, a, um, part. p.b. Repeated,
doubted, rehearsed againe.

It&ebreve;ro, as, p.b. To doe a thing eftsoones
or againe: to goe backe againe: to repeate,
to double, to renew, to doe a thing againe,
or the second time, to tell, speake, or saie
againe: to beginne a fresh, to interate.

It&ebreve;rum, adverb. p.b. Eftsones, againe,
the second time, twise.

It&ibreve;dem, adverb. p.b. So, likewise, af­
ter the same sort, semblably, in like man­
ner.

I&umacron;g&ebreve;rum, ri, vel iugeris à nominat.

I&ubreve;gum, gi, n.g. The ridge or toppe of

or the embroderer doth roll vp his worke:
a thing made with forkes or speares like a
gallowes, vnder which enemies vanqui­
shed in despite were caused to go: a frame
whereon vines are ioyned: a beame wher­
on ballances or scales doe hang: the seate
in a ship whereon the rower fitteth: the
signe in the firmament called Libra: as
much ground as two oxen will care in a
daie: also the necek of a lute or such in­
strument, whereinto the pins be put, Iun.

Ius, i&umacron;ris, n.g. Law, right, good dea­

or statue: dutie, reason: a priuiledge or

vel honorarium, Papin. The actes, sta­

dem quod Civile. Summum jus. The
extremitie and rigour of the law. Ius




singulare, Paul. Some speciall and ex­
traordinarie law in a particular case.

Iustitium, tij, n.g. A ceasing from the

wealth, &c. The vacation, or out of
tearme.

Iustus, iustior,  Iustissimus, a, um.
Iust, vpright, dealing truly, reasonable,
deserued, a vertuous and a good man: full
perfect, due, meane and indifferent, nei­
ther to great, nor too litle: right, lawfull
sufficient, fauourable: also great: true
and right, Digest. Iusti dies. Certaine
appointed daies, vid. Dies.

Iust&omacron;, ablativus, vice adverbij. The same that Iuste: . Iusto longius, Quin.
Longer then neede is, or than is meete.

LAbans, tis, part. Fainting, de­

discomfited and readie to flie:
which one cannot hold vp.

Labarum, ri n.g. Iun. A
church banner, flag, or streamer: also a
banner or flagge for the warre, embro­
dered with gold, beset with glistering pre­
tious stones, and was wont to be caried
before the Emperour: the common souldi­
ours had such an opinion thereof, that
they did worship it: afterward Constan­
tine in stead hereof commaunded the
figne of the crosse to be caried before him.

L&abreve;b&omacron;ro, as. To labour, to striue, con­

diseased: to be fautie, or diseased: to be

with: not to be well able to prooue: to haue
or be in, to susteine or suffer, to be bended
with, to be greatly troubled, cumbred, or
vexed with, to haue scarcitie of.

uoke, stirre, or egge a man to wrath or
contention, be it with wordes, writing, or
acte: to beginne first, to raile on one, to
prick with some ill language or acte: to
abuse in speech, to proffer wrong: to de­
sire instantlie & importunatelie: to trou­
ble with importunate requestes: to single
as ones flesh doth: also to stampe & scrape,
Stat. to fret or thrust against, Sil. to vex
and molest, Luc.

L&abreve;cessor, &ebreve;ris, vel Lacessior, &imacron;ris,
&imacron;tus sum, Pass. Colum. Prouoked, stir­
red, egged, or mooved.

L&abreve;ch&abreve;n&imacron;zo, as, Suet. To be feeble,
weake, or feint.

Lachne, Ovid. Rug, shaghaire, or

Lactens, tis, part. à Lacto. Milch,

Lactes, ium, f.g. Plin. By the opini­
on of Plinie and moste Phisitians, are the
small guts, by which first the meate pas­
seth out of the stomack, and is not the part
called Meseuterium, as Gaza doth in­
terprete it: Probus sayth they be certaine
tender partes vnder the ribbes that can
not suffer anie streke.

Lacuna, næ, f.g. A ditch wherein

decaied, or wanting a blemish Lacuna, is
also when any thing in writing doth lack,
as Mendum is that which is corupted. E­
rasm.

L&abreve;cus, us, m.g. Catull. A poole, lake,

L&abreve;mia, æ, f.g. Plin. A beast that hath

L&abreve;miæ, arum, Iun. Women that were
thought to haue such eyes, as they could
pull out and put in at their pleasure, or
rather certaine devills in a counterfaite
shape, which with flatterings allured




faire young springals, and taking vpon
them the likenes and fashion of women,
were thought to deuoure them, and bring
them to destruction: Apuleus calleth
them Ladies of the faire, or such as make
chidlren afraide.

L&abreve;pis, &ibreve;dis, m.g. A stone: also a
mile, Bud. an hill. Virg. A negligent
person or slow fellow that stirreth not
liuelie in doing, Terent. Lapis opera­
rius, Plin. A stone that workeman vse in
their worke, as the whetstone, &c. Qua­
dratus, Vitruv. A square stone. Ma
nalis, Fest. A stone whereout runneth a
fountaine or spring, or whereout water
gusheth. Molaris, Quint. Incusus,
Virg. A milstone, or a g rindstone. Re­
divivus, vel veteranus. That hath ly­
en long vnused, and is newlie occupied
afresh. Armenius, Iun. A stone of a
green colour mixed with blew, and that
may be easilie broken into crumbes: yet
saome saie it is of such a hardnes, that
seales maie therwith be grauen. Parius,
Virg. white marble. Cyaneus, cærule­
us. stellatus, vel Lapis lazuli, Iun. A
stone that is of Azure or bright blew, cal­
led Lazulus. Preciosus, Curt. A gemme
or pretious stone. Specularis, Lunaris,
vel Arabicus, Plin. Glasse stone, or fine
glasse which maie be cut into verie small
and thinne panes, which in old time they
vsed in stead of glasse windowes, because
the light might be seene through it. Ae­
rarius vel luminis vid. Pyrites. Aero­
fus, vel calaminaris, Plin. A stone out
of which brasse is drawne. Asius, Iun.
vid. Sarcophagus. Bibulus, Virg. vid.
Pumex. Ceraunius, Iun. A thunder­
bolt. Erythæus, Stat. Pearle. Fronta­
tus, vitruv. Which being smoothed on
both sides is iust and euen with the thick­
nes of the wall, or a stone that goeth tho­
rough the wall, and is seene on both sides
thereof, a perpender or perpent stone. Iu­
daicus, vid. Tecolithus.  Terminalis,
Iun. A meere stone, a lande marke, a
stone set and placed in the endes of lands
or fields. Thracius, Iun. A kinde of
black Agath stone, which water setteth
on fire, and oyle quencheth a blck iette
stone. Viridis, Iun. vid. Smaragdus.

L&abreve;rix, &ibreve;cis, f.g. Luc. A tree hauing
leaues like the Pine tree, the tymber be­
ing apt for building: it will not perish ei­
ther by rotting or eating of wormes, nor
burn with flame, nor be brought to coals,
but by long space consume: the gumme
that cometh of it is called Larisma re­
sina, it is vsed for Turpentine.

Laudatissimus, a, um, Plin. Moste
commended, the verie best, and of moste
account.

Laud&amacron;t&imacron;vus, a, um, Quint. Of or be­
longing to commendation, wherein praise
is contained.

Laud&amacron;tor, oris, m.g. verb. A praiser
or commender.

Laud&amacron;trix, &imacron;cis, f.g. verb. Shee that
praiseth.

Laud&amacron;tus, a, um, part. sive nom.
Praised, commended.

Laudea, pro Lamea, Isid.

Laudicoena, næ, m.g. Plin. Iun. He
that is hired for a supper to praise a man.

Laudo, as. To priase, to commend, to
extoll: also to cite or name, to bring as a
witnes.

L&abreve;ver, eris, n.g. & aliquando fæm. Plin. 
An hearb growing in the water like
alssander, but hauing lesse leaues, some
cal it bolders or bell ragges, some yeallow
water cresses, others water parselie.

Laverna, næ, f.g. Fest. The goddesse
to whose custodie theeues committed
themselues.

Lauernio, onis, Iun. A cheefe, a fel­
low that sleepeth by daie, that he may
steale by night.

Laverum, vid. Lanerum.

L&abreve;vo, as, l&amacron;vi,  lautum, &  lotum, &

be wet and moiste, Plaut.

Lavo, is, vi, &omacron;tum & &amacron;tum, &ebreve;re, Virg.
Idem.

Laurea, æ, f.g. A bay tree, a leafe, or
branch of bay: a garland of hay, or laurel.

Laur&ebreve;&amacron;tus, a, um. Crowned with
lawrell: wearing a garland of hay. Lite­
tæ laureatæ, Liv. Letters of victorie ob­
teined against the enemie.

Laurentalia &omacron;rum, n.g. Fest. Festi­
vall or holidaies dedicated to Laurentia,
who was the nurse of Romulus and Re­
mus.

Laur&ebreve;&obreve;la, æ, f.g. dim. à Laures.
A garland that victourers were wont to
weare in their triumph: lorell, or laurie.

Laur&ebreve;&obreve;lum, li, n.g. Aurel. An in­
strument in surgerie, being a kinde of




pinsers, or made hollow like a litle spoon,
wherewith gunshot, as pellets, &c. ar­
rowes, dartes, and other iron things are
pulled and taken out of the flesh.

Laur&ebreve;&omacron;tis, is, f.g. Gal. Ashes that
come of trying siluer in goldsmithes for­
ges.

Laur&emacron;tum, ti, n.g. Plin. A groue of
bay trees: a place where bay trees doe
grow.

Laureum, i, n.g. Cat.  vid. 
Laurea.

Laur&ebreve;us, a, um, Liv. Of or belonging
to baye.

Lauria, orum, Liv. Presents or gifts
bestowed vpon outlandish embassadours.

La&umacron;rices, um, Plin. Young conies
out out of the dames bellie, or taken from
the teats, which being sodde with the
entralls not well clensed, in old time was
counted a most delicate meate.

Laur&ibreve;fer, a, um, Plin. That beareth
bayes.

Laur&ibreve;ger, a, um, Mart. That wea­

Laurus, ri, f.g. The laurell or baie
tree, dedicated to triumphes and victo­
ries, and being Apollos tree is the reward
of poesie, and is neuer blasted with light­
ning. Laurus Alexandrina vel Idæa,
Iun. Laurell of Alexandria, or tongue
laurell. Laurus baccalia, Iun. The bay
tree bearing berries.

Laus, dis, f.g. Lande, praise, com­
mendation, glorie, renowne, a mans good
report or fame, a praise worthie deed.

lie, daintilie, gallantlie.

Realmes.

Lautissimus, a, um, Plin. Verie fine
and sumptuous.

costlie, gailie, gallantlie, &c.

Lautr&imacron;ces,* The wiues of two bree­
thren.

vsed to wash or bath them.

à Lavo. Washed.

Lautus, a, um, & Lautior, us. Neat,
cleane, minion, fine, tricke, handsome:
