Laxamentum, ti, n.g. Release, recrea­

or lewser.

Lax&amacron;tus, a, um, Plin. Lowse, delive­

at libertie.

Lax&emacron;, adverb. Looselie, largely, farr.

Laxior, us, compar. à Laxus, Pro­
cul. More large, longer.

Laxissimè, adverb. Plin. A greate
way of, or farre from.

Lax&ibreve;tas, &amacron;tis, f.g. Loosenes, libertie,
widenes, largenes.

Laxo, as. To loose, vntie, or sette at
libertie: to release, to recreate, to refresh,
to open, to make larger: to make merie &
pleasant, to growe broader: to ridde and
dispatch out of, &c, to prolong: to prise
lower. Laxare vel facere pedem, Virg.
To let goe the foote, and take fast footing
againe by turnes as they doe in barges
when they rise and fall in rowing.

Laxus, & Laxissimus, a, um. Loose,
slack, vnbound, large, wide, soft, weak,
vnbent, long, free. Laxæ habenæ, pro
molli & loni imperio.

Lazuli lapis, Iun. A stone partelie
greenish, and partlie blewish, called the
azure or lazul stone.

Ambassadour: Libera legatio. A lega­

with more authoritie prosecute his owne,
priuate matters in the countrie whether
he is sent. Votiva legatio. When one
purchaseth the title of an embassadour
or lieuetennans more honourablie to per­
forme a vow that he hath made.

L&emacron;th&amacron;lis, le, Plin. Mortall, deadly,
pestilent, noysome.

L&emacron;th&amacron;l&ibreve;ter, adverb. Plin. Mortal­
ly, deadly.

L&emacron;thargia, æ, f.g. Plin. The lethar­
gie, &c. vid. lethargus,

Lmetharg&ibreve;cus, a, um, Plin. Pertai­
ning to the drousie euil.

Lethargicus, ci, m.g. One sicke of the
drousie euil.

L&emacron;thargus, gi, m.g. Cels. A disease
contrarie to phrantikenes, wherein is
leannes, and a necessitie of sleeping in a
manner not to be resisted: the lethargie, or
sleepie, drowsie, and forgetfull sickenes,
whereby memorie and reason almost pe­
risheth, and the power sensitive is greatlie
anoied.

L&emacron;th&amacron;tus, a, um, part. à Lethor,
Ovid. Killed, murderd, put to death,
dead.

L&emacron;th&ibreve;fer, a, um, Colum. Deadlie,
bringing or causing death.

L&emacron;th&ibreve;f&ibreve;cus, a, um, Lucan. Which
can kill, or hath the force to kill.

L&emacron;tho, as, Virg. To kill, to make one
die.

L&emacron;thum, thi, n.g. Death.

L&ebreve;v&amacron;men, &ibreve;nis: & Levamentum, ti,
n.g. Solace, comfort, consolation: that
deminisheth and asswageth euill or sor­
row, that maketh it lesse, more tollerable,
and easie.

Levasso, pro levo, Enn.

L&ebreve;v&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. A conso­
lation, an easing, a diminishing of paine
or sorrow, a delivering from, &c.

L&emacron;v&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Liv. Lifted vp,
eased.

Leuca, æ, f.g. Isid. A measure of
ground contayning 50. pases.

Leuc&abreve;cantha, thæ, f.g. Plin. A
kinde of thistles that hath white prickle
leaves, a stalk two cubites high, of thick­
nes of a finger, and hollow, in the toppe
and head not vnlike the Artichoke, but
more pricked: it is called S. Marie thistle.

Leuc&abreve;ch&amacron;res, tæ, m.g. Plin. A pre­
cious stone that is white.

Leuc&abreve;nth&ebreve;mis, idis, f.g. & Leu­
canthemum, mi, n.g. Plin. The hearb




Camomil.

Leucargillon, vel Leucargillium,
lii, n.g. Plin. White clay.

Leuce, es, f.g. Plin. A white Poplar
tree: also an hearb verie like to Mercury,
but that a whtie line runneth through
the middle leafe, Plin. a kinde of fowle
spottines of the bodie, which hath some
likenes with the white morphew, but it is
whiter, Cels.

Leuciscus, sci, m.g. Iun. A kinde of
riuer mugle or lumpe: some take it for a
fresh water mullet.

Leucochrysus, Plin. A kinde of In­
stinct stone hauing a white veine min­
gled with the colour of golde.

Leucogæa, & Leucographia, Pli.
A pretious stone all white.

Leuc&obreve;gr&abreve;phis, idis, f.g. Plin. An
hearb good for those that spit blood.

Leucoion, coii, n.g. Plin. The gene­
rall name of all violets, but properlie it is
taken for the winter giloufer. Fuchschius
also seemeth to comprehend vnder this
name the giloufers called close sciences.

Leuc&omacron;ma, &abreve;tis n.g. Hermol. The
webbe in the eye: the white of an egge:
also a table called in Litine album,
wherein the names of iudges or officers
and the acts done euerie yere be written.

Leuc&omacron;mænides, um, Hermol. Smal
fishes called also Boces.

Leucon. Ovid. Blanch or whitecote.

Leuc&obreve;n&ibreve;um, or Leuconicum, ci, n.
g. Mart. Winte cotton.

Leucop&abreve;ryphus, phi, m.g. q.b. Cæl. Rhod.
He that weareth white garments
but not costlie.

Leuc&obreve;p&ebreve;r&abreve;los, Plin. A white preci­
ous stone with strakes of golde.

Leuc&obreve;phæ&amacron;tus, a, um, Mart. That
weareth a russet colour of wooll vndied.

Leuc&obreve;phæus, a, um, Plin. Ashe co­
lour: a browne or russet colour.

Leuc&obreve;phlegmat&imacron;a, æ, f.g. Cels. The
third kind of dropsie rising of fleugme ga­
thered in all partes of the bodie, and mix­
ed with the flesh maketh it spongie, and
causeth the wholl bodie to swell.

Leuc&obreve;ph&obreve;rum ti, n.g. Plin. Boras
that they solder golde withall.

Leuc&obreve;phthalmos, Plin. A precious
stone like a white eye.

Leuc&omacron;pus,* White of natural colour.

Leucopygi,* Nice, tender, effemi­
nate, hauing white buttocks.

Leucostictos, ctis, com. g. Plin. A
stone that hath white spottes in it like the
Porphyrie white marble, or marble ha­
uing white specks or strikes in it.

Leucrocuta, æ, f.g. Plin. A verie
swift beast in Ethiopia, counterfeiting a
mans voice, as big as an Asse, hauing the
necke, taile and breast of a lyon, the head
of a cammell, &c.

what light, wanton, or vainglorious.

L&ebreve;vidensa, æ, f.g. Course cloth and
of a low price.

Levidense munus. A small gifte, a
simple gift of small value.

Levigo, vid. Lævigo.

L&ebreve;v&imacron;fidus, a, um, Plaut. Of small

L&ebreve;v&ibreve;pes, &ebreve;dis, omn. gen. Swift,

L&ebreve;vir, &ibreve;ri, m.g. Modest. The hus­

L&ebreve;vis, ve, & h2Levior, us. Light, liger,
swift, easie, wavering, mutable, vncer­

small reputation or credit: also quicke
and liuelie, Claud. vid. Lævis.

L&ebreve;visomnus, a, um, Lucret. Watch­
full, soone waked.

L&ebreve;viss&ibreve;mus, a, um, Plin. Lightest.

Levist&ibreve;eum vulgare, Matthiol. A­
lisander or loueage.

L&ebreve;v&ibreve;tas, &amacron;tis, f.g. Lightnes, ligernes,
inconstancie, shittlenes, lack of gravity.
vid. Levitas.

L&ebreve;v&ibreve;t&ebreve;r, leviùs,  levissimè, adverb.
Lightlie, slenderlie, vnconstantlie, smal­

cientlie, gentlie.

L&ebreve;v&ibreve;usc&ubreve;lus, a, um, dim. Plin. Som­
what light and wanton.

L&ebreve;vo, as. To lift or hold vp, to take a­
waie, to vndoe, to abate, to diminish, as­
swage, or mitigate, to make easie or light,
to helpe, to vnburden, to ease or lighten,
to deliver or ridde out of, to recreate &




refresh, to extenuate and excuse: also to
heale, Plin. vid. Lævo.

Levor, & Levus, vid. Lævor Lævus.

Lex, l&emacron;gis, f.g. A law: a statute, or­
dinance, or decre: a rule, maner, or fa­
shion to follow, an order, a couenant or
condition. Lege, Plaut. Rightfullie &
according to the law.

Lexis, ios, f.g. A worde.

Lexipyeti,* Medecines that heale
man of agues.

Centaurie.

or oyle glasse: the vessell wherein the ho­

anie thing tasted and offered.

be sacrifice, offered, or tasted: to be ta­

stone like to frankencense.

Lim&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. à Libo. A
thing offered, a tasting in offering.

Libatus, a, um, part. Tasted, assay­
ed, offered, sarificed, culled, drawne out.

Libella, æ, f.g. dim. à Libra. A
certaine coyne: of it were two sortes, one
the tenth part of Sestertius: an other the
tenth part of Denarius: three farthings
of our monie. Also, a line or plummet of a
mason or carpenter, a pound weight, Mi.

Libelli. Letters missiue, points or arti
cles in a letter, bills of attachment.

Libellio, &omacron;nis, m.g. Varr. A cari­
er of letters: also he that writeth and sel­
leth bookes, Stat.

L&ibreve;bellulus, li, m.g. Ieró. A litle booke.


L&ibreve;bellus, li, m.g. à Liber. A little
booke, a supplication: a libell or declarait
on in the law of debt, trespasse, couenant
and other like: a bill of remembrance, de­
liuered to a magistrate or officer: a libell,
a writ, a citation, a bill of processe: a cer­
tificate, a testimoniall, a passeport: also
a kinde of measure, Cat. A Libellis, vel
libellorum Magister, Suet. Master of
the requestes. Libellus supplex, Mart.
A bill of request, a supplication. Libel­
lus memorialis, Suet. A bill of recorde,
amemorandum. Libellus famosus,
Iun. A slaunderous, biting, and reproch­
full libell.

L&ibreve;bentiùs, adverb. compar. Hor.
More willinglie, &c.

L&ibreve;ber, bri, m.g. The inward peele,
rinde, or barke of a tree: Also a booke,
a worke written, an inuentorie, a regi­
ster. Libri rituales. Bookes which pre­

with the manner of them, such as be the
missall and the Pontificall, &c. Ele­
phantini, Vopisc.Ivorie bookes or ta­
bles: costly and chargeable bookes, Sacri,Iun.
The Bible containing the olde and
new testament.

L&imacron;ber, ra, rum. Free, at libertie, safe,
void of or without, &c: not restrained or
limited, not bounden, not subiect, not
senile or of bond condition: bold or frank,
without busines or let, large or great, at
ones pleasure: also standing out, Varr.

L&imacron;b&ebreve;r&amacron;l&ibreve;a, &omacron;rum, n.g. Iun. A so­
lemne or festivall day dedicated to Bac­
chus: Shrouetyde.

L&imacron;b&ebreve;r&amacron;lis, le, & liberalissimus, a,
um. Comelie, well fauoured, honest, good,
meete for an honest man, liberall, free,




harted, full of largesse, bountifull, free,
franke: also free borne and of an honest
house, Terent. Liberalis cause, & li­
berale iudicium, Plaut. Which tou­
cheth or concerneth ones libertie.

L&imacron;b&ebreve;r&amacron;l&imacron;tas, &amacron;tis, f.g. Liberalitie,
bountie, freenes in giuing or bestowing,
honest intreating and dealing: also that
which is opposite to servile feare, Ter.

L&imacron;b&ebreve;r&amacron;l&ibreve;ter, adverb. Liberallis, free­
lie, frankelie, largelie, aboundantlie, ho­
nestlie, like an honest man, without base
or vile ocupation, taking his pleasure.

L&imacron;b&ebreve;randus, a, um, part. To be freed,
deliuered, or set at libertie.

L&imacron;b&ebreve;r&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Deliuered,

Lib&ebreve;ri, &omacron;rum, m.g. Sonnes & daugh­

be born of them, also one sonne or daugh­

Liberi flos, Plaut. Fragrant wine.

Liberta, æ, f.g. vide Libertus.

L&imacron;bertus, ti, m.g. & Liberta, tæ, f.g.
He or she that of bond is made free: a late

L&ibreve;bet, libuit, &  libitum est, impers.
It liketh or contenteth: it is my pleasure
or phantasie, I thinke it good: I lift: he
would faine, &c.

Libet, personale. It liketh, it plea­
seth, he liketh or listeth after.

of lechery.

Libidinosissimus, a, um, Superl.
Lamprid.

L&ibreve;b&imacron;d&ibreve;n&omacron;sus, a, um. Wilfull, bent to
pleasure, lustfull, pleasant: lecherous,
fleshly, baudie, sensuall: giuen to the
lust of the bodie: incontinent. Sententiæ
libidinosæ. Giuen at a mans lust and
pleasure, to serue his phantasie.

L&ibreve;b&imacron;do, inis, f.g. Sensualitie, vnlaw­
full appetite, lust, or desire: appetite, wil,
phantasie, wanton lusts of bodie, lecherie,
concupiscence, pleasure and delight.

L&ibreve;b&ibreve;t&imacron;na, næ, f.g. Horat. The coste,
charge, and expenses of burials: the god­
desse in whose temple were sold all things
pertaining to funeralls and burialls: the
buying or selling of those things as apper­
taine to burying: death, or the beere wher­
on dead bodies were caried.

L&ibreve;b&ibreve;t&imacron;n&amacron;rius, a, um, Plaut. He that
hath the suruey and charge about inter­
ments: the steward or prouider: also the
seller of all things necessarie for a fune­
rall.

Libitonarium, rij, n.g. Isid. A kinde
of garment without sleeues, such as the
the monkes in Egypt doe weare.

L&imacron;bo, as. To taste, or touch lightly: to
sacrifice or offer: to take, gather, or picke
out in reading.

Libonotus, ti, m.g. Iun. The south­
west winde.

L&imacron;bra, bræ, f.g. quæ & æs, & mina,
seu mna, & Pondo dicitur. A pound,
whereof be three sortes: Troiana, mer­
calis vel Zygostatica, beeing 16. oun­
ces. This all common occupiers doe vse in
buying and selling: the French men call
it the Kings pound. Romana, conteinig




12. ounces, which Apothecaries vse, and
all Phisitians and aunceitn writers doe
speake of: the third is Marca, Octonaria,
or nummularia, conteining but eight
ounces: by this money is weighed: also a
parie of balances or wheightes: one of the
12. signes: a Carpenters line, or Masons
rule: a counterpoise: a balassing. Libra
Attica, Iun. An Athenian pound, which
was more by foure drachmes then a Ro­
mane pound. Libra Romana, * Iu coyne
is double our pound, that is, 40. shillings,
or thereabout. Libra mensuralis, consi­
steth of tenne equall partes or ounces, and
is lesse then Libra ponderalis by two
ounces.

L&imacron;br&amacron;lis, le, Plin. That is a pounde
weight or measure.

L&imacron;br&amacron;men, inis, n.g. Liv. &

L&imacron;br&amacron;mentum, ti, n.g. A balasing or

ding or euen weight: the tongue of a ba­
lance: a leuelling or making euen. Libra­
menta tormentorum, Tacit. The strings,
thongs, or cordes, wherewith they shoote
in engines of warre.

L&ibreve;br&amacron;ria, æ, f.g. Gell. A librarie.

L&imacron;brilla, or Libella, Fest. Stones tied

L&ibreve;burnum, ni, n.g. Iuv. A kind of li­
cter and couch made like a foiste or bri­

to be caried so softly and easilie, that they

the prise, &c.

Libycontes,* Carbuncle stones, which

L&ibreve;center, adverb. Licentiouslie, ouer
freelie, with too much libertie, ouer boldly
or rashly.

L&ibreve;centia, æ, f.g. Licence: vnlawfull,
immoderate, or ouer much libertie, power
or licence to doe as one will: boldnes or vn­
rulines: also free speach, Quint.

Licentiatus iuris, * vid. Prolyta.

L&ibreve;centior, us. Ouer liberall, free, or
licentious, too licentious, dissolute wherin




one writeth or speaketh his minde freely.

L&ibreve;centi&omacron;sus, a, um, Quint. Rash,
vsing vnlawful libertie, licentious: disso­
lute, vnrulie.

L&ibreve;ceo, es, &ubreve;i, &ibreve;tum, &emacron;re. To be prised, to
be set at a price, or for how much it shal be
solde.

L&ibreve;ceor, &emacron;ris, &ibreve;cus sum, &emacron;ri, depon. To
set the prise higher, to shew for how much
he will sell it, to price the thing: also to
cheapen, to offer the price.

L&ibreve;cet, &emacron;bat, &ubreve;it, &emacron;re, Impers. It is
lawfull: it may: it is free: I am content, I
haue authoritie, power, or leaue to doe,
&c., thou maist if thou wilt: it is easie.

L&ibreve;cet, adverb. concedentis, Virg.
Be it so.

L&ibreve;cet, coniunct. Although, albeit.

Lichanos, Iun. the froefinger string,
or the third string. Also D. sol. re. Iun.

L&ibreve;chas, Iun. A measure which excee­
deth not foure fingers: the span from the
thumbs end to the forefingers and stretch­
ed out.

L&imacron;chen, &emacron;nis, m.g. vel Lichene, es,
f.g. Plin. A tettar or ring worme: Plinie
taketh it for the daungerous tettar that
beginneth vnder the chinne, and therfore
is called Mentagra: also the hearb Li­
verworte.

Lichnis agrestis, * An hearb called
also Tragonarum.

L&imacron;c&ibreve;&abreve;t&omacron;r&ibreve;um, rij, Ovid. A weavers
shettle or a silke womans tonnell or ta­
vell, whereon silke or thread is cast or
shotte through the loome or webbe: the
yarne beame.

L&ibreve;c&ibreve;nia, æ, f.g. Colum. a kinde of
Oliues, called also Liciniara.

Licinium, nij, n.g. Isid. Vestis ge­
nus, sic dictum, quòd textura cius li­
gata sit in totum: also a kinde of wood

L&ibreve;t&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Virg. Appea­

L&ibreve;t&emacron;ra, æ, f.g. A letter of the crosse­
row: a bill or scrowle, ones writing, his
hand in writing. Lirera caduca, Plin.
A blinde letter that will in short time be
worne out. Litera fugiens, vel exoles
oens, Iun. A dimme letter that is hard
to be discerned or read.

L&ibreve;t&ebreve;ræ, &amacron;rum, f.g. A letter missiue,
an epistle or letter sent from freind to
friend: an iniunction, ordnance, or de­
cree of a Prince: bills of reckoning and,
account: learning, knowledge, science,
good letters, writings, deeds, instruments,
evidences. Literæ honorariæ sive sa­
cræ, Symmach. Honourable letters,
wherein honour & preferment is bestow­
ed vpon some men. Laureatæ, Liv. Vi­
ctorie indices, Iun. Victrices. Letters
of victorie obtained against the enemie.
Aculeatæ, Biting, taunting, and spite­
full letters. Præsormare literas infan­
ti, Quint. To set a sample or coppie.

L&ibreve;t&ebreve;r&amacron;rius, a, um, Plin. Pertaining
to learning or letters.

L&ibreve;t&ebreve;r&amacron;t&emacron;, adverb. Like a cunning
man, learnedlie, cunninglie.

Literatior, us, compar. à Litera­
tus, Sen.

L&ibreve;t&ebreve;r&amacron;tor, &omacron;ris, m.g. Suet. A young
grammarian that vnderstandeth gram­
mar pretie well, a smatterer in learning.

L&ibreve;t&ebreve;r&amacron;t&umacron;ra, æ, f.g. Grammer, lear­
ning, writing, cunning, literature.

L&ibreve;t&ebreve;r&amacron;tus, a, um. Cunning, learned, &
teacher of grammar: workmanlie. Plaut.
Applyed wholie to studie: also that hath
letters grauen in it.

L&ibreve;t&ebreve;r&omacron;sus, a, si, Non. Greatly learned.


L&ibreve;t&ebreve;r&ubreve;la, læ, f.g. dim. à Litera. A
scroule or bill, a little letter.

Literulæ arum, f.g. A little letter: al­
so good letters, knowledge of learning.

L&ibreve;thargyrium, siue Lithargvros,
r.b. Plin. Litargie or white lead, which
is the foame of lead tried, and not of sil­
ver, as the word soundeth: also the scum,
foame, froth, or spume of siluer. Of the
3. sortes. The first & best is called Chry­
fitis or Lythargirium auri, Plin. Fome
that commeth of lead tried, being in co­
lour yellow like golde: the second Argy­
rites, and the third Molybditis.

gendred in a mans bodie: also a litle
white and hard swelling or push in the
eyelids.

buncle shining wanly and faintlie.

ment, wherwith stones be ioyned or glew­
ed together.

L&umacron;do, is, si, sum, &ebreve;re. Lo play, to mock

ludere, Iun. to runne at tilt, iusts and
tronment.

thereby to signifie both fruitefulnes, and

Lustr&ibreve;cus, a, um, vt Lustrici dies,

Lustr&ibreve;f&ibreve;cus, a, um, Valer. Argon.

Lustro, as. To compasse or goe round
about, to view on euerie side, to behold e­
uerie waie, to looke round about, to view
narrowly, to weigh and examine diligent­
lie: Also to purge that by sacrifice which is
vncleane. Lustrare exercitum, Cæs. To
make a general muster.

Lustror, aris, depon. Plaut. To haunt
brother houses or stewes.

cherie is vsed: a brothel house or stewes, or




the haunting of the same vice, Plaut.
The purgation of the citie by sacrifice e­
uerie fifth yeare: also the space of foure
yeares, or rather 50. moneths fully ended
and past, Liv.

L&ubreve;t&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Lamprid. Be­
rayed, made myrte and durtie.

L&umacron;te&obreve;la, læ, f.g. * A little flower of
colour yealow, in greatnes and sauour
not much vnlike a violet: also a little
bird not much vnlike a goldfinch called a
Siskin, vid. Lygurius.

L&umacron;tea, æ, f.g. Plin. an hearb grow­
ing in waterie and fennie places, called
also Corneola or Lysimachium.

L&ubreve;tensis, se, Plin. That is nourished
with mudde.

L&umacron;t&ebreve;&obreve;lus, a, um, Virg. Somewhat
yellow, yellowish.

L&umacron;t&emacron;r, &emacron;ris, m.g. Ieron. A cup where­
in wine was delayed with water: also a
bason, or vessel wherein other vessels are
washed.

L&umacron;t&emacron;rium, rij, n.g. dim. à Luter, Poll.
A vessel wherein cups are washed.

L&ubreve;tesco, is, ere, Colum. To turne to
claie, to waxe verie durtie.

L&ubreve;teus, a, um. That is made of claie,
lome, morter, mud, or durt: earthen: also
vile, nothing worth, filthie.

L&umacron;teus, a, um, Plin. Yellow. Luteus
color, Iun. Yellow colour like the yolke
of an egge. Luteum ovi, Plin. The
yoke of an egge. Luteæ violæ, Plin. The
winter Gilofer.

L&ubreve;to, as, frequent. à Luo, Non. To
paie or suffer often.

L&ubreve;to, as, Catul. To lay on clay, lime,
or morter: to spotie or beray.

L&ubreve;t&omacron;sus, a, um, Plin. All myrie and
durtie.

Lutra, træ, f.g. Plin. A beast liuing in
the water, an Otter.

L&ubreve;t&ubreve;lentus, a, um. Myrie, beraied
with myre, dirtie, muddie: also a vile or
filthie person.

L&ubreve;tum, ti, n.g. Clay, lome, myre, dirt:
also a filthie and baudie slaue, a foule &
filthie person. Lutum paleatum vel a­
ceratum, Fest. Daubers morter, lome tem­
pered with chopt straw. Sigillatum, Avi­
cen. Red earth, or a veine of Vermilion.

L&ubreve;tum, ti, n.g. Plin. An hearb fit to
die yellow withall.

Lux, &umacron;cis, f.g. Light, day: brightnes,
cleerenes: an eye: time, season, life: also
great renowne: an ornament. Lux dubia,
Ovid. Twilight. In luce, pro in rep. vel
in publico. Luces in plur. pro stellis.

Lux&amacron;tus, a, um, Plin. Out of ioynt, or
mooued out of the right place.

Luxo, as, Plin. To loose, to put out of
ioynt.

Lux&ubreve;ria, æ, & Luxuries, ei. f.g. All
superfluitie or excesse in carnall plea­
sure, sumptuous faire, or building: riote,
rankenes.

Luxurians, tis, part. Hora. That
vseth things excessiuely.

Lux&ubreve;ri&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Ovid.That
hath vsed things excessively.

Lux&ubreve;rio, as. & Luxurior, aris, de­
pon. Liv. To exceede, to abound exces­
sivlie: to be wanton and giuen to riote: to
spring or grow too rankelie, to be lustie &
ranke.

Lux&ubreve;ri&omacron;s&emacron;, adverb. Riotouslie, ouer
rankely, too aboundantlie, excessively, su­
perfluouslie.

Lux&ubreve;ri&omacron;sus, a, um. Too prosperous, li­
uing in too much pleasure: ouer ranke,
excessive or superfluous, very costly.

Luxus, a, um, Salust.  vide Luxatus.


Luxus, us, m.g. vide Luxuria.


L Y

Lycanthr&omacron;pia, æ, f.g. p.b. Iun. A
kind of phrensie or madnes, wherewith
some beeing haunted, doe forsake the com­
panie of men, and hide themselues in
holes & caves, howling like woolues.




Lycas, Simon.  vid. Lycisca.

Lychnis, &ibreve;dis, f.g. Iun.vide Rosa
Græca, Lychnites, & Digitalis, Lych­
nis coronaria, Iun. Rose, campane.
Lychnis sylvestri, Iun. Calues snowt.
Lychnis agria, Plin. An hearbe like to
line or flaxe.

Lychnites, is, m.g. Plin. A kind of
white marble cut out of the quarries by
candle light: also a gem, whose lively
cleerenes is stirred vp by candle light, and
is red like scarlet.

Lychnitis, &ibreve;tidis, f.g. Plin. An hearb
called also, Taxus barbatus.

Lychnobius, bii, m.g. Sen. He that
in stead of the daie vse to the night, and
liueth as it were by candle light: he that
turneth daie into night, and contrarilie.

Lychnocaia, æ, f.g. Iun. Candelmas
daie.

Lychnopoæus, i, m.g. Iun. A candle
maker, a waxe chandler, or torchmaker.
Lychn&umacron;chus, chi, m.g. A candlesticke:
a braunch wherein lampes or candles
hang: also, a lanterne or light bearer Iun.
Lychnuchus pensilis vel pendens,
Lucret. A hanging candlesticke.

Lychnus, ni, m.g. The match of a
lampe: a lampe, light, or candle. Lychnus
ligneolus. A lanterne of wood.

Lycion, Plin. A medicine made of the
decoction or iuyce of the bramble roote.

Lycisca, & Lyciscus, Isul. A dogge
ingendered of a wolfe & a dogge. Lycis­
ca, Ovid. Lycitas, Virg. Wolfe or churle.

Lycium cii, n.g. Diosc. A kinde of
thorne like vnto boxe.

Lycoctonon, ni, n.g. Diosc. A kinde
of poyson, so called because that it beeing
hid in bones, couered with raw flesh, hun­
ters doe therewithall kill woolues.

Lycophos, Fest. Cleere light, or the
first appearing of the daie light.

Lycophthalmus, mi, m.g. Plin. A
pretious stone of foure diuers colours.

Lycopsis, is, f.g. Plin. By Dioscori­
des description seemeth to be the hearb
called hounds tongue, which hath longer
and thicker leaues then lettice.

Lycopus, pi, * The hearbe Mother­
woorte.

Lycos, Plin. The least kind of spider.

Lydius lapis, Plin. The touchstone
wherewith gold and siluer is tried.

Lygos vel ligus, gi, vid. Vitex.

Lympha, phæ, f.g. Colum. Water.

Lymphans, tis, part. Stat. Making
madde.

Lymph&amacron;t&ibreve;cus, a, um, Fest. vid. Lym­
phatus.

Lymphatio, onis, Plin. Fantasticall
pangues.

Lymph&amacron;tus, a, um. Madde, furious,
enraged, bestraught, outragious, phanta­
sticall: fallen out of his witte by seeing
some thing, as it were the likenes or ap­
pearance of a nymphe in the water.

Lympho, as, Valer. Flac. To trouble,
to make madde.

Lymphor, aris, Plin. To be madde or
out of his witte.

Lympidus, vid. Limpidus.

Lynaceus, a, um. Of the beast Linx:
also he that seeth quickelie, or is quicke
sighted.

Lyncurium, rij, n.g. Plin. A pretious
stone ingendered of the congealed vrine of
the beast Linx, which vrine that beast
hauing voided, she couereth it with earth,
as repining that any bodie should see it.

Lynx, lyncis, m. vel f.g. Virg. A beast
like vnto a woolfe having many spottes &
beeing exceeding quicke of sight: a woolfe
like an hart, a Los or Lynx.

Lyra, ræ, f.g. Plin. An harpe.

Lyrica, orum, n.g. Plin. A song to the
Harpe.

Lyr&ibreve;cen, p.b. Horat.  vid. 
Lyristes.

Lyr&ibreve;cus, a, um, p.b. Pertaining to an
harpe, a player on a harpe. Carmen lyri­
cum, Iun. A song to the harpe: it consisted
of Strophe, Antistrophe, & Epodos.

Lyristes, stæ, m.g. Plin. Iun. An
harper, or one that singeth to the harpe.

Lysimachium, Iun. Willow hearbe,
or loose strife: water willow.

Lysis, eos, f.g. A solution, a lewsing: a
chinking or opening of a wall: It is also
the same that Cymatium, Vitruv.

Lyta, tæ, m.g. Iun. A bachelour of law

Lytrum, tri, m.g. Enn. A ransome.

Lytta, tæ, f.g. Plin. A worme in a
dogges tongue which maketh him mad,
if it be not taken out.

vitailes.

Somewhat leane.

M&abreve;c&emacron;r&amacron;tio, onis, f.g. Vitruv. A so­

M&abreve;c&ebreve;r&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Plaut. Soked,

M&abreve;c&ebreve;resco, is, &ebreve;re. Cat. To be made
or become soft with watering or lying in
licour.

M&abreve;c&ebreve;ria, æ, & Maceries, ei, f.g. A
wall of stones heaped togither without
morter or lime, made in stead of a mound.
also lennesse or barennes. Afran. Also
the row or set of teeth, Iun. Maceries
templi, Iun. The compasse, circuit, or
wall of the Church.

M&abreve;c&ebreve;ro, as, Horat. To make leane
or thinne, to make soft by steeping in li­
quor, to soke or wash in water or other li­
quor, to water: also to vex and disquiet,
to hurt himself with sorow and care, Te­
rent.

M&abreve;cesco, is, &ebreve;re, Plaut. To waxe or
become leane and barren.

M&abreve;chæra, æ, f.g. Plaut. A sword, a
dagger, a knife, a long sword being sharpe
but on one side.

M&ebreve;chær&obreve;ph&obreve;rus, ri, m.g. A sword
bearer.

M&abreve;chær&obreve;poeus, i, m.g. * A cutler
or bladesmith.

Machil, Isid. The robe of the Ephod
made altogither of blewe silke, hauing
round about the skirts thereof 72 pome­
granates of blewe silke, and purple, and
scarlet, and as manie billes of golde be­
tween them round about.

M&amacron;ch&ibreve;na, æ, f.g. An instrument or
engine, a framing or workemanship: a
scaffold in building: also things craftily
invented, subtill deuisei or shiftes: craf­
tie meanes to deceiue: also the place ouer
the stage, from whence some god appea­
red or spake.

M&amacron;ch&ibreve;n&amacron;lis, le, Plin. Belonging to
engines or instruments of warre.

M&amacron;ch&ibreve;n&amacron;mentum, ti, n.g. Liv. An
engine.

M&amacron;ch&ibreve;n&amacron;rius, rij, m.g. Paul. One
that slingeth or casteth with an engine
of warre: also a cunning workeman who
can both devise well, and worke well.

M&amacron;ch&ibreve;n&amacron;rius, a, um, Digest. Of, be­
longing, or serving for engines which
beareth or draweth engines. Mensor
machinarius, Vlp. A measurer of land.

M&amacron;ch&ibreve;n&amacron;tio, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. A
subtill inuention or deuising: a subtill
meane or working: also an instrument
of warre, Cels.

M&amacron;ch&ibreve;n&amacron;tor, &omacron;ris, m.g. verb. An
inuenter, a deuiser, a worker, an authour:

M&amacron;ch&ibreve;n&amacron;tus, a, um, part. That in­
uenteth or deuiseth, maketh or fashion­

M&amacron;ch&ibreve;nor, &amacron;ris, depon. To deuise,

by craft and subtiltie.

Maclis, Plin. A beast in Scandinauia

Macte, in sing. & Macti in plur. vo­

nem significantes, quibus propriè
vtimur, quum aliquem ob rem bene

Mage, pro magis. More, rather.

M&abreve;gis, adverb. More, rather.

M&abreve;gistellus, li, m.g. * A litle master.

M&abreve;gistra, æ, f.g. A maistresse or tea­

M&abreve;gistr&amacron;tus, us, m.g. A magistrate,

or gouernance of the people: also the au­

M&abreve;gistro, as, Fest. To play the master,

Magma, atis, n.g. Plin. A confecti­

Magn&amacron;lia,* Great things to be won­

Magn&abreve;n&ibreve;m&ibreve;tas, &amacron;tis, f.g. Valiant­

Magnas, &amacron;tis, m.g. A noble man of

Magn&emacron;rarches, is, Liv. The choise

Magn&emacron;s, &emacron;tis, m.g. The loadestone

Magn&emacron;tis, Iun. A stone called Cat­

Magni, absolutè. Of great value &
account.

Magnifacio, is, &emacron;ci, actum. To e­
steeme greatlie.

Magnificatio, onis, f.g. Macrob.
An extolling or advancing.

Magn&ibreve;f&ibreve;c&emacron;, aduerb. Nobly, honou­
rablie, royallie, magnificallie, highly,
with much commendation, greatlie, with
wordes of great honour: with a maiestie,
solemnely, like a lorde or great man: with
a great gravitie or maiestie.

Magn&ibreve;f&ibreve;centia, æ, f.g. The doing or
atchiuing of great things & verie sum­
ptuous or gorgeous, magnificense, noble
and sumptuous prouision: a loftie, hautie,
and statelie vtterance, &c. full of osten­
tation.

Magn&ibreve;f&ibreve;centior, us, & Magnifi­
centissimus, a, um. More noble, honou­
rable, sumptuous, costlie: more loftie,
hautie, statelie, and higher.

Magnificentiùs, magnificentissi­
mè, adverb. Terent. More noblie, cost­
lie, magnifically, loftelie.

Magn&ibreve;f&ibreve;co, as, Plin. To extoll, to

Magn&ibreve;f&ibreve;cus, a, um, Plaut. That
doth great actes: great, noble, honoura­

quas antiqui solebant in modum cy­

Manceps, &ibreve;pis, com. g. A farmer
that buieth or hireth a thing of the people
vpon a rent: one that buyeth or hireth
things at great, and after setteth or fol­
leth them at a high price, for his own gaine:
he that vndertaketh a thing in great: he
that buyeth a thing in open porte sale of
goods: also he that giueth or selleth a
thing vpon warrantise, Plaut. Plinius
vsus est metaphoricè, pro co qui cau­




sidicum in causis agendis, conducta
ad hoc corona vulgi plaudentis, lau­
dendum redemit.

Manc&ibreve;p&amacron;tio, &omacron;nis, f.g. Boeth. A
manner of selling before witnesses with
sundrie solemnities and ceremonies, vid.
mancipi Emptio.

Manc&ibreve;p&amacron;tus, a, um, Part. Bonde,
inthralled, sold or giuen ouer to the pow­

Manc&ibreve;p&amacron;tus, us, m.g. verb. Plin.
A selling on warrantise.

Manc&ibreve;pi, or Manc&ubreve;pi, indeclin.
in vtroque num. The interest and
right of a thing. Res mancipi vel man­
cupi, Vlp. Anie thing that is in ones
full and proper power or possession, anie
thing that maie be alienated from ones
possession to an other. Emptio mancipi,
dicebatur solenne quoddam genus
emptionis, quod siebat inter solos
cdes Rom. præsentibus non minus
quinque testibus puberibus Roma­
nis, & eo qui libram tenebat, Libri­
pensque vocabatur: quibus præsen­
tibus, is qui mancipium accepit. æs
tenens ita dicit, Hunc ego hominem
ex jure Quintium meum esse aio: is­
que mihi emptus est hoc ære, ænea­
que libra. Deinde ære percutit libra:
idque æs dat ei, à quo mancipium
accipit, quasi pretij loco.

Mancipium, pij, n.g. A prisoner ta­
ken in warre, a captiue, a bondman, a
slaue, a drudge, anie thing taken with
the hand: the contract or bargaine of a
thing sold by warrantise, the assurance
of a thing to one as his own: possession:
also power and authoritie ouer another:
freehold or possession. Mancipium no­
vitiam, Vlp. A young seruiture, a no­
vice, a newcome bondman. Veteranum,
vel tritum, Vlp. An olde tried servant,
an olde seruiture. Sui mancipij esse. To
be subiect to no man, to be free, and at his
owne libertie.

Manc&ibreve;po, as. To dispossesse ouer selfe
and giue the right to an other, to deliver
possession, to make liverie and season, to
deliuer in bondage, to sell for money, to
giue vp by bargaine.

Mancus, a, um. That lacketh a limb
lame, maymed, vnperfect, weake, of no
force or power: also he that hath but one
hand.

Mandans, tis, part. Plaut. Com­

Mand&amacron;t&amacron;rius,* He to whome a com­

Mandar&umacron;tus, a, um. He that will

Mand&amacron;tus, a, um. Giuen in charge,

Mando, as. To bid, to commaund, to

Mando, is, di, sum, &emacron;re. To chewe

Mando, &omacron;nis, m.g. Varr. A great
eater, he that is alway chawing and ea­

Mandor, eris. To be chewed.

Mandra, æ, f.g. Iuv. An houell or
other like place made in the fields for
the succour of beasts in vehement heate
or tempests: a stable, a stall, a place for
fodder: also a companie of them that
beare burdens, or of other bruite beastes.
Inv. A great carte, or such like, wherein
beames be caried, Probus.

Mandr&abreve;g&omacron;ras, æ, m.g. Pli. The Man­
drake: the temperature therof is verie cold,
and therefore it is vsed to cast men into
deep sleepes when they must be cut of




Chyrurgians, and for other diuers purpo­
ses in Physick.

Mand&ubreve;c&amacron;tus, a, um, * Chewed, grin­
ded with the teeth.

Mand&umacron;ces, Plaut. Images caried in
pageants, with great cheekes, wid
mouthes, and making a great sound with
their teeth.

Mand&umacron;co, onis, & manducus, ei,
m.g. Plaut. A great eater.

Mand&umacron;co, as, Suet. To chaw, to eat.

Idem.

Manducum, idem quod Obsoni­
um, Varr.

Mand&umacron;cus, ci, m.g. Plaut. A disgiu­
sed or hugely picture, such as was vsed in
maygames and shewes, seeming terrible
by reason of his broad mouth & great cra­
shing or the teeth, & made to cause the
people to giue roome: also a great eater.

M&amacron;n&emacron;, adverb. The beginning of
the morning, earlie, in the morning. Be­
ne mane. Verie earlie.

Manebitur, maneri. impers. They
will tarrie.

M&abreve;nens, tis, part. Tarying, abiding.

M&abreve;neo, es, si, sum, &emacron;re, f.g. To ta­
rie, staie, abide, stand still, remaine, con­
tinue, or persist: to be like to chaunce,
come vnto, follow, or befall: to abide loo­
king for: also to stick to, or to stick at: to
remember, not to forget.

M&amacron;nes, ium, m.g. The spirites, soules,
and ghostes of the dead: the good and bad
angell: also duels: sometime Gods: also
the punishment that the soules doe abide,
Virg.

Mango, &omacron;nis, m.g. Plin. He that
buyeth, stealeth, and selleth one that is
freeborne: a baud that paynteth vp boyes,
women, or servants, and pampereth them
to make them seeme the trimmer, there­
by to sell them the deerer: an horse cour­
ser that pampereth and trimmeth his hor­
ses for the same purpose hucsters, regra­
ters that buy & polish anie kinde of ware
to make it seeme fairer, &c. vid. Inter­
polator.  Mango equorum, Iun. An
horsecourser: he that buyeth horses, and
putteth them away againe by chopping
and chaunging.

Mang&omacron;n&ibreve;cus, a, um, Suet. Pertai­
ning to the craft of polishing and trim­
ming of things.

Mang&omacron;mium, nij, n.g. Plin. The
craft of pampering, dressing, and making
of things saleable.

Mang&obreve;n&imacron;z&amacron;tus, a, um, Hermol.
Polished, painted or trimmed vp to make
it seeme the fayrer, or be the better solde.

Magn&obreve;nizo, as, Plin. To polish, paint,
or trimme vp a thing to make it to be the
better solde.

M&abreve;nia, æ, f.g. Madnesse, outrage,
furie: a disease rising of too much aboun­
dance of good blood, hauing recourse to
the head, whereby the partie is in a fury or
rage: also the hearb called Henbane. Iun.

M&abreve;ni&abreve;cus, Iun. Brainesick, madde,
depriued of common sense.

Maniæ, arum, f.g. Iun. Hobgoblins
and such like deformed and mishapen i­
mages, or imagined spirits, as nurses doe
fraie their babes withall to make them
leaue crying.

M&abreve;n&ibreve;ca, æ, f.g. A sleeue of a gar­
ment or a flappe couering the hande, the
handsleeue. Manica Hippocratis, vid.
Saccus vinarius.

Manicæ, arum, f.g. Virg. Manakles to
tie & wring the handes: also gauntlets
and splentes, Iuv. mittens, long glooues,
Plin. Iun.

M&abreve;n&ibreve;c&amacron;tus, a, um. Having sleeues
or gauntlets, sleeued, gloued.

M&abreve;n&ibreve;con, called also Dorychnion,
Plin. A kinde of the hearb Strychnis,
whereof if one take a dramme weight, he
shall seeme to see diuers and pleasant
shewes, if he take 2. in 3. daies in will
make him mad, of 3. it will kill him.

Manicleatus, a, um, Isid.  vid. Ma­
nicatus.

M&abreve;n&ibreve;c&umacron;la, æ, f.g. Plaut. A little

M&abreve;n&ibreve;fest&amacron;rius, a, um, Plaut. Open­
lie knowne, notorious, taken in the deed.

M&abreve;n&ibreve;fest&emacron;, & manifestò, adverb.
Clearelie, plainlie, manifestlie, euident­
lie, certainlie, openlie, in the verie deed
doing.

M&abreve;n&imacron;festo, as, Ovid. To manifest,




to make apparant, to bewray.

M&abreve;n&ibreve;festus, a, um. Manifest, cleare,

M&abreve;n&ibreve;p&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. Plin. An hand­
full, a gripe, a bundell, a bottell. also a

and tent: and that band is called Mani­

Manius, nij, m.g. Iun. A childe

Manliana, orum, n.g. Plin. A kinde
of apples so called of Manlius who first
grafted them. Manliana imperia, Liv.
Hard, seuere, cruell.

Manna, æ, f.g. Plin. In the scrip­
ture it is a delicate thing that God cau­
sed to fall from heauen in great aboun­
dance in maner of a dewe, white, and
like a coriander seed, in eating verie
pleasant: in Phisick it is a maner of dewe
congealed on trees and plants, and so is
gathered in certaine countries, and re­
serued as a gentle purger of choler. Ga­
len calleth it Mel aerium. Aier dew
or Manna. Manna thuris, Plin. The
manna or honie which hangeth vpon the
Frankincense tree, crummes and mam­
mocks of frankincense.

Mann&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. Mart. A litle
ambling nagge, a little horse, or colte.

Mannus, ni, Horat. Idem.

M&amacron;no, as. To spring, issue, gush, or
runne out as water doth, to droppe out,
to runne out or downe as sweat out of the
pores, to trickle downe: to descend, to
proceed: to goe, or spread, or be sowen a­
broad or ouer, to passe, to be conveighed,
to serue or stretch, to increase.

M&abreve;n&omacron;barb&ubreve;li, Sipont. Dartes

Manon, Plin. A kinde of sponge, som­
what thinne and soft.

Mansio, onis, f.g. verb. à maneo.
An abiding or tarying, a lodging or bai­

the place where currours and postes did
stay and chaunge their horses or wagons.

M&abreve;rasmus, mi, m.g. Iun. The third

rall heat hath so preuailed in the substan­

bers, that the naturall moisture thereof is
cleane exchausted and consumed, & ther­
by is become vtterlie vncurable.

M&amacron;t&ebreve;ria, e. Matter or stuffe whereof

booke, oration, or poesie. Materia vitiosa,

Greatest or moste in estimation, verie

Optimus maximum fundus, Cels. Land
holden in franke tenure.

M&ebreve;diast&imacron;nus, m.g. A drudge or

command: the phisicians cal it the vpper­
most thin skinnes in the bellie, which be a
certaine mdidle wall, deuiding the wholl
as it were into two little bellies.

M&ebreve;d&ibreve;c&amacron;b&ibreve;lis, le, Ovid. Curable, medi­

M&ebreve;d&ibreve;c&amacron;ment&amacron;rius, rij, m.g. An

M&ebreve;d&ibreve;c&abreve;ment&amacron;rius, a, um, Plin.
Pertaining to medicines.

M&ebreve;d&ibreve;c&amacron;ment&omacron;sus, a, um, Cato. That
is medicinable, that cureth or healeth:
that is in stead of a medicine.

Medicamentum, ti, n.g. A medi­
cine, a salve. Medicamentum aborti­
vum, Marcell. That destroyeth and ca­
steth the child out of the wombe, by cau­
sing an aborssement. Attrahens, Iun.
That draweth out corruption and matter
from the bottome. Cicatricem ducens,
Iun. A salve that bringeth a skin or
thin scar ouer a wound or sore. Discusso­
rium, Iun. That driueth away a maladie
or disease through the pores of the skin.
Medicamentum acræpalum anasto­
moticum, anodynum, aquiducum, ato­
cium, crustisicum, depascens, degla­
bratorium, depilatorium, discusiori­
um, diureticum, dropax, ecbolion,
ecphracticum, ectyloticum, emolli­
ens, emmoton, emplasticum, eruga­
torium, escaroticum, extersorium,
exulceratorium, glutinans, hydrago­
gum, incarnans, masticatorium, me­
tasyncriticum, obstipans, obstruens,
osculans, penicularium, præsens,
præsentaneum, prophylacticum, psi­
othrum, pyroticum, relaxans, rare­
faciens, repellens, repurgans, sangui­
nem sistens, siccans, soporiferum, ster
natorium, stupefaciens, suppurato­
rium, tentipellium, theriacum, ven­
trifluum, vrinale, Iun. vide suis
locis.

M&ebreve;dimnum, ni, n.g. & Medimnus,

doth containe onely 108. Libras mensu­
rales, or 48. Choenicas: it is almost two
bushels of ours.

M&ebreve;d&ibreve;um, dij, n.g. The middest: a

M&ebreve;dius, a, um. The middle, halfe, e­
quallie distant from the extremities, be­
tween both, meane, neither to be praised,
nor dispraised: also manifest, common to
all, to be seene, or easilie attained to of e­
uerie man: indifferent, doubtfull, vn­
knowne.

M&ebreve;d&ibreve;usf&ibreve;d&ibreve;us, adverb. A manner
of othe, and it is all one with Mehercu­
les, as ye would say, So the sonne of Iupi­

By the faith of God, or of the daie time.

Medo, &omacron;nis, * Mulse, or water and
honie.

M&ebreve;dulla, æ, f.g. Marow in bones, in
hearbs and shrubs the pith or harte: also
strength, the inward partes of the heart
or minde. Medulla arboris, Iun. The
middle, heart, pith, sap, or life of the tree.
 Medulla panis, Iun. The pith or crum
of a lofe: all between the vpper and ne­
ther crust. Medulla spinalis, Iun. The




marrow or pith of the backbone.

M&ebreve;dull&ibreve;tus, adverb. Plaut. Inward­

M&ebreve;dull&ubreve;la, æ, f.g. The tender marow.

Melanæetus, ti, m.g. Iun. A birde

M&ebreve;lanch&obreve;lia, æ, f.g. Melancholie,
blacke choler, a kind of madnesse rising of
melancholie. Melancholia hypochon­
drica, sive flatulenta, aut flatuosa,
Iun Melancholie or black choler vnder
or about the short ribs, or windie melan­
cholie, which is bred of ach and sorenes
about the saide partes, from whence a
black fome arising doth hurte and trouble
the minde.

M&ebreve;lanch&obreve;licus, a, um. Melancholike,
full of black choler, sad, sullen, solitary,
heauie.

M&ebreve;rens, tis, part. Ovid. Deseruing.


M&ebreve;reo, es, ui, &emacron;re, & Meteor, eris,
&ibreve;tus sum, &emacron;ri, depon. To deserue, to me­
rite, to get, to haue gaine or aduantage:
also to take wage, to serue for wages, to
take a souldiers pay. Bene mereri, to doe
a pleasure or good turne, to deserue wel of
one. Male mereri. To doe one a displea­
sure or ill turne: to deserve no fauoure at
ones hand.

M&ebreve;r&ebreve;tr&imacron;ci&emacron;, adverb. Plaut. Whorish­
lie, like a harlot.

M&ebreve;r&ebreve;tr&imacron;c&imacron;um, cij, n.g. Tranq. Whor­
dome or brotherly.

M&ebreve;r&ebreve;tr&imacron;cius, a, um. Pertaining to
brothelrie, whordome, or harlots, whorish.




M&ebreve;r&ebreve;tr&imacron;cor, &amacron;ris, Colum. To liue in
brothelrie, to play the harlot.

M&ebreve;r&ebreve;tr&imacron;c&ubreve;la, læ, f.g. dim. à Mererix.
A little harlot.

Meretrix, ic&ibreve;s, f.g. A whore, an har­
lot, a light housewife. Meretrix qua­
drantaria, Cæcil. That will be hired for
a farthing.

Merga, gæ, f.g. Plaut. A pitchforke, a
forke wherewith sheaues of corne are cast
vp: a manner of reaping hookes or sithes.
also merle or white earth like chaulke.

Merges, &ibreve;tis, f.g. Virg. A gripe of
corne in reaping, or so much corne or hay
as one with a pitchforke or hooke can take
vp at a time.

Mergina, e, f.g. Diosc. The hearb cal­
led Smilax aspera.

Mergo, is, si, sum, ere. To drowne or
sink in the water, to deep, to ouerwhelme:
also to thrust in, Claud. to cast into great
debt. Vlp.

Merg&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. Iun. A little diuer,
or didapper, called an arsefoote, because
his feete doe ioyne close to his arse.

Mergus, oris, n.g. * A bucket.

Mergus, gi, m.g. Var. A name com­
mon to sundrie birdes of the sea, as a Car­
morant, a gull, and certaine other, but
moste commonly a Carmorant: in a vine,
a braunch turned bowewise, and hauing
the toppe set into the ground. Mergus
magnus, Iun. vid. Cataractes.

Meris, Diosc. An hearb called also
Tripolium.

Merismos,* A figure called also Di­
stributio.

M&ebreve;r&ibreve;tissimo, adverb. Of a verie

cause: for his good deseruing sake, or as

Meritissimum, mi, n.g. Plaut. The
greatest merit or desert.

M&ebreve;r&ibreve;to, as, Plin. To gaine, to be ren­

M&ebreve;r&ibreve;t&omacron;rium, rij, n.g. Iuv. An house
or lodging wherevnto a man is receiued

adulterie, or for fleshlie pleasure.

M&ebreve;r&ibreve;t&omacron;rius, a, um. That is let or set
for aduantage. Meritorius puer. One
that suffereth himselfe to be abused a­
gainst nature: a boye with whome carnal
pleasure is had as with a wench. Taber­
na meritoria, vid. Meritorium.

M&ebreve;r&ibreve;tum, ti, n.g. A benefite or plea­

or as one hath deserued, a default.

M&ebreve;r&ibreve;tus, a, um, part. à Mereor. That
hath deserued, that hath done a pleasure
or displeasure: iustlie and deseruedlie,
&c. he that by doing a good turne hath
deserved well: due, worthie. also passi­

M&ebreve;r&obreve;b&ibreve;bus, a, um, Plaut. That drin­

M&ebreve;rops, &obreve;pis, m.g. Virg. A birde

Drowned, ouerwhelmed, couered or wa­

often: also to make one sorowfull.

Mesentericæ venæ.* Braunches of
the vaine called Porta, which conuey
the iuice of the meate concocted from
the stomach to the liuer.

M&ebreve;sent&ebreve;rium, rij, n.g. Iun. The mi­
dle of the bowells or entrails: a certaine
thicke and fattie skin, or the double skins
that fasten the bowells to the backe and
each to other, and also wrappeth and in­
closeth a number of veines being braun­
ches of the great carying veine, by which
both the guts are nourished, and the iuice
of the meate concocted is conueyed to the
liuer to be made blood.

M&ebreve;s&obreve;ch&obreve;rus, ri, m.g. Sidon. He that
standing in the midst of the companie, gi­

some other thing.

M&ebreve;s&obreve;craneum.* The crowne of the

M&ebreve;s&obreve;m&ebreve;l&amacron;s, Plin. A pretious stone

lour by the middest.

Meson, Fest. The person of a Cooke,
mariner, or such like in a comedie or ra­
ther a meane or mixt person, which is
neither servile, nor altogether free.

M&ebreve;s&obreve;nauta, æ, m.g. Iun. He that

M&emacron;ta, tæ, f.g. A butte or pricke to

bout the which they rod their horse round

stone of a mill: also a Pyramis or three

M&emacron;trenchytæ, Gal. Instruments

cines into the bellie.

M&ebreve;tr&emacron;ta, tæ, (sive metreta Atttica)
f.g. Colum. As Dioscorides saith, it
containeth tenne Congios, that is of our
measure tenne gallons, and tenne pintes,
which is a leauen gallons and an halfe.
Georgicus Agricola and Iunius saie,
it conteineth 12. Congios. that is 72.
Sextarios, and then it is of our measure
13. gallons and a halfe, vnlesse ye wil
take vid. Sextarius, as Phisitians doe for 18.
ounces, and not for 24. as Budæus
doth. Metreta Syriaca, conteineth 120.
Sextarios, Iun.

measure.

Metropolitanus, & Metropolini­
tes,* Of the cheife or mother citie.

M&emacron;tropolitanos, Isid. The bishop of
the chiefe citie, now an Archbishop.

Metrum, tri, n.g. Colum. A mea­
sure, demension, or verse. Metrum bioti­
cum, Victor. A measure whereby we buy
and sel whatsoeuer is requisite and neces­
sarie for our life, as 1. when we buy and
sel by measuring in lenght by the yard,
&c. 2. by weight, 3. by the bushel, pecke,
&c. 4. by the pottle, quart, pint, &c.

Millefies, * idem quod millies.

Mimus, mi, m.g. A iester or vice, a
counterfeiter of mens doings and man­

To beare the burden, to sing the plaine

Min pro mihine. Pers.

Mina, næ, f.g. It is both a summe of
mony, and a poyse or weight: in money
it is 100. Drachmæ, that is of old sterling
mony 35. s. 4.d. or after others account
which take Denar&ibreve;us Romanus (which
is all one with Drachma) for 7.d. it com­
meth to 58.s.4.d. When it is taken for a
poyse, it weigheth twelue ounces, and a
halfe, so that it is more than the Romaine
pound by foure Drachmes. Also a mea­
sure of ground containing 122. foote in
length, and as many in breadth. Varr. A
sheepe pylde vnder the bellie, Varr.

Misocali,* They that hate al kind of

Missa pro defunctis, Iun. A foule

vnto.

Missiculo, as, Plaut. To send often.

Miss&ibreve;le, is, n.g. Plin. A dart, stone, or

Miss&ibreve;lia, um, n.g. Suet. Things that

in a largesse among the people, as bread,

Miss&ibreve;lis, le, Pli. That may be throwne,

Missio, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. à Mitto. A
sending away, licence to depart: leaue, li­
cence, or a passeport graunted to a souldi­
er: whereof there were three sortes. Mis­
sio honesta, Iun. A lawful licence, ei­
ther before or after the warre is finished,
but yet with the consent of the general.
Causaria, Vlp. A pasport made to a soul­
dier that is sicke, wounded, or vnseruice­
able, whether he doe counterset or not.
Ignominosa, Iun. A shamful or reproch­
ful pasport, which is giuen in respect of
some notorious offence, whereupon the par­
tie is discharged and put out of paie and
seruice.

Missus, a, um, part. Sent, cast, hurled,
throwen, shot forth: let passe, let out, spo­
ken, ended, laying aside. Missum facere.
To suffer to depart, to demisse, to omit
or passe ouer, to let passe, not to speake,
talke, or meddle any more, &c. to leaue, to
mitigate or asswage, to put away.

Missus, us, m.g. verb. A cast, a hurle:
also a messe or seruice of meat, Lampri.
a sending, Cæs. a course, a turne, a bring­
ging in of things by turne or order, Suet.

Mithrax, Plin. A stone of the rose co­

A singular confection vsed in phisicke,

M&imacron;tis, te. Meeke, mild, gentill, soft,

M&imacron;tra, træ, f.g. A mitre: also an at­

Mitto, is, misi, ssum, ere. To send,

passe, to omit, not to speake of, to giue, to
send as a present: to cast, hurle, or fling: to
bring or put forth: also to write, to speake
and vtter.

Miva. æ. * An Arabian word, signi­
fying the iuice of fruits boyled vntill they
be as thicke as honie: now it is taken for a
syrrup made with the iuyce of quinces,
wine, suger or honie.

an to their father, & a barbarian to their

M&omacron;v&ibreve;lis, & Mobilior, us. Mooueable,
that may be mooued, actiue: mutable, wa­
uering, light, vnconstant, wagging.

M&omacron;b&ibreve;l&ibreve;tas, &amacron;tis, f.g. Mooueablnesse,
wagging, vnconstancie, mutablenesse: a
promptnes and readines.

Modi, orum, m.g. The measures,
rests, times or pauses in singing or play­
ing. Modos concidere & frangere.
The voice falling to sing and as it were
to gather strength, or to fal from the high­

M&obreve;di&amacron;lis, le, Plaut. That which con­

M&obreve;di&amacron;tio, &omacron;nis, f.g. Digest. A mea­
sure containing a bushell: it is also a mea­

M&obreve;d&ibreve;cè, adverb. A litle, somwhat,
meanlie, measurablie, not too much, not
too litle, reasonably, contentedlie, patient­

M&obreve;d&ibreve;cum, adverb. Plaut. A litle,

M&obreve;d&ibreve;cum, ci, n.g. Iuv. A litle or

M&obreve;d&ibreve;cus, a, um. Litle, small, few,
briefe, measurable, reasonable, indiffe­
rent, that exceedeth not, that is not too

M&obreve;d&ibreve;f&ibreve;c&amacron;tio, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. à Mo­
dificor, Sen. Measuring or bringing in

M&omacron;d&ibreve;f&ibreve;c&amacron;tus, a, um. Drawne and
chaunged from it proper nature to some
other vse: also chewed, &c.

M&obreve;d&ibreve;f&ibreve;cor, &amacron;ris, depon. To take the
measure of a thing, to measure.

M&obreve;di&obreve;lus, li, m.g. dim. à Modius,
Vitruv. A litle bushell, a bucket to take
or draw water out of a well or pit, and it
is also called Modiolus acceptatorius
Front. a litle cup to drinke in like a gob­
let: the name of a cart wheele: also an
instrument that surgeons vse to cut out a
small bone withall, called a trep and iron,
or the round saw of Hippocrates. Modi­
olus erogatorius, Front. A bucket
that goeth with a pullie, or some such de­
uise, and is lifted on high when it is full of
water, and so emptied. Modiolus rotæ,
Plin. the stocke or naue whereon the
spokes be fastned.

Modiperator &omacron;ris, Var. One ordai­
ned to see measure kept in bankets: or he
that did appoint the guests a certain law
and measure of drinking.

M&obreve;dius, dij, m.g. A measure of al­
most halfe a bushell, or as some count it,
our pecke and an halfe: we call it a bu­
shell: it was among the Romanes a mea­




sure of drie things conteining 16. Sexta­
rios. Also the hole or place wherein the
mast of the shippe is put. Modius agri,
Var. A square peece of ground in the
field being 100 foote long, and as manie
broad: Modius vini, Bud. 36 Sextaries
of wine, and euerie Sextarie containeth
8. pintes Parys, that is, 8. quartes En­
glish.

M&obreve;d&obreve;, adverb. temporis. Now,
now late, of late, while ere, a litle while
a goe, a time verie litle past, present, or
instant: so, so that: also onlie, at the least,
notwithstanding, sometime, one while.
 Modò vel tantum non, Terent.
Almost.

Pæonia, as big as a bull: being narrowlie

dure, which if it light vpon the hunter,

Mult&ibreve;plex, &ibreve;cis, adject. Manifold,
of diuers and sundrie sortes or waies: va­
riable, chaungeable, full of varietie, or
intreating of diuers and sundry matters:
doubtfull, that may be interpreted diuers
waies.

Multo, as. To punish, to punish by the
purse, to beat, to condemne, to put to a
fine, to intreat ill, to vexe, to put to paine:
also to depriue or cast out of. also to hus­

fore.

Mult&omacron;p&ebreve;r&emacron;, Plaut. Verie greatlie.

farre, exceeding much, earnestly, hartely.

Multus, a, um. Much, manie, great,
long, bigge and thick. Multam noctem,
Late in the night. Multo mane. Earlie
in the morning.

Mus, &umacron;ris, m.g. A mouse. Mus agre­

A rat. Odoratus vel peregrinus, Iero.
A muske cat. Mus araneus, Plin. A
kind of mouse called a shrew, which if he
goe ouer a beasts backe, he shal be lame in
the chine: if it bite, he swelleth to the hart,
and the beast dieth. Muris cauda, Iun.
vid. Malva major.

Musc&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. dim. à mus. A
little mouse or rat: also a muscle or fleshie
part of the body compact of flesh, veins,
sinewes, & arteris, seruing especially to
the motion of some part of the bodie by
meanes of the sinewes in it: also an en­
gine of warre, vnder which men safely ap­
proch to the walles of a towne to fill the
ditches: Cæs. a fish which is guid to the
whale that he runneth not vpon rockes,
Claud.

Muscus, sci, m.g. Virg. Mosse grow­
ing vpon trees or other places. Musci co­
ma interiecta navium commissuris
ferruminare textus, Plin. To solder, or
calke the ioynts of ships with mosse. Mu­
scus marinus, Iun. Sea mosse, flauke.

Mseacum, ci, n.g. Plin. A worke
cunningly painted, so that it seemed to be

Muse&abreve;rius.* He that painteth such
workes.

M&umacron;s&ibreve;ca, cæ, vel Musice, es, f.g. Mu­
sicke: it was vsed for studie of humanitie,
and especially poetrie. Hereof some make
3. kindes, 1. with the voice. 2. with the
hand. 3. with blowing: or (as the masters
of musike call it) Vocall, instrumentall,
& proportionall. also of musicall instru­
ments there be 3. kindes. 1. in blowing, as
the Organes, the Flute, &c. 2. in strings
or wyers, as the Lute, the Virginalles,
&c. 3. in striking or beating, as the Drum,
&c. Iun.

Musica, orum. Idem.

M&umacron;s&ibreve;c&emacron;, adverb. Plaut. Delectably:
in an harmony: also perfectlie, that lack­
eth nothing.

ing man.

csike. Ars musica. Terent. Comedies.

Muss&ibreve;t&amacron;bundus, a, um. * One that

betweene his teeth.

Muss&ibreve;tandus, a, um, Terent. To be

Mussitatio, onis, f.g. Iun. A mum­
bling or speaking betweene the teeth.

Muss&ibreve;to, as, frequent. à Musso. Liv.
To mutter or talke often softly betweene
themselues, or to holde his peace and not
speake.

Musso, as, Plaut. To mutter betweene
the teeth, as they doe that dare not speak:
to murmure, to repine, to grunt: to com­
plaine with soft noise: to talke softly and
secretlie, to keepe silence, to doubt.

Mustum, sti, n.g. Newe wine, ale, or

Mustus, a, um, Plaut. New, fresh.

Mutab&ibreve;lis, le. Chaungeable, mutable,
vnconstant, variable: vnsteadfast, wa­

into what fashion we list.

Mutab&ibreve;l&ibreve;tas, &amacron;tis, f.g. Chaungeable­

Mutans, tis, Part. à Muto, Quint.
Chaunging, altering, mutable.

M&umacron;tatio, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. A chaun­
ging, a remoouing: also exchaunge, Ter.

Mutatus, a, um, part. Chaunged, tur­
ned, altered, made otherwise, transformed
farre vnlike.

Mutilapides, vid. Mutus.

Mutia, &omacron;rum. An hole daie dedica­

Muticus, a, um, vt Spicæ muticæ,
Varr. Eares of corne without a beard.

M&ubreve;t&ibreve;latus, a, um, part. a Mutilor
Minished in some thing, hauing some
parte cut or broken off, maimed, made
vnversite, lacking of the full number.

M&ubreve;l&ibreve;lo, as, Terent. To cutte of, mi­
nish, take awaie, make vnperfit, or
maime.

M&ubreve;tilus, a, um. Lacking some princi­
pall parte, limme, or member: mutilate,
lame, maimed, vnperfit.

Mutincusis color, Iun. A naturall
colour of wooll or cloth not died. vid. Im­
pluviatus.

M&umacron;tio, is, &imacron;vi, &imacron;tum, &imacron;re, Terent.
To speake softelie as with an vnperfit
voice: to mutter.

M&umacron;t&ibreve;to, as, Gell. To feast one ano­
ther, also to exercise or doe a thing.

M&umacron;to, as. To chaunge, to translate,
to alter, to turne, to barter or exchaunge
one thing for another: to chaunge from
one nature or colour to another: to vnsay,
to vndoe. Mutari civitate. To be made
free in a citie and forsake the right that
he had in another before.

Muto, &omacron;nis, Iun. The priuie member
of a man.

Mutoniatus, Iun. That hath a priuie
member of a great or large size.




Muttum, ti, vel rectiùs, Mutto,
onis, à verbo mutio, Cornut. A
worde.

M&umacron;tu&amacron;t&ibreve;o, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. à Mutu­
or. A borowing.

M&umacron;tu&amacron;t&ibreve;tius, a, um, Gell. Borowed.


M&umacron;t&ubreve;&amacron;tus, a, um. Borowed, taken of
another.

Mutuè, adverb. vid. Mutuo.

Mutuiter, pro Mutuo, Non.

M&umacron;t&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. Cato. A stay cut
out of stone or timber in building to beare
vp the summer or other part: in masonry
they call it a corbell: in timber worke, a
bragget: shouldering peeces, or such
like: also a fish of that name, which the
Normans call a Plion, the Venetians a
Capporoll, Horat.

M&umacron;tu&omacron;, adverb. Togither, one ano­
ther, mutuallie.

M&umacron;tuo, as, Valer. &

M&umacron;tuor, &amacron;ris, depon. To lende, to bo­
row, to take of another and vse as his
owne.

Mutuum, adverb.pro Mutuo.

M&umacron;tus, a, um. That can not speake,
dumbe, speechlesse, tongueles, that ma­
keth no noyse, without wordes: also qui­
et, still, silent. Mutilapides in agro­
rum diuisionibus dicebantur, fine
inscriptione appositi, ideo quia nul­
la significatione apparerent, quoto
loco numerarenrut, Hyginus. Mutæ
literæ, Fest. Certaine consonants. Mutæ
cicadæ, * not because they doe not sing
at all, but because they sing but litle.

M&umacron;tuum, tui, n.g. A lone, that which
is borowed.

M&umacron;tuus, a, um. Lent or borowed, mu­
tuall, one another.

Mya, æ, f.g. Plin. A kinde of shell­

Ruscus.

Myaces, Plin. A kinde of shellfish.

hearb with a stalke like fenell and leaues
like madder, the iuice whereof is good for
sores in the mouth.

Mycanius, Iun. Balde.

Mycopros,* Mice dung.

Mydas,* A worm breeding in beans.

Mydri&amacron;sis, p.b. A disease of the eyes
named Disatatio pupillæ: it chaungeth
not the colour of the eyes, but maketh
things seeme lesse then they are.

Myg&abreve;le, es, f.g. p.b. A field mouse
called a shrew.

play called hoodman blind, blind bob, or
blindman buffe.

Mylacris, idis, Pollux. A kinde of
Blatta, as big as a grashopper, breeding
about milles, and feeding vpon meale.

Myle, es, f.g. Galen. The roote of a
dock or wilde sorrell.

Myloecos, p.l. Plin. A certaine but­
terflie being in milles.

Mylos.* A mill.

Mymphur, Sipont. A turners spin­
dle or pin.

My&omacron;pia,* Poreblindnes.

Myops, Plin. Poreblind: that can not

the thing that is to be seene or read.

sines, or mouseare.

sweet roote, and is called also Eryngium.

thousand.

fruite growing in India like plummes or

balan Ben, or the nut of Egypt: of which
be diuerse kindes verie gentillie purging
all superfluous humours, and much com­
forting nature.

Myrobrecharij, Plaut. Are they
which be annointed with sweet oyles.

Myrobrechi,* Oyle vessells.

Myr&obreve;p&omacron;la, æ, m.g. p.b. Plaut. A

Myr&obreve;th&emacron;cium, cij, n.g. p.b. A boxe
of sweet ointments.

Myrrh&imacron;t&emacron;s, Plin. A pretious stone ha­

whereby a thing is properly in that kinde

clination, or motion.

Lent. A litle boate: a small barke or ship.

N&amacron;v&ibreve;g&ibreve;um, gij, n.g. All sortes of
vessells to sayle or row in: also sayling:
the conducting or guiding of a ship, Scæ­
vol. Navigium actuarium, Cæs. vid.
navis actuaria.

N&amacron;v&ibreve;go, as, &amacron;vi, &amacron;tum, &amacron;re. To goe or
be carried on the water in a vessell: to
sayle.

N&amacron;vis, is, f.g. A ship, a boate, a bark,
a vessell of the sea. Navem solvere, O­
vid. To depart the land, and take sea. Na­
vis actuaria. A barke or vessell for pas­
sage that goeth with oares and sailes to­
gether. Actuariola, horia, vel oraria,
Iun. A shore ship, or a small barke to saile
neare to the shore. Aperta, Iun. An open
ship, a ship without a deck. Constrata
vel tecta. A covered ship, a ship with a
deck. Frumentaria, gravis, oneraria.
A marchaunts ship, or a ship for burthen.
 Longa, Cæs. A galley, or long barke.
 Præsidiaria, Iun. A ship of warre or ayd.
 Prætoria, Iun. The admirals ship. Ro­
strata, Liv. A ship stemmed, beaked, or
pointed with brasse, or hauing an iron
nose. Speculatoria, A brigantine, a foist,
a barke for espiall. Vectoria, Vlp. A
barge, a forrie, or anie other vessell ser­
ving for passage. Navis alvus, Iun. The
bulke or bellie of the ship. Arbor, Paul.
The mast of a ship. Armamenta, Iun. The
munition or necessarie furniture of a ship.
 Commissura, Fab. the ioyning or fra­
ming of a ship. Commissuras navium
feruminare musci coma, Plin. To stop
the ioynts of shippes with mosse, okam, or
towe, properlie called to calke. Navium
statio, Virg. A bay, station, or rode for
shippes.

Nunc, adverb. temporis. Now, euen
now. Nunc demú, nunc denique, nunc
iá, Now at last, at this present, at this time,
now and neuer before. Nunc verò, idem.
also but now. Nunc nunc, Virg. Even
verie now, at this verie moment. Nunc
nuper. Terent. Even now, latelie, now,
not long since. Nunc primum, Plaut.
First and formost.

Nunc&ubreve;po, as. To name, to call by some

nuncupare, Plin. Iu. To make a solemne
vow with formall wordes. Testamentum
nuncupare, Plin. By worde of mouth
without writing to make and declare his
last will.

N&umacron;trix, &imacron;cis, f.g. verb A nource: also
a nourcery or place whre men graffe &
plant trees or hearbs, to the end afterward
to remooue them, and set them in a gar
den or Orchard, Plin. Nutrices also are
a womans pappes or teates, Catul.

N&umacron;tus, us, m.g. A signe that one ma­
keth with his eyes or head: a beeke, a nod:
ones will, pleasure, or appointment: the
bending, inclination, or declining of a
thing downeward: also a fall, Val. Flac.

Nux, n&ubreve;cis, f.g. All fruites that haue
a hard shell, a nutte: a nut tree. Nux a­
vellana, Pontica, Prænestina, mini­
ma, Iun. An hasel nut or filberd. Basili­
ca regia, iuglans, Iun. A great nut, a
walnut. Græca vel Thasia, Iun. An al­
mond. Molosca, Iun. A peach. Vnguen­
taria vel odorata, Iun. A nutmeg.
 Pinea, Iun. A pineaple. Rancida, Iun.
A moldy or musty nut. Vitiosa, Plaut.
A faultie, rotten, or vnsound nut. He­
racleotica. Macrob. A chestnut.
 Nuces, Pers. Childish pastimes. Ludere
nucibus, Catul. To play at the top castle,
or other games with nuts.


N Y

Nyct&abreve;lops, &omacron;pis, com. g. Plin. He that
seeth in the day time well, in the euening
a little, at night nothing at al.

Nyctegretium, vid. Nyctilops.

Nycteris, &ibreve;dis, f.g. Plin. A reremouse,
or bat.

Nyct&ibreve;c&obreve;rax, &amacron;cis, Iun. A night crow
or rauen.

Nyct&ibreve;l&emacron;ia, orum, n.g. * Sacrifices
made to Bacchus in the night time.

Nyct&ibreve;lops, &obreve;pis, Plin. An hearb cal­
led also Nyctegretum, because that it
shineth a farre of in the night time. It is
also called Chenomychon, because
that at the first sight thereof geese are
made afraid.

Nympha, æ, f.g. A nimph: a bride or
new maried wife: also young bees before
they flie, Plin. the holownes or voide
space in the nether lip, Iun. the cup of the
flower by little and little gaping and ope­
ning it selfe, Iun. A little peece of flesh
rising vp in the midst of a womans priuie
part, which closeth the mouth of the neck,
and driueth cold from it, Iun.

Nymphæ, arum, f.g. The goddesses of
waters, young bees before they flie.

Nymphæa, æ, f.g. Plin. A water lilly,
a water rose, yellow & white Nenuphar.

Nymphæum, i, n.g. Plin. A stew or
baine, a washing place: also a bride­
house, as when a hall or other large place
is prouided to keepe the bridall in, because
the dwelling house is not of sufficient
roome to serve the turne, Iun.

Nymphus, phi, m.g. * A bridegroome.

Nysia, æ, f.g. * A certain kinde of Ivie.

Nyssia, æ, f.g. * A barre or raile from
which runners fetch their feese or race:
also the marke it selfe.

Obnoxi&ebreve;, adverb. Liv. Fearefullie,
like a subiect or salue. Non obnoxiè,
Plaut. Evidently.

Obnoxius, a, um, Plaut. that hath
deserued to be punished, guiltie, fautie, or




condemned, bounden, subiect: apt, open to,
in daunger to or of: obedient: that regar­
deth, &c. seruil, charged with, knowing
himselfe giuen to: dishonest, base: easie to
be hurt: sicklie, diseased. Arva obnoxia
curæ, Virg. That of necessitie must be
husbanded.

heauie and sad incountenance.

Obnunci&amacron;tio, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. A de­

thing ought not to be done, because of the
signification of ill luck.

Obnuncio, as. To tel or shew ill tidings

Ob&obreve;leo, es, &ubreve;i, &emacron;re, Plaut. To stink:

Ob&obreve;lus, li, m.g. Terent. A weight
containing three carrets, that is, halfe a
scruple: it is also a coyne, but variable, ac­
cording to the countrie: with vs it is an
halfpenie. Iunius taketh it for penie far­
thing of our monie. Oboli octo, 8. pence,
8. farthings, Iun. After our account 4.
pence. Obolus terræ. * Five foote in
breadth and tenne in length, which con­
taineth 50 foote square.

 Obscure aliquid ferre. To dissemble a

Obsc&umacron;rus, a, um. Obscure, darke,

waterish swelling, thinne and without
griefe, consisting of a colde intempera­
ture, and flegmatike matter: it is easilie
pressed downe with the finger, & leaueth
a dent and hollownes, the member re­
taining it natural or else a white colour.

OEnanth&amacron;rium, Aegin. The oile cal­
led OEnanthinum.

OEnagra, vid. OEnathara.

OEnanth&emacron;, es, f.g. Pli. An hearb ha­
uing a leafe like carets, a white floure, a
big stalke, and like orage, a great roote
with many round heads: also the flowre
of that wild vine which bringeth forth a
flowre onely, and no grapes. Gaza trans­
lateth it Vitiflora.

OEnanth&ibreve;nus, na, num, Plin. Of OE­
nanth.

OEnaria,* As Poets say, the leaues
of a vine.

OEnas,* A bird of the bignes of a cul
uer, which Gaza translateth Vinago

OEnathara.* The name of an hearb
like to the leafe of an almond tree.

OEnigena, Fest. Proceeding of wine.

OEnocratali. Aelian. Certaine raue­
nous birds like to swannes, but they haue
beneath their mouth a little gorge, into
which they swallow their meate greedely,
and after ward chaw it againe.

OEn&obreve;m&ebreve;l&imacron;, itos, Diosc. vel OEno­
melum, li, n.g. Isid. A drinke made of
honie and sowre wine.

OEn&obreve;ph&obreve;rum, ri, n.g. A wine pot,
flagon, or bottle.

OEn&obreve;ph&obreve;rus, ri, m.g. * A seruant
bringing wine to the boord.

OEn&obreve;pola, læ, m.g. * A tauerner, a
vintner.

OEn&obreve;p&omacron;lion, lij, n.g. Plaut. A wine
tauern.

OEnoptæ, Cæl. Rhod. They whose
dutie it was to see that all should drinke
alike, when the Grecians met at a feast.

OEnotrius pes, Diom.  vid. Bacchi­
us pes.

OEs&obreve;ph&abreve;gus, gi, * The gullet or pipe
which reacheth from the mouth to the
stomacke, and is as it were a passage for
meat and drinke.

OEstrum, stri, n.g. vel OEstrus, stri,
m.g. Virg. Madnesse or wood furie: also
a flie that maketh a great noise when he
flieth: it may seeme to be a gadbee, dun­
flie, brimsee, or horseflie that in the sum­
mer time vexeth cattell.

OEsypum, pi, n.g. s.b. Ovid. The filth
and greasines of cattle, proceeding of
sweat, and cleauing fast to the wooll of
their flankes and shoulders: the greasie &
sweatie filth of wool.


O F

Offa, æ, f.g. A morsel, gobbet, or peece
of flesh: a mouthful, a steake or collop, or
any like peece: a kind of meat made with
fatte broath, hard cheese, pepper, cina­
mon, &c. a goblet, lump, or little peece
of paste or dowe: also a pudding pie, a bag
pudding, Pli. Offa penita, Fest.
A peece
of flesh cut of with the tyale, the rump.
 Offa melle saporata, Virg. Honie
soppes.

Offæ, arum, Colum.  vid. Turundæ.


Off&amacron;rius, rij, m.g. Isid. A maker of
such meates and iunkets.

Off&amacron;tim, adverb. Isid. In morsells.

wooll: properlie, he which restoreth a co­
lour that was lost.

Offella, læ, f.g. dim. ab Offa, &  poe­




tis Ofella, Mart. A steake, a collop, a
little morsel or gobbet or flesh minced: al­
so pottage made with peeces of flesh.

Offend&ibreve;c&ubreve;lum, li, n.g. Plin. Iun. An
impediment, a let: also a doubt.

Offend&ibreve;mentum, ti, n.g. Fest. &

Offendix, &ibreve;cis, f.g. Fest. A riband or
lace wherewith a bonet or hat is knit fast
to the head: or rather the knot or button
of the lace, wherwith the cap or hat is fa­
stned or slacked.

Offendo, is, di, sum, &ebreve;re. To find by
chance, to meete with, to fall into, to light
vpon: to strike or hit a thing vnawares, to
hurt: to empaire, to be lothsome: to offend,
to doe amisse, to displease, discontent, mis­
like, or not to content: to find some fault,
not to away with: also to haue mishap or
ill successe in his doings. Offendi in ali­
quo. To be deceiued in his opinion that he
had in one. Offendere apud Iudices.
To plead ill, to be cast in his suite, to be con­
demned.

Offensa, sæ, f.g. An offence or displea­
sure, blame: also hurt and griefe, Cels.

Offens&amacron;c&ubreve;lum, li, n.g. * That which
is laid in a mans way, whereat he stum­
bleth.

Offensans, tis, part. ab Offenso,
Quint. Stopping, staying: iutting.

Offens&amacron;tor, oris, m.g. verb. He that
staggereth in reading, or he that readeth
otherwise then it is written Offensator
equus, Quint. A stumbling horse.

Offensio, onis, f.g. verb. ab Offendo.
Hurt or harme, staying, iutting, or stop­
ping: grudging, offence, griefe, ill will: di­
spleasure or hatred that one beareth to­
ward a man. also the fault or offence of
him that displeaseth: discontenting: a
stumbling. Offensiones belli. Losses or
ouerthrowes in warre.

Offensiunc&ubreve;la, læ, f.g. dim. ab Offen­
sio. A small offence or displeasure.

Offenso, as, frequent. ab Offendo,
Liv. To hit often, or to let, to thrust a­
gainst a thing that displeaseth.

Offensum, si, n.g. The fault in miscon­
tenting the audience.

Offensum est, impers. It hapned a­
misse, or otherwise then well, he chaun­
ced to offend or doe amisse.

Offensus, a, um, & Offensior, us.
Hurt, anoyed, displeased, offended, dis­
contended: somewhat angrie: odious, tript,
slipt, stumbling.

Offensus, us, m.g. verb. ab Offendo,
Lucret.  vid. Offensa.

Offercio, sis, si, tum, ire, ex Ob &
Farcio, Plaut. To stuffe or fill vp.

Off&ebreve;ro, fers, obt&ubreve;li, obl&amacron;tum, ferre,
ex Ob & Fero. To offer, proffer, present,
or come before, to put himselfe in, to put to,
to meete with: to giue willinglie, to pro­
mise: to doe, to giue occasion of, to cause
to haue: also to withstand, resist, or be a­
gainst.

Off&ibreve;ci&omacron;sus, Officiosior, Officiocis­

well and readilie. Officiosus dolor.
Griefe proceeding of a good and reaso­

Off&ibreve;cium, ij, n.g. Office, dutie of be­
hauiour in honestie and reason, a point, a

solemnities of interrement at ones burial.

O H

Oh, interject, Ter. A voice that wee
vtter when we see a friend whome of long
time wee have not seene: Admirantis,
what? Affirmantis, why? Dolentis, &
reprehendentis. Oh: Dolentis, & re­
prehensi, Alas. Exultantis, Oh heyda.
 Exultantis ob rem bene gestam, oh.

Oh, oh, oh, oh, Plaut. The sound of one
that sobbeth, weepeth, howleth, or cryeth
out in weeping.

Oho, Interiect. Ter. 
A voice signify­
ing one to be weary of that he seeth or hea­
reth: ho, ho.

Oho, Interiect. Plaut. 
An interie­
ction of marvelling.

and honie sodden togither.

Oniscos, Dorion. A fish called Asel­

and doth not much keepe companie with

Oppr&ibreve;mo, is, essi, ssum, &ebreve;re, ex Ob
& Premo. To oppresse, to weigh downe, to

quiet, quaile, or quench: to take sodenly
or come vpon: to ravish a woman: to pre­
vent, to overtake, or goe beyond one, to
slea. also to get of one or wrest out by force,
Plaut. to make one leave or forgoe, Plaut.

tresse.

Oppugn&amacron;tor, &omacron;ris, m.g. Verb. 
He
that seeketh the hurte of an other man, &

an assaulter, a wrong doer, a hinderer of
an others profite.

Oppugn&amacron;tus, a, um, part. Propert.
Assaulted, besieged.

Oppugno, as. To assault, to batter,
to lay siege vnto, to fight against, to en­
devour to hurt: to labour against one by
all meanes he can: also to reason against
a thing earnestlie.

Opp&ubreve;to, as, Plin. 
To cut of boughes,
to prune trees.

Opus, &ebreve;ris, n.g. p.b. A worke, deed,
matter, busines, trauell, or labour: a buil­
ding: also workemanship. Opere mag­
no, Plaut. Verie earnestlie. Opere ni­
mio. Exceedinglie. Opere tanto, Plaut.
So greatlie. Opus albarium, Iun.
White liming worke, or pargetting
worke. Coronarium, Plin. Round
and embossed worke. Emplecton,
Vitru. Worke well knit and couched to­
gither: properlie stones so layd, that their
fronts and partes which are in sight, being
smooth, and trim on both sides: their na­
turall substance remaineth rough & vn­
hewne to stuffe and fill vp the midst of a
wall, &c. Intestinum, vel sublicium.
Plin. Wainescot or feeling worke: ioyned
worke, or worke made of piles and postes.
 Isidomum, Plin. Of equall line, level,
and row: even. Pseudisodomum, Iun.
Of vnequal line, level, and rew: vneuen.
 Reticulatum, Iun. Net worke orlat­
tise worke. Signinum, Plin. Made with
shardes, and morter tempered togither, ci­
ment. Tectorium, Varro. Plasterers or
dawbers worke. Temporarium. Plin.
during but for a time: tide worke. Ope­
re intestino vestire parietes, Iun.To
couer wals with wainscot or ioyned work.

Opus, indecl. adject. Needfull, ex­
pedient, necessarie: need or want of.

Opusc&umacron;lum, li, n.g. dim. A little
worke, a litle labour.


O R

Ora, æ, f.g. p.l. The ende or extreame
part of any thing: the edge of a billement,
the ends & borders of countries: a region,
land, or countrie. a coast, a marches or
frontires: the hem or skirt of a garment,
the brim of a pot or any other measure, a
clime or parte of the firmament devided:
also the beginning of a thing, Fest.




Or&amacron;c&ubreve;lum, li, n.g. p.l. An oracle, sen­
tence, counsell, or answer giuen by God:
also a worthy & notable saying or iudge­
ment, Cato. The temple wherin oracles or
answers were given, Plin. A prophecie or
prediction, Ovid.

Orandus, a, um, part. p.l. Virg. To be
prayed vnto, to be intreated, requested, be­
sought, or sued vnto.

Oraria navis, Iun.  vid. Navis.

Orandus, a, um, part. Virg. That is to
bed intreated or praied vnto.

Otans, tis, part. ab Oro, p.l. Terent.
Which prayeth, desyring, intreating.

Or&amacron;ta, tæ. f.g. p.l. Fest.
vid. Aurata.

vtterance, words, a style, language, com
munication, praier, an oration, eloquence.

Or&amacron;t&ibreve;unc&ubreve;la, læ, f.g. dim. A little, o­
ration, a little talke, a short speech, or
briefe prayer.

Or&amacron;tor, oris, m.g. verb. An oratour,
an ambassadour, a spokesman: a headman,
a suter: an aduocate, a pleader: an in­
treater: he that can make a speech wisely,
aptly, and eloquently.

Or&amacron;t&omacron;ria, æ, & Oratrix, icis, f.g.
Quint. Rhetoricke.

or ambassadour: eloquently, rhetori­
callie.

ted wholly to praier.

Or&amacron;t&omacron;r&ibreve;us, a, um, n.g. p.l. Of or pertay­
ning to an oratour or ambassadour.

Praied, desired, intreated, besought.

quest, a thing desired, a petition.

pray­
ing, an intreating, a beseeching.

A de­
priuer or bereauer of one of a thing: also
