Orbicularis, Iun. The hearb sowbread
or swinebread.

Orb&ibreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;tim, adverb. Plin. Round
like a circle, or compasse.

Orb&ibreve;c&ubreve;l&amacron;rus, a, um. Made round in the
forme of a circle or compasse. Pomum or­
biculatum, Var. Pompe paradise.

Orb&ibreve;c&ubreve;lus, a, um, dim. ab Orbis, Ca­
to. Euerie smal round thing, a litle hoope,
or circle: also a pulley, Cato. the male or
rundle through which the latchet of the
shoe passeth, & is fastned with th etongue
of the buckle: the loope, Iun. A muske
ball, a pomander, Iun. Orbiculus alea­
torius, vid. Fritillus.

Orb&ibreve;cus, a, um, Var. Round in the fa­
shion of a cirle: circular.

Orb&imacron;le, is, n.g. Var. The ring or circle
of a cart: also the circuit of a roofe.

Orbis, is, m.g. A circle, a ring or round
circuite, a course, a round compasse: also
a round couer or trencher, a roundle to set
dishes on for foyling the table cloth: the
world: a continual course or succession of
things in writing with a certaine mea­
sure: a region or countrie: also a great
company or multitude of people, Ovid. a
yeare, Virg. a bottome of yarne, Ovid. An
oyle presse, Cato. a fish called a lompe, or
paddle, a seaowle, Iun. Cavus orbis,
Virg. a buckler or targate. Orbis salta­
torius. The daunsing of the round or in
a ring. Orbes in homine dicuntur
frontis foramina inter quæ latent o­
culi, Stat. also the eyes themselues,
Lactan.

Orb&ibreve;ta, e, f.g. A cart wheele, the track
or furrow of a cart wheele made in the
ground: also a way, a compasse or round­
nesse.

Orb&ibreve;tas, atis, f.g. The lacke of chil­
dren on the parents part, the lacke of pa­
rents on the childrens part, childlesnes,
any lacke.

pronus cùm esset, per orbes flexuo­
sos in exquiliarum collem duceret,
Fest.

Orbo, as. To take from, to depriue of a
thing, to bereaue of a thing that he set




teth much by.

Orbus, a, um. He that hath lost or doth
want his sight, or any thing that he lo­
ueth much, as father, mother, or any other
thing: fatherlesse and motherlesse: or a
father and mother hauing lost their chil­
dren: berest succourlesse, destitute & for­
saken. Legatio orba: that hath lost the
chiefe messenger. Orbi palmites, Col.
Vine branches that doe not bud and shoot
out young.

Orca, cæ, Plin. A great sea fish ene­
mie to the whale: also a great vessel for
wine, as butts, vats, and pipes, Var. a
vessel to keepe figges in, Plin. a pretious
stone, Plin. an earthen potte with a nar­
row mouth and a long necke, into which
children practised to cast nuttes, Pers.
a boxe like a funnell, wherein dice be sha­
ken adn cast on the table, Plin. a coffer
that womens paintings were kept in,
Plin.

Orchas, Iun.  vid. Orchite.

Orchestra, æ, f.g. A place betweene
the stage and the common seats, wherein
Senatours and Noble personages satte to
behold plaies and open games: sometime
the sessions of the Senate: a theater or
scaffold whereon musitians, singers, and
such like shew their cunning.

Orchites, is, f.g. Virg. A kinde of
olives to be eaten, beeing round and like
to codstones.

Orchis, &imacron;tis, Colum. The hearbe rag­
wort, gandergoose, or dog stone, hauing a
roote like two little codstones: also a kind
of fish, it is well knowne to be the hardest
of all fishes, which is called Orchis: it is
round and without scales, and consisteth
wholly of a head, or hath a heade bigger
then his bodie.

Orcins thesaurus, pro sepulchro,
Gell.

or Pluto. Orcinus libertus cùm nulli­
us libertus viventis sit. Ditis sive Or­
ci libertus nominatur. He which by
will directly is made free, and neuer had
a patrone aliue.

dead bodies doe lie.

Orc&ubreve;la læ, f.g. dim. ab Orca.Cato.
A little vessel for figges, or other seruice,

Orcus, ci, m.g. The darkenes of hell,
or a riuer in hell, hel it selfe. Cum orco
rationem habere vel ponere, Var. to
put himselfe in hazard of death, to get
somewhat.

A busie and naughtie fellow alwaies in

stones of the like fashion or quantitie laid in

Orno, as. To garnish, decke, trimme,

vp, commonlie named tenentare. wilde­
fetches or chokeweede.

Orobax,* The floure called the piony.

Or&obreve;b&imacron;a,* A kinde of frankincense in

like the blades of corne.

musick in an high tune that Arion vsed
when he cast himselfe into the sea.

Orthocala,* The beasts that haue the
cramp so in their feete, that they goe on
the top of their hoofe onelie.

Orthodoron, Iun. A spanne, the
length of the hand from the wrist to the
top of the litle finger.

Orth&obreve;doxia,* The right opinion or
faith.

Orth&obreve;doxus, a, um, Isid. He that

beleefe.




Orth&obreve;g&omacron;nius, a, um, Colum. That
hath right or euen corners.

Orth&obreve;g&omacron;nus, ni, m.g. * A right cor­
ner equall on both sides.

Orth&obreve;graphia, æ, f.g. Quint. The
right forme of writing, also a platte of
building drawn our with the figure of the
whole worke.

Orth&omacron;mast&ibreve;ca, Plin. Certaine fruites
that be like to teares.

Orthopuoea, æ, f.g. Cels. Such a
straightnes of breath, by stopping of the
lightes, that one can not breath, but hol­
ding his neck vpright.

Orthopnoicus, a, um, Plin. He that
hath the pipes of his lightes so stopped or
made streight, as he can not breath, but
holding his neck vpright.

Orthos,* Right, not crooked.

Orthostadios,* A garment worne
vngirded.

Orthost&abreve;ta, æ, m.g. Vitru A kinde

or stone so mortized or fastned.

Orthr&abreve;g&obreve;niscus, ci, m.g. Plin. A cer­
taine great fish that grunieth being ta­
ken, and is called a molebout.

Ortus, a, um, part. ab Orior. Borne,
bred, sprung, begunne or having begin­
ning, descended, come risen, that pro­
ceedeth.

Ortus, us, m.g. verb. ab Orior. A
springing, rising, or beginning: the east ri­

heauenlie bodies in our hemisphere: ones
birth or nativitie, a growing vp: also an
appearing, Virg.

Ortyg&obreve;m&emacron;tra, æ, m.g. Plin. The Cap­

Ortyx, gis, f.g. Plin. A quaile.

Oryx, gis, m.g. Colum. A certaine
wilde beast of the kinde of goates in A­
frike.

Oryza, æ, f.g. Horat. A graine cal­
led rice, wherewith they make pottage.


O S

Os, &omacron;ris, n.g. The mouth, visage, coun­
tenance, face, looke, favour, or voyce: the
proportion of all the bodie, presence, lan­
guage, tongue, pronuntiation, audacitie,
boldnes or hardines, a sturdie looke: ac­
cord or consent, reporte or commendation:
also a mouth, passage, or entrance of a
river or floud: also the vttermost parte of
a thing, the brime or edge, that which
is open in a thing, Virg. The beake or bill
of a birde, Ovid. the mouth of anie cup or
can, Fab. the bunghole, Iun.

Os, ssis, n.g. A bone: also the stone
that is in damsons, cheries, olives, dates,
and other like fruites. Os sacium, Iun.
The great bone wherevpon the ridge bone
resteth. Os leonis, Colum. A certaine
hearb with a purple flower. Os terræ re­
tectum obtegere. To cast the earth into
the graue, to fill it vp with earth.

Osa,* Lawes concerning devotion.

Osanna, in Hebrew Osianna, Isid.
I pray the save vs.

Osasum, pro Odi, Non.

Osc&emacron;do, &ibreve;nis, f.g. Gell. A fault or

Stomacacce.

Oscheum, Cels.  vid. Scrotum.

turn for the good estate of ones selfe and
his: also litle puppies or babies for children
to play withall, Iun.

Oscill&amacron;tio, &omacron;nis, f.g. Iun. A tottering
or hanging motton, which is a kinde of
game, commonlie vsed of children and
countrifolkes, wherein the ends of cords
being tied hard to a beame or tree, they
clime or swinge, as it were houering in
the aire: some take it for a gambell called
the baltring of Hixmare.

Oscillo, as, Plaut. To moue the mouth,
to bow downe.

Oscillum, li, n.g. dim. ab Oseulum,

Oscillo iactari, Iun. vid. Oscillatio.

Oscinis, vel Oscen, inis, com. g. A
bird that by his voice signifieth somewhat
to come: also anie singing bird, Plin.

Ostia, orum, n.g. Virg. The en­

Osti&amacron;rius, ij, m.g. Plin. A dorekeeper,

Ostimatim, adverb. From dore to dore,

euerie part one after another by name.

Ost&imacron;go, inis, f.g. Colum. The scabbe
in sheep, lambes, goats, or kids, about their
mouthes and lippes, being deadly to them
whiles they are suckelings.

Osti&omacron;lum, li, n.g. dim. ab Ostium,

Ostium, stii, n.g. A dore, gate, or entry:

Antæ.  Ostium fluminis. where a riuer

Ostracias, æ, m.g. Plin. A certaine
pretious stone brickle like a shel, and re­
sembling the Agathe.

Ostracinda, dæ, f.g. Iu.  vid. Ostracites.

Ostr&abreve;cismus, mi, m.g. Arist. A kind
of banishment among the Athenians for
10. yeares space, which was done by de­
liuering of shells with the names of the
persons condemned written in them. It
was vsed not so much to punish other of­
fences, as to abate the immoderate pow­
er of noble men.

Ostracties, Iun. A kinde of
play, wherein a line drawne doth
part children on two sides: then a cap or
oyster shel beeing cast vp, and falling
downe on the hollow or flat side, that part
which did choose it, doth follow the other
part running away, and he that is taken
doth sing, Hollow or flat, lise or nits,
night or day.

Ostracties, vid. Ostracias, & To­
phus.Also another sotne like a shel vsed
to smooth the skinne in stead of a pumish
or steele stone, Plin.

Ostracium, ii, n.g. Plin. A shell: it is
sometime taken for the Onyx stone.

Ostracus, Isid. Est pavimentum
testaceum, co quòd fractis testis
caulce admixto feriatur.

Ostrea, æ, f.g. Plaut. All kind of fish
that hath an hard rough shel, as oysters
and muscles, and such other like.

Ostre&amacron;tia, æ, f.g. Plin. A place where
oysters or shel fishes are nourished and
found.

Ostre&amacron;rius, a, um, Plin. Of or belong­
ging to oysters and shell fish. Ostrearius

Ostre&amacron;tus, a, um, Plaut. Hard and
rough, like an oyster shel.

Ostreosus, a, um, & Ostreosior, us,
Teren. Maurus. Full of oysters.

Ostr&imacron;nus, a, um, Var. Of purple, or

Ostrum, stri, n.g. The liqour, iuyce, and

Ostus, vid. Hostus.

O V

Ov&amacron;lis, le, p.b. Gell. Of or belonging to

Ovans, tis, adiect. Triumphing, re­

Ov&amacron;tio, onis, f.g. p.b. ab Ovo, as.
 A
small triumph of a Prince or Captaine for
a victorie without slaughter of men, in
which he did either goe on foote, or ride on
horsebacke with his souldiers about him
singing, or shouting for ioy, and wearing
on his head a garland of mirtle.

Ov&amacron;tio, onis, f.g. p.l. ab Ovum, Pli. The
season when hennes lay egges, or a laying
of egges.

Ov&amacron;tus, a, um, part. ab Ovum, p. an­
cip. Plin. Made like an egge.

Ov&amacron;tus, us, m.g. verb. ab Ovo, as,
 p.
b. Varr. A shout or cry of triumphers or
conquerours.

Ov&ibreve;&amacron;r&ibreve;a, æ, f.g. p.b. Var.
A flocke of
sheepe.

Ovi&amacron;r&ibreve;cus, a, um, p.b. Of or belonging

Ov&ibreve;c&ubreve;la, æ, f.g. dim. ab Ovis. A little

The sheepe
coat, a fold or sheepe house.

Ov&ibreve;l&umacron;t&ebreve;um,* The yolke of an egge.

OV&imacron;nus, a, um, p.b. * Of a sheepe.

Ov&ibreve;p&ebreve;ra, æ, p.l. * Birds, beasts, or fish­
es that breed egges on spawne. Ovipera
gallina, * A brood henne.

Ov&ibreve;s, is, f.g. (& quandoq; masc. Fest)
p.b. A sheepe. Ovis reicula. Var. Keb­
bers, or cullers drawne out of a flocke of
sheepe: a ridgeling, which is either verie
aged or sickly, or at the least not fit for
meate.

Ovo, as, p.b. Valer. to reioyse with
noyse, or shout with a multitude: to sing
for ioy.

Ovum, vi, n.g. p.l. An egge: also
spawne in fishes. Ovum decumanum,
Fest. A faire large, and great egge. E­
durum, Iun. Halfe hard and halfe soft:
an egge reare dressed. Frixum, Iun. A
fryed egge. Geminum, Iun. A 2. yolked
egge. Irritum, subventaneum, hype­
nemium, zephyrium, Pli. A wind egge
or barren egge, wherof nothing can be in
gendered. Pullescens, Colum. An egge
begun to be a chicken. Recens, Iun. A
new laied egge. Requietum, Iun. An
old laid egge, a stale egge. Tremulum,
molle, sorbile, Cels. A soft egge that
may be sipped vp. Vrinum, cynosurum,
Pli. An addle egge, vnfit for generation.
by reason that the hen doth cease to sit on
it. Ovi albumen, albor, candidum, Iun.
The white of en egge. Luteum, vitellus,
Horat The yolke of an egge. Testa, pu­
tamen, cortex. Plin. An egge shell.
Vmbilicus, Iun. The strein or kenning
of the egge. Ovum pisci, Iun. The frie or
spawne.

Ox&abreve;lis, &ibreve;dis, f.g. Plin. Sorrell, sowre

Oxifalus Isid. A measure containing

Oxyg&abreve;la, e, f.g. Oxyg&abreve;lum, li, n.

Oxyg&abreve;rum, ri, n.g. Mart. Sharpe

the stomach.

Oxym&ebreve;l&imacron;, sive Oxymel, elis, n.g. Pli.

together.

Oxym&omacron;ron, Bud. A sentence spoken
with such affectation of wit, & grauitie,
that it seemeth foolish.

Oyxmyrs&imacron;n&emacron;, es, Plin. A shrub like to

Oxyphoenix,* The tree that beareth
the fruite called Tamarindi.

Oxyp&obreve;r&obreve;p&omacron;la, æ, m.g. Plin. 
He that
selleth meat in sharpe sauce and syrrups.

Oxyp&obreve;rum, i, n.g. Colum. Any sharp
sauce made with vineger or veruce: also
an oyntment or plaister tempered with
vineger, that the veriue thereof may pe­
netrate the better.

Oxyrrhodium,* A liquid medicine
made of vineger and rosewater, and laid
to their heads which are troubled with
the frensie.

Oxyrrhincus, Strab. A fish onely in
Nilus, which the Egyptians worshipped
for a god.

Oxys, idis, Iun. A vessell of vineger.
also Sorrell bois, or Alleluya: cockowes
sorrell, stubwort.

Oxysaccharum.* A sirrope made with
suger and vineger.

Oxyschoenos, Plin. A kinde of bull­
rushes.

Oxytoca,* Medicines to make the birth
quickly deliuered.

Oxytonon* Wilde poppie.

Oxytriphillum, li, n.g. Scrib. It is
all one with Silermontanum: it hath a
strong smell, mossie leaues, and t hose sharp
or pricking in the top: some take it for tri­
folium acutum.


O Z

Ozæna, æ, f.g. p.l. Cels. A disease
or sore inthe nose causing a stincking sa­
uour: also a kinde of fish of the many foots
kinde, so called of the strong and ranke sa­
uour of his head, whom for this cause lam­
preis do hunt after, pursue & chase.

Ozæn&imacron;tis, p.l. Plin. A kinde of spike­
nard hauing the smell of poyson.

Oze, es, f.g. p.l. Cels. The stinking of
the breath.

Ozymum, n.g. Pers. A meat made
of the inwards of beastes: also a sweete
hearbe named basil. Catul.





P A

PA, pro parte, Fest.

P&amacron;b&ubreve;l&amacron;ris, re, Colum.
Pertaining to fodder, prouen­
der, forrage, or meate for
beast.

P&amacron;b&ubreve;l&amacron;tio, onis, f.g. verb.
Cæs. For­
raging, pasturing, feeding, or grazing: pro­
uiding of fodder for labouring cattell.

P&amacron;b&ubreve;l&amacron;tor, oris, m.g. verb.
Cæs. A
forrager, a prouider of fodder or meat: a
purueyour.

P&amacron;b&ubreve;l&amacron;t&omacron;r&ibreve;us, a, um, Colum. Of or
belonging to forraging, fodder, or meat.

P&amacron;b&ubreve;lor, aris, Cæs. To go in forraging:
it is when men of warre go to seeke for­
rage in the fieldes among villages: to fod­
der and serue cattel: to feede or nourish.

P&amacron;b&ubreve;lum, li, n.g. Pasture, foode, fod­
der, forrage, flouer, or prouender, for cat­
tell: any thing that feedeth, maintaineth
or nourisheth: food, sustenance. Camelo­
rum pabulum, Iun. vide Iuncus o­
doratus.

P&amacron;c&amacron;lis, le, Ovid. That bringeth or sig­
nifieth peace, peaceable.

Pacarius, Sen.  vid. Proxeneta.

P&amacron;c&amacron;tor, orism m.g. verb. à Paco.
Sen. A pacifier, asswager, tamer or
quieter.

P&amacron;c&amacron;tus, a, um. Quieted, appeased,
asswaged, tamed, made patient, and still:
calme, peaceable, fauourable.

Pacifer, a, um, ex Pax & fero.Plin.
That bringeth peace or quietnes.

Pæan, anis, m.g. An hymne or song
of praise made to Apollo the God of the
Painimes, at such time as any plague or
pestilence raged, and also after the obtai­
ning of some victorie and triumph. Pæa­
nem citare. By litle and litle to lift vp
the voice, to arise from note to note, or to
sing lowder and lowder.

Pæd&ebreve;ros, &omacron;tis, Plin. A pretious stone
called Opalus, wherein appeareth the
fierie brightnes of the carbuncle, the shi­
ning purple colour of the Amathist, the
greene shew of the emerald, all shining
togither with an vnbeleueable mixture.
Also a bramble or hearb called Beare­
breech, whereof there are two kindes, the
one pricking & curled, which is the shor­
ter and lower of the two, the other smooth
and not rough, which some call brank vr­
sine, some black leafe, some bearefoote.

leaues and braunches from vines. vide

Pamp&ibreve;n&amacron;tus, a, um, part. vel nom.
ex part. Plin. That hath the young leaues
or young braunches cut away.

Pamp&ibreve;neus, a, um, Virg. Of, hauing,
or belonging to a young vine braunche or
leafe. Pampineus odor, Propert. The
smell of wines.

Pampino, as, Var. To cut away leaues
from a vine, that the sunne may come to
the grapes: to cut of needlesse sprigs or su­
perfluous twigs.

Pamp&ibreve;n&omacron;sus, a, um, Col. Ful of leafes
or branches, as a vine.

Pamp&ibreve;n&ubreve;la, læ, f.g. vide Pampi­
nella.

Pamp&ibreve;nus, i, m.g. The leafe of a vine,
the greene branch or young wood of the
vine with his leaues, the budde of a vine:
also the bristles of the fish Polypus, Plin.

Panacea, æ, f.g. Lucil. Salt.

P&abreve;n&abreve;c&emacron;a, æ, f.g. Lucan. &

P&abreve;n&abreve;ces, is, n.g. & P&amacron;nax, &amacron;cis,
f.g.
Colum. An hearb that hath a leafe like

the toppe a knap with sweete seedes ha­

Opponax. Panaces Herculeum, of
some it is taken for Angelica, Iun.

Panagios,* Altogether religious, a
very deuout man.

Pancarpos,* Chamelion niger.

Panacr&abreve;tius, Sen. &

Pancr&amacron;tiast&emacron;s, stæ, Gell. He that in

activenes, cunning at all kinds of games
and exercises.

Pancr&abreve;t&ibreve;c&emacron;, adverb. Plau. 
Mightily,
strongly, wrestlerlike.

Pancr&abreve;tium, ij, n.g. Propert. A ma­
ner of wrestling, wherein one laboureth
by all meanes he can to ouerthrow the
other: an exercise in all feates of activity,
as wrestling, running, and al kind of a­
ctive games: also a sea onyon, Plin.

Pancreas. Iun. A kernel and fat
flesh neere the nether mouth of the sto­
mach: in a hogge it is called the sweete
bread.

Pancreon,* A part of the bodie in the
nether rime of the caule betweene the li­
ver and the stomacke.

ward.

Pandens, tis, part. à Pando, is,

Pandectæ, arum, f.g. Bookes of di­

lume of the ciuil law, called Digests.

Pandicularis dies, Fest. All saints
daie, or the feast of all saints, wherin they
did sacrifice to all the gods in common.

Pand&ibreve;c&umacron;l&amacron;tio, onis, f.g. Plaut.
A ga­

Pand&ibreve;c&ubreve;lor, aris, depon. Plaut.
To

come from sleepe.

Pando, as, Plin. To bow downe and
make to stoupe, as vnder a burden: to yeeld
and sinke downe vnder a burden.




Pando, is, di, sum, &ebreve;re. To open, to
set abroad, to spread, shew, declare, and

P&abreve;nicum, ci, n.g. Cæs. A grain like

P&amacron;n&ibreve;s, is, m.g. Bread. Panis acerosus,
gregarius, squarosus, sordidus, Iun.

Iun. White bread. Similagineus, vel
similaceus, Iun. Simnel bread, fine m&amacron;­
chet. Spongiosus, Iun. Light or puft

bunne. Subcinericius, Iun. An ashcake,
or bread baked vnder ashes or hot embers.

P&abreve;p&umacron;la, læ, vel Papulæ, arum, f.g.

wheales or pimpels which rise on the skin

P&abreve;pyrus, ri, f.g. & Papyrum, ri, n.g.
s.l. A great rish in Egipt, growing in

made: now it is vsed for printing & wri­
ting paper, &c.

Par, p&abreve;ris, n.g. A paire or couple. Par
impar, Suet. A kind of play, called euen
and odde.

Par, p&abreve;ris, adiect. Euen, equall, like:
meete, conuenient, reasonable: able or of
sufficient force to match & sustaine: also
two. Par pari. Like for like, one for ano­
ther, as much againe, an equal match.

Parabolani, Vlp. Glebæ ascripti­

ministers that might neuer goe from the

P&abreve;r&abreve;g&omacron;gia, æ, f.g. Alciat. A place

P&abreve;r&abreve;gr&abreve;phus, Martian. A para­

Paralia,* A kinde of pitch.

P&abreve;r&abreve;l&imacron;p&obreve;m&ebreve;non, Isid. Left out: not
spoken or written of.

P&abreve;r&amacron;lius, Plin. A kinde of spurge cal­

P&abreve;rall&emacron;li, Plin. The circles and lines
in the sphere of the world drawne from
the east to the weast, hauing one of the
poles for their center, and in euerie parte

P&abreve;rell&emacron;lus, a, um. Plin. Equallie di­
stant.

Paralogismus,* A deceitfull conclu­
sion, or captious reasoning or arguing.

Paralos.* A kinde of ship at Athens
wherein certaine went to Delum euerie
yeare in the name of all the rest to sacri­
fice to Apollo, and they which went in
that ship were called Parali.

P&abreve;r&abreve;lysis, is, f.g. t.b. A resolution of

P&abreve;r&abreve;lyt&ibreve;cus, a, um, Plin. One sicke

Paramese, Iun. The fift string, being

&omacron;rum, Vlp. All things that the woman

Parapsis, Mart.  vid. Paropsis.

P&abreve;r&amacron;riumæs, Suid. Double wages

P&abreve;r&amacron;rius, a, um, Fest. A broker that

P&abreve;rarthi&emacron;sis, vid. Iuxatio.

P&abreve;rasc&emacron;ve, es, f.g. Iun. A
preparati­
on: also Good friday.

P&abreve;r&abreve;si&omacron;p&emacron;sis, vid. Præoccupatio.

P&abreve;r&abreve;s&imacron;ta, æ, f.g. Plaut. A
woman pa­
rasite, a she flatterer.

P&abreve;r&abreve;s&imacron;taster, stri, m.g. Terent. He
that countersaieth to be a parasite, a
cogging marchant.

P&abreve;r&abreve;s&imacron;tor, &amacron;ris, depon. Plaut.
To
sooth one in his sayings & doings, to hold
him vp with yea and nay: to agree in all
things to one, to faune and flatter him for
a meales meate, to cog and foyst, to play
the parasite.

P&abreve;r&abreve;s&imacron;tus, ti, m.g. A smell feast, a
flatterer, a parasite, a trencher or belly
freind: one that saith and doth all things
to please the humour of another, and a­
greeth vnto him in all things, to haue his
repast scotfree. In olde time this worde
was vsed in the good parte for them that




attended vpon, accompanied, or were
assistants to high priests or chiefe magi­
strates, Athæn.

Passus, us, m.g. A prise in going, a

Pecc&amacron;t&umacron;, pro peccata, Gell.


Pecc&amacron;tum, ti, n.g. A sinne: a fault, an
offence, a trespasse.

Pecc&amacron;tur, impers. & activ. & passi.
 They offend or doe amisse: things are done
amisse, faults are committed.

Pecco, as, avi, atum, are. To sinne: to
faile in some thing, to offend, to do amisse,
not to doe that we ought, to commit a
fault.

Pecten, &ibreve;nis, n.g. Ovid. The slay of a

dered, examined, recompensed.

examine, paie, and recompense often.

wey, ponder, consider, examine, trie
by weight, and esteeme: to recompense, to
supplie, to buie.

ones office or that which is inioyned him.

Weyed, examined, considered, tried, re­

bookes.

daie long: the whole day throughout.

gainst another, to bring to passe or goe
to an end that one hath purposed.

tickle, to grope or feele: to laie hold vpon.

Pes, p&ebreve;dis, m.g. A foote: the mea­




sure of a fooote, it is diuided into 12. in­
ches: also a head louse, Var. the halser in
a ship wherwith the saile is hoisted vp,
Iun. Pes contractus, Iun. Halfe a foot
long and broad. Græcus, Iun. Which is
longer then Romanus by halfe an inch.
 Planus, Iun. vid. Area. Porrectus, Iun.
Theiust length of a foote, or a full foote
measure. Quadratus, Iun. A foot long
and broad, or a foote square euerie way.
 Digiti pedum, Ov&imacron;. the toes. Pesmon­
tis, Iun. The roote or foot of an hill. Plan­

pedis, Iun. The hollownes of the foote.
 Pes corvi, Iun. The hearb Crowfoote.
 Pes leporis, Iun. vid. Lagopus.  Pes
vinaceorum, Col. the stalke of grapes.
 Pes milvi vel milvinus, Colum. The
hearb Hawthorne. Pes gallinaceus, Pli.
A kinde of fumitorie growing on walles,
and in hedges, some call it bastard or
wild perslie. Pes leonis. * The hearb
low wallow, or our ladies mantell. Pes
accipitsinus, Diosc. vid. Lychnis syl­
vestris.

 Pessum abire, Plaut. Pesum ire, Col.

haire or wooll, that is vnshorne, of frieze
or frizadow: also grosse & rude, Quint.

P&ebreve;z&imacron;ta, æ, m.g. Plin. A mushrome
growing on the rootes of trees.

Philtrum, i. n.g. & Philtra, orum, p.

sight doth purchase loue and fauour.

they were wont to write.

Pi&amacron;b&ibreve;lis, le, Ovid. For which satisfa­

Pi&emacron;, adverb. Deuoutly, godly, duti­
fully, mercifully, louingly, with naturall
and honest affection: naturally.

Piens, tior, tissimus, * Mercifull, natur­
rall and louing.

Pi&ebreve;tas, atis, f.g. The dutie, honestie,
conscience, good dealing, that is due first to
God, and afterward to our fathers and
mothers, children, kinsfolke, and vncle:
deuotion, godlines, godly affection: natu­
rall and reuerent loue, naturall affection
or zeale, reuerence, remorse of conscience.

P&ibreve;la, æ, f.g. A ball to plaie with all,
anie round thing like a ball. Pila cla­
varia, Iun. A ball stuft with hard haire
or wooll, which they vse to smite in plaie
with cudgels leaded at the end. Italica,
lusoria, manuaria, recussabilis, Iun.
A handball to plaie withall. Paganica
Iun. A ball stuft with soft wool or haire,
and vsed to be tossed from hand to hand:
a tossing or yarneball. Pilæ lusoriæ,
quadruplex ratio refertur à Polluce.
1. Cælestis pila. A ball so taken with
the hand, as that it is smitten into the
ayre. 2. Refractio pilæ. A rebound. 3.
Communis pila. When a bal is so smitten
that both sides doe cunninglie take it and
readilie smite it backe againe beyond the
marke. 4. Impostoria pila. vid. Impo­
storia. Mattiaca pila, vid. Mattiacæ.

Pila, æ f.g. Iun. A morter, a square

of the force of the water from the wharff
or hauen sides, Iun.

Pilæ arum, f.g. Fest. Viriles & mu­
liebres effigies ex lana compitalibus
suspendebantur in compitis, quòd
hunc diem festum esse deorum infe­
rorum, quos vocant lares, putarent:
quibus tot pilæ, quot capit seruo­
rum, tot effigies, quot essent liberi,
ponebantur, vt vivis parcerent, & es­
sent his pilis & simulachis contenti.

Pl&amacron;c&amacron;b&ibreve;lis, le. Easie to be pleased, or
appeased: gentle, myld, soone qualified.

Pl&amacron;c&amacron;b&ibreve;l&ibreve;tas, atis, f.g. When a bodie
is easie to be appeased or pacified: gentle­
nes, placabilitie.

Placæ,* Plates of gold and silver.

Pl&amacron;c&amacron;men, &ibreve;nis, & Placamentum,
ti, n.g. Liv. An appeasing: a thing that
one is appeased or qualified with.

Placandus, a, um, part. Ovid. To be
pacified or appeased.

Placans, tis, part. Appeasing, &c.

Pl&amacron;c&amacron;t&emacron;, & Placatiùs, adverb.
Peaceably without stirring: quietly, gen­
tly, caulmely, patiently.

Pl&amacron;c&amacron;tio, onis, f.g. verb. A pacifying,
asswaging, pleasing, mitigating, qualify­
ing.

Plac&amacron;tus, & Placatissimus, a, um.
Appeased, pacifyed, pleased, contented:
without any motion, quiet, calme, with­
out trouble: peaceable, mill, gentle.

Pl&abreve;cendus, a, um, Plaut. To be plea­
sed: that ought to please & be acceptable.

Pl&amacron;centa, æ, f.g. Plin. A cake, a tart,
a wafer, a iunket: a marchpaine: also a
cheesecake, Iun. Placenta vmbilicata,
Iun. A pastie, or a large broad and thin
cake vsed in sacrifice.

Pl&abreve;centia, æ, f.g. Apul. An indeuour
or desire to please.

Pl&abreve;ceo, es, &ubreve;i, &ibreve;tum, &emacron;re. To please,
delight, like, seeme, or thinke good, to be
content.

Pl&abreve;cet, &emacron;bat, &ubreve;it, &ibreve;tum est, impers.
It liketh or pleaseth: he thinketh good, or
is content: his opinion, will, and plea­
sure is.

Pl&abreve;c&ibreve;d&emacron;, adverb. Peaceablie, quiet­
lie, caulmlie, softlie, gently, pacientlie,
without noyse or trouble.

Placidior, us, compar. Liv. More
gentle and quiet.

Pl&abreve;c&ibreve;dus, & Placidissimus, a, um.
Gentle, patient, milde, peaceable, quiet,
still, caulme, without trouble, that wil not
be angrie: pleasant, toothsome, tractable,
sweet and amiable: fauourable, running
quietly and with a still water, blowing
softlie.

tem ad testudinem evolare non po­
test, Galen.

gay shew caried about either on mens
showlders, or in carts.

 Pomum cadivum, vel caducum,
A falling apple which without pulling

 Nanum. Iun. Smal fruit, a little pelting

Summer fruit: a summer apple, a geni­

P&omacron;no, is, s&ubreve;i, s&ibreve;tum, &ebreve;re. To put or set:




to place, to pitch, make, edify, or build: to
lie down, to lay, as one layeth a foundation,
to erect, to plant, to lay in wager, or as a
gage: to lay aside, to put away, to leaue, or
cease, to lay apart, to lay or bang downe,
to put of, as one doth his close: to set be­
fore one, as they doe meate on the table:
to employ, to spend, to bestow, to doe, to
plant or set: to propose, moove, or put forth
a question or doubt, to alledge, to paint or
draw out the forme of a thing in a table:
to worke, to suborne, to recken, or repute,
to account, to esteeme: to impute, to ap­
point, to giue, to appease, to make cleane,
to determine.

Pons, tis, m.g. A bridge: also a lad­
der in a ship. Virg. Pons longus, Iun. A
bridge, or rather a banke, or banke cast
between two meddowes, or made in a
fennie ground to passe ouer. Sublicius,
Liv. vel  roboreus, Oui. A great bridge
of wood, timber, or posts, such as serue for
horse and carts, &c. Versatilis, Iun. A
draw bridge: a falling bridge, or a trap
bridge. Also a bridge turned downe, or
put out of a ship, whereon to passe ouer to
and fro when the ship is ariued, and hath
gotten the hauen: a shipboord.

Populacia, Iun.  vid. Popularia.

P&obreve;p&ubreve;landus, a, um, part. Ovid. To

P&obreve;p&ubreve;lans, tis, part. Ovid. Wasting,

Popularia, um, n.g. Suet. Places
where the comminaltie doe assemble, or
where the commons sitte in beholding
games: also trifling, childish, Non. Po­
pularia sacra, Labeo. Which were
made of the wholl people, and not attri­
buted to any one famely.

P&omacron;p&ubreve;l&amacron;ris, re. Of or belonging to the
people: accepted and fauoured of the peo­
ple: that delighteth and pleaseth the peo­
ple, fauouring the quarrell, or giuen to
maintaine the libertie of the commons:
one that seeketh by all possible and flatte­
ring meanes to haue the favour of the
people: made by the people: common: A
companion of the same towne or citie, a
countrie man: one of the meane people or
commonaltie: a subiect: a companion,
fellow or confederate: of the same state or
condition.

P&obreve;p&ubreve;l&amacron;r&ibreve;tas, &amacron;tis, f.g. Plin. Iun.
Friendship or familiaritie by reason of
countrieship: the favour & will to main­
taine the commons: also the fauour of
the people towards one.

P&obreve;p&ubreve;l&amacron;r&ibreve;ter, adverb. Homelie: after
the fashion or opinion of the people: also
with the loue & fauour of the commons:
commonlie, ordinarilie.

P&obreve;p&umacron;l&amacron;tim, adverb. Through all the
people, altogether, wholly.

P&obreve;p&ubreve;l&amacron;tio, onis, f.g. verb.
Liv. A
wasting, destroying: a pilling, polling,
robbing, and spoyling of people: a ransac­
king of countries, a corruption.

P&obreve;p&ubreve;l&amacron;tor, &omacron;ris, m.g. verb. à Popu­
lor, Ovid. A piller, robber, destroyer,
waster, and spoyler of people and coun­
tries; a forager in warre.

Præceps, c&ibreve;p&ibreve;tis, adject. Headlong,
steep downe, that hath a downe fall, dan­
gerous, present and perilous, daungerous
to clime vp, hanging in such sort that it
is easie forone to come tumbling downe:
verie speedie, sudden, quick, exceeding
& ouer hastie, passing swift, without
consideration, on head, verie rash, hotte,
headie, harebraine, headstrong, foole har­
die: also drawing to an end, Sen. deepe,
feirsely, violently, Virg. Abire præci­
pitem, Salust. To fall to extreame pouer­
tie, need, ruine, and vtter decaie. Pal­
mites præcipites, Col. Young shootes
springing out the year present, and tied
to the bodie of the tree.

ces gard. Virginum sacrarum, Iun. The

Præj&umacron;d&ibreve;cium, ij, n.g. A preiudice or

those which we call ruled cases in the
lawe: also a maner of sentence giuen be­
fore iudgement, as if two did contend for
one ffice, and the magistrate, because the
controuersie will be long, in the meane
time appointeth one of them to minister
the office, wherein he seemeth to giue
iudgement before, for him whom he fa­
uoureth.

other like matter before iudged: also to

person or thing before he commeth to the
place to heare it: by preiudice to hurt or
hinder ones cause.

Prætexo, is, ui, &ebreve;re. To couer the bor­

Prætexta, æ, f.g. siue Prætexta toga.
A long robe or gowne edged or garded a­
bout with purple silke, that noble mens
children vsed to weare, till seuen yeares of
age, and therefore were called Prætexati.
It was also the robe of estate that the king
of Rome, or the other chiefe officers did
weare, when they sat in their maiestie, &
was wont to be burned with them that dy­
ed in their office, neither could any iudge
giue sentence on a man, till he had put of
that robe. It was also a coate that cap­
taines wore in triumph, and that Sena­
tours were knowen by from the order of
gentlemen.

Prætextati, & Prærextatæ, Suet.
Noble mens sonnes and daughters wea­
ring long robes garded with purple.

Prætext&amacron;tus, a, um. That weareth a
long robe, garded with purple. Also ho­
nest and chast, Fest. or after Suet. very
filthy and rebaudrous. Prætextati an­
ni, Plin. Youth or childes age. Prætex­
tatus assecla, Iun. A page of honour, or




a henchman.

Prætextum, ti, n.g. & Prætextus, us,
m.g. Marcel. A pretence, cloke, or colour,
an excuse: a border, brim, couering, or o­
uercasting.

Prætextus, a, um, part. Ovid. Borde­
red, that hath the edges embrodered or
garded: made or builded. Prætextæ acti­
ones seu comoediæ, Horat. wherin
are personages of great dignity, &c.

Præt&ibreve;meo, es, ui, ere, Plaut. to be

Præt&ibreve;mesco, is, &ubreve;i, &ebreve;re, * To begin to

Prætinctus, a, um, Ovid. Dipped or

Prætondeo, es, di, &emacron;re, * To sheare or
clippe before.

Prætor, oris, m.g. An officer in olde
time hauing the rule of an army: after­
ward he had authority in iudgement, &
was as a chiefe Iustice, hauing other
Iudges sitting vnder him as Asconius
saith, to the number of 71. other write,
75. in processe of time were so many Pre­
tors chosen, as there were countires sub­
iect to the Empire: a Maior, Pretor, or
he that sitteth in iudgement and decideth
matters in the law. Prætor vrbanus,
which iudgeth betweene citizens. Pere­
grinus, which iudgeth betweene straun­
gers. Pretor comitatus Augustalis,
Iun. Controller of the Princes houshold.

Præt&omacron;ri&amacron;nus, & Prætoritius, a, um,
Mart. Of or belonging to, or attending
on Pretors, vid. Satelles.

Præt&omacron;rium, ij, n.g. The house or pauilli­
on of the Pretor, or chiefe captaine, of the
Maior, Iudge, or Alderman: also a Prin­
ces pallace, court, or manour: also a place,
or court, where iudgements were giuen,
& matters heard by the Pretor, Maior, or
Lord chiefe iustice: also a great house
builded in the ceuntry, which some citizen
inhabited when it was his pleasure to be
in the country. Præfectus prætorio, Suet.
The lord Maior, or Lord chiefe Iustice.

Præt&omacron;rius, a, um. Of, or belonging to,
or attending on a Pretor, lord chiefe Iu­
stice, or chiefe Captaine. Vir prætorius.
One that hath bin Pretour.

Prætortus, a, um, Col. Wrested or
wroong very hard: very crooked.

re, * To begin to swell very much.

Præv&amacron;r&ibreve;c&amacron;tio, onis, f.g. verb. à Præ­
varicor. A letting passe, or light touch­
ing of that which should haue bin more
earnestly declared, as making much to
the matter: preuarication, or collusion in
pleading: also corrupting of an accuser.

Præv&amacron;r&ibreve;c&amacron;tor, oris, m.g. verb. He
that leaueth the right way, or speaketh
not that which ought to be spoken: he that
pleadeth by collusion, and furthereth the
aduersaries cause: an attorney or man of
law pretending to helpe a man, and be­
traying his cause to his enemy: an an­
swerer corrupted with mony by the per­
son acccused: a flase dealer, a corrupt ac­
cuser: Also a cogging or cousening gam­
ster at dice, Iun.

Præv&amacron;r&ibreve;cor, &amacron;ris, depon. To make
semblance or shew to do a thing, and doe
cleane contrarie, to worke by collusion in




pleading, and purposely to suffer his ad­
versarie to obtaine against him that he
defendeth: to betray ones cause to his ad­
versarie, to swarue from truth, to goe out
of the right way, to leane out that ought
to be spoken, & more earnestly declared,
as effectuall to the matter.

Pr&ebreve;mo, is, ssi, ssum, &ebreve;re. To presse, to

stroy, to be contrary or against, to let, stay,
or hinder: to constraine, to restraine: to

P S

Psallo, is, li, ere. To sing, to play on
the harp or lute.

Psall&obreve;c&ibreve;th&abreve;rista, æ, m.g. Suet. A sin­
ger to the harp.

playing togither on an instrument: a sin­
ging togither of Psalmes.

Psalmus, mi, m.g. Iun. A song of or
to God: a Psalme sung to the psaltery, or
a song sung by the voyce.

Psalt&emacron;rium, rij, n.g. Quint. An in­
strument of musick like an harp, but more
pleasant: some call it a Psaltry to play ho­
lie hymnes vpon, & to sing vnto in play­
ing.

Psaltes, is, m.g. Iun. A singing man,
or Organ player.

fall to the ground, and be taken of sheep­

Publ&ibreve;c&amacron;nus, a, um. A farmer that

citie at a rent certaine, the order of which
persons were gentlemen and of good repu­
tation, vid. Manceps.

the common cost or charge of the wholl
city: to or in the common weale, by a com­
mon decree.

Publ&ibreve;cius, a, um, Ovid. Common.

in general, to confiscate, set abroad as one
doth a booke, or abandon in common as
harlots doe: also to shew himselfe openly

Pulsus, vs, m.g. verb. à Pello. The mo­

powers is discerned: also a beating or
thumping, thrusting, or striking.

 Pulvis Damascenus, Iun. Sweet pow­

Pyrrhiacus, a, um. * Of or belonging to
the daunce Phrrhica.

Pyrrh&ibreve;ca, æ, vel Pyrrh&ibreve;ce, es, Plin.
A certaine forme of daunsing in armour

inuented by Pyrrhus.

Pyrrhicarius, & Pyrrhichista, Vlp.
He that vseth such daunsing.

Pyrrhichius, Iun. A foote consisting
of 2 short syllables: it is so called of nim­
ble mouing vsed in the Pyrrhichian daun
sing which was in armour.

Pyrrh&omacron;pæc&ibreve;lus, Pli. A kinde of mar­
ble, whereof the Egyptians made Obe­
liscos, which they dedicated to the Sun.

Pyrum, ri, n.g. p.b. Propert. A peare.
 Pyrum acidulum, vel postautumnale,
Iun. A lateward peare: an after haruest
peare. Amerinum, Plin. A winter peare,
a S. Thom as tide peare. Ampullaceum,
Plin. A tankard peare, so called of his
likenes: or an english apple peare. Colo­
ratum, vel Venereum, Iun. A Venus
or faire louely peare. Crustuminum, Pli.
A S. Iames peare, or Katherine peare.
 Cucurbitinum, Plin. A bell peare, or
gourd peare, so called of his likenes. Do­
lobellianum, Plin. A long taild, or long
stalkt peare. Falernum, Plin. A peare
full of iuyce. Hordearium, Pli. A muske
peare. Librale, Plin. A poundpeare.
 Mammosum, vel Pomponianum, Iun.
A breast pear, resembling the fashion of a
womans breast. Volemum, sementi­
num, musteum, Iun. A peare warden.
 Regium, Plin. A king peare with a very
litle stalke. Signinum, testaceum, Iun.
A red or sand peare. Superbum, Plin. A
water peare.

also a prophesying spirit, or a man posses­

Qui, cuius, cui, relat. Which, who,
that: for so much as, seeing, what man­
ner of, who.

Qu&abreve;, adverb. How, by what meanes,
wherefore, why, whence, would to god.

Quia, coniunct. Because, for that, for­
somuch as.

Quinam, adverb. Plaut. Where­
fore, why.

Quiane, Virg. Truly, &c.

Quicquam, cuiusdam, n.g. Any
thing, something.

Quicque. Euery thing, any thing.

Quicquid. Whatsoeuer.

Quicum, pro Cum quo. With whom.

Qu&imacron;cunque, æcunque, quodcun­
que. Whosoeuer: whatsoeuer, such as, a­
ny kinde of.

Quid, duius, cui. What, what thing,
any thing, who, why, what manner of,
what saie you of, or to this? wherein?
Quid? admirativè dictum à respon­
dente. Do you aske me why? what? what
saie you? why? how.

Qu&imacron;dam, quædam, quoddam vel
quiddam, cuiusdam. Some certaine
person or thing, one.

Qu&ibreve;dem, adverb. Truly, verily, cer­
tainly, doubtles, indeed. Ne quidem.
No not? Et quidem. Yea and that.

Quidnam, cuiusnam. What thing
what matter, what.

Quidni, adverb. Wherefore not? why
not? what else?

Quidpiam, ciuispiam. Something,
any thing.

Quidque, cuiusque. Every thing.

Quidvis, cuiusvis. Whatsoeuer thou
wilt, any thing.

Quidum, adverb. Plaut. How then?
how so?

Quies, &emacron;tis, f.g. Ease, sleepe, quietnes,
rest, vacation and ceasing from labour &
trouble: also calme, faire, and still wea­
ther, Virg. Quietes in plur. vid. Olim
per quintam declinat. inflectebatur




Quies, quiei.

Quiescens, tis, part. Being quiet and
making no stur.

Quiesci, Impers. Terent. to be at
quiet.

Quiesco, is, &emacron;vi, &emacron;tum, ere. To rest,
sleepe, or take rest: to be at quiet: to cease
or end: to be void of labour, care, and bu­
sines: to be caulme, to hold ones peace and
make no more a doe: to suffer or permit: to
pause and take breath, to stand still and
not to moue: also to appease or cause to
be quiet, Plaut.

Qui&emacron;t&amacron;lis, vel quietatus, Fest. vid.
Orcus.

Qui&emacron;t&emacron;, adverb. Peaceably, quietly,

Quietes, Lucret. Beastes dennes: also

quiet and calme.

Qui&emacron;tissimè, adverb. Cæs.

Qui&emacron;t&umacron;rus, a, um, part. That will

Qui&emacron;tus, & Quietissimus, a, um.
Restfull, still, peaceable, quiet, caulme:

Quincunx, is, m.g. Fiue ounces: al­
so a very exact planting of trees in an or­
chard by squire, so that which way soeuer
one looke, the trees stand directlie one a­
gainst another, & of like distance: it hath
the name of the letter V, that signifieth
fiue, and being doubled maketh tenne, &
may be multiplied vpward and downe­
ward many waies. also a measure, litle
more then halfe an Hemina, Mart. fiue
ynches, Plin. Quincunx vsura, Scævol.
Vsurie of 5. in the hundred.

Q V O

Qu&omacron;, adverb. ad locum. From whence,
whether, to what place.

Quo, coniunct. That, wherefore, to the
end that, for, because, by how much, and
therfore, to what purpose.

Quad, adverb. Vntill, how long, as
long as, so farre, or as much as, as touch­
ing. Quoad vsque, Suet. Euen vntill.

Qu&omacron;circ&abreve;, conjunct. Wherefore, for
which cause, therefore, for that cause.

Qu&omacron;cum. With whome.

Quocunque, adverb. Whether soe­
uer, what way soeuer.

Quod, cujus, adject. Which, what,
that which, which thing, why, for what
cause, as touching, so farre or so much as.

Quòd, conjunct. Because, for as much
as, for that, as to that, as touching that,
if so be that, but, that: also sence, Pli. Iu.

Qu&obreve;damm&obreve;d&obreve;, vel quodam modo.
After a certaine fashion, after a sort, in
a manner.

Quodcunque, cujuscunque. What
soeuer: also as many as you can.

Quodpiam, cujuspiam, à Quispi­
am. Any or some thing. Aliquod quod­
piam. Some certaine, &c.

Quodvis, cujusvis. Any thing, what
one will.

Quoi pro cui, & Quojus pro cujus.

Qv&omacron;m&ibreve;nus, adverb. But that, not,
how much lesse, that they could not.

Qu&omacron;m&obreve;d&obreve;, adverb. How, after what
fashion, in what sort, by what reason, by
what meane: also as.

Qu&omacron;m&obreve;d&obreve;cunque, adverb. How
soever.

Qu&omacron;m&obreve;d&obreve;nam. But how.

Qu&omacron;nam, adverb. ad locum, Plaut.
To what place, whither.

Quonam modo. How or after what
fashion.

Quondam, adverb. tempo. In time
past, at another time, sometime, once, in
time to come.

Qu&obreve;niam, conjunct. Because, sith
that, for as much as, that.

Qu&omacron;piam, adverb. ad locum, Ter. &

Qu&omacron;quam, adverb. ad locum. Into
some place, any whither.

Qu&obreve;que, conjunct. Also, likewise,
and trulie.

Qu&omacron;qu&omacron;, adverb. ad locum. Toward
what part soeuer, whither soeuer, in what
time or place soeuer.

Q&umacron;oqu&omacron;m&obreve;do, adverb. Plau. 
How­
soeuer, after what sort & maner soeuer, in
any wise, howsoeuer it be, by al meanes,
alwaies.

Qu&omacron;qu&omacron;versum, sive Quoquover­
sus, adverb. ad locum. On euery side, e­
uery way, on euery part.

Quorsum, & Quorsus, adv. ad locum.
Toward what place or thing, toward
what side, on what side: to what end, in­
tent, or purpose: whither, which waie.

Quot, indecl. p.n. How many, so ma­
ny as.

Qu&obreve;tannis, adverb. Euery yeare,
yeare by yeare.

Quotcunque. How many soeuer.

Qu&omacron;t&emacron;ni, æ, a, p.n. How many, to what
number.

Quotiadianò, adverb. Pli.  vid. Quo­
tidie.

Qu&obreve;t&ibreve;di&amacron;nus, a, um. Daily done, that
happeneth euery day, ordinarily, quoti­

Q&ubreve;oties, adverb. How manyi times,

Qu&obreve;tiescunque, adverb. So many

Quotquot, Catull. As many as.

Qu&obreve;t&ubreve;plex, icis, * How many fold, or

Qu&obreve;t&ubreve;plus, a, um, * How much: also

Q&ubreve;otus, a, um. Of what number, how

order or place, how smal.

Q&ubreve;otuscunque, acunque, uncun­

Q&ubreve;otusquisque, no. numerale. What

lum, & reges, nationesque, & civita­

do per reciperatores reddantur res,

ferre ad aliquem. to tell pr prospose a
matter to ne, and aske his minde, coun­
sell, or advise concerning the same. Ad
seipsum aliquid referre. To iudge ano­
ther mans act by himselfe, considering
what he would doe, if he were in that
case. In acceptum referre. To approue
and allow as well done, and to be accpepted.

feare, a reuerent feare and doubt of con­

nestie, conscience, a scruple of conscience,
curiositie.

R&ebreve;l&ibreve;gi&omacron;s&emacron;, adverb. Carefullie, dili­
gentlie, with great devotion, religiouslie,
deuoutlie, godly, curiuslie, superstitious­
ly, with a feare of conscience.

Res, rei, f.g. A thing: chaunce, or
present occasion: the meane, the mat­
ter, cause, case, state, condition, deede,
or importance: empire, dominion, the
world, power: busines, contention: riches,
substance, heritage, monie, profite, weale,
experience, abilitie, affaires. Res fami­
liares. Domestical busines, housekeeping,




houshold affayres or charge, ones peculiar
substance or goods. Res rusticæ. Rurall
matters, countrie affaires, busines belon­
ging to the countrie, as fields, villages,
&c. Rerum natura. The world. Divina
res. Sacrifice, Gods seruice. Bellica res.
Martiall prowesse, warfarre. Pastoria
res, Varr. Grasing. Re vera. In deede,
truly, verily. Rem vel res agere, Liv.
To be a captaine in warre.

to take comfort, to be refreshed or eased, to

sauour, Stat.

Resplendeo, es, ui, &emacron;re. To shine much
or bright, to be gorgeous, gay, and braue.

Respondens, tis, part. Stat. Answe­
ring, giuing sound againe.

Respondeo, es, di, sum, &emacron;re. To an­
swere, to agree, accord, consent, be like, e­
quall, correspondent, or answerable: to
appeare or answer when one is called: to
resemble or be like, to be ouer right a­
gainst, to pay or satisfie, to giue counsell to
those that aske our aduise.

Responsio, onis, f.g. verb. An an­
swere.

yers doe.

Responso, as, frequent. à Respon­
deo. To answer, to resist, to gainsay, to o­
uerthwart in words.

A surety, he that answereth, vnderta­
keth, or promiseth for another.

Responsorius cantus, Isid. quòd
alio desinente, id alter respondet.

Responsu. To be answered.

tos dicuntur opiniones & sententiæ
quas consultoribus suis viri pruden­

R&emacron;st&ibreve;b&ibreve;lis, le, Colum. Which beareth

Reus, i, m.g. The defendant in a pro­

Rex, &emacron;gis, m.g. A king, a prince: also a

manorum, Iun. Cæsar, or the king of the
Romanes. Sacrorum, quód is solus
Pótifici maximo subjiciebatur, Iun.
A Cardinall. Rex vini, Iun. Who beeing
made king at feasts and bankets by lot or
by chaunce of the dice or hucklebones did
commaund and appoint one to drinke, a­
nother to powre out wine, some to depart,
some againe to tarrie, &c.

our Ladies rose. Canina, sylvestris, Iun.
The eglantine or sweete brier rose: an
hedge rose, a wilde rose. Croneola, pal­
lida, odorata, moschetta, Iun. A
musket rose. Iunonia, Iun. The Lilly.
 Milesia, purpurea, vel rubra, Iun. A
red rose. Græca, Plin. Of the bignes of a
violet, growing in moist places, hauing
onlie fiue leaues, and no savour at all, de­
sired onely for the colours sake, and that
to set in garlands. græcula, Plin. Latis­
sima habet folia sed panniculos ita
convolutos, vt nunquam nisi manu
coacta dehiscat, semperque nascen­
ti similis fit.

Rostellum, li, n.g. dim. à Rostrum,

made and trimmed with stems or fore­
frunts of ships, out of which place they
were wont to make orations: the pulpit.

Rostrans, tis, part. Plin. Running in.


Rostratus, a, um. That hath a byll,
beake, or snowt: that hath a stemme. Ro­
stratæ naues: ships hauing stems shodde,
or pointed with iron or brasse. Rostratus
vectis. Plin. A barre or leauer with an
iron point or end: a rostle.

Rostro, as, Plin. To thrust in the beake
or bill, to picke.

Rostrum, stri, n.g. The bill, beake, or
nibbe of a bird: the nose or snout of a
beast or fish: the snout or stemme of a ship:
 Rostrum vectis, Ivn. that part of the
barre which is put vnder the weight, and
sticketh in the roller: the point, ende, or
tongue. Rostrum Ciconiæ, Iun. vide
Geranium.  Procinum, Iun. vid. Am­
bubeia.

nesse.

round.

R&ubreve;dis, is, f.g. A rod or yard that was
giuen to sword players at threescore years
of age, in token that they were set at li­
bertie or dischargd and released from
that exercise. Lampridius writeth that
sword plaiers vsed to play with such rods
or swords rebated: it is sometime taken for
libertie from labour, a discharge.

R&ubreve;dis, de. Rude, ignorant, that know­
ing nothing, rusticall, vntaught, not ex­
ercised or traded in a thing, nothing ex­
pert or cunning, that knoweth not how, or
that neuer, &c. vnwrought, rough, not
fashioned, homely, simple, plaine, base,
blunt, not tilled or husbanded, not kemb­
ed: not picked or curious.

rance, when a man knoweth nothing.

New rubbish comming of the hewing of

Old rubbish comming of houses pulled
downe, and whereto litle lime is put. Sta­
tuminare rudus, Pallad. to mingle or
temper rubbish and lime, as one parte of
lime with two parts of rubbish.

Ruo. is, ui, &ubreve;tum, ere. To fall, to rush,

to runne headlong adn with violence, to

ward an end: to poure out, to subuert, to
ouerthrow, to beat downe, to batter, to
destroy and bring to decay or come to ru­
ine, to runne or flocke togither: to cast




downe violentlie, to digge & roote vp or
out of the ground and cast abroad hither
and thither, to breake a sunder: to throw
downe, to fall in errour or be deceiued, to
rage or be in a furie, to be outragious and
doe what be listeth: to ouerflow.

Rust&ibreve;c&ubreve;lus, a, um, dim. That smelleth
somewhat of the countrie, or is somewhat
rude or homely: a litle rusticall, clownish




or countrie like.

Rust&ibreve;cus, ci, m.g. Virg. An husband­
man, a country man, an vplandish man:
also a rusticall or rude bodie.

Rust&ibreve;cus, a, um. Of the countrie, vp­
landish, homely, rusticall, without cur­
tesie, churlish, clownish, homely, plaine,
rude, that knowes no good fashion: of the
countrie, perteining to husbandrie.

R&umacron;ta, tæ, f.g. Herbegrace, rue. Ruta
muraria, Iun. Wall rue.

Ruta, orum, n.g. All things digged
out of the ground, as stone, sand, grauell,
chalcke, wood, led, timber, coles.

Ruta cæsa. Those things that may be
taken away without any daunger of the
house, moueable goods that are not fast in
the ground, nor any part of the buil­
ding.

R&umacron;t&amacron;b&ubreve;lum, li, n.g. Colum.
A col­
rake to make cleane an ouen.

Lucil. A little mattocke: a corne scoope
or shovell.

Ruticilla, læ, f.g. * A bird called a red
taile.

R&ubreve;t&ibreve;l&amacron;tus, ta, tum, Liv. Yeallow as

R&ubreve;t&ibreve;lesco, is, ere, Plin. To waxe som­
what ruddie, or yeallow.

R&ubreve;t&ibreve;lo, as, Plin. To shine, to glister: to
make to shine or glister like goold, to make
bright yeallow.

R&ubreve;l&ibreve;lus, vel Rutileus, a, um, Plin.
Shining red like gold, bright yellow, rud­
die, yellow: bright, cleere shining, or fiery
red.

Rutinalis, Iun.  vid. Sphondilium.

Ruto, as, frequent. à Ruo. * To fall
often.

Rutrum, tri, n.g. Liv. An instrument
wherewith sand or such like is digged
out, or the ground made plaine: a mat­
tocke, a spade or shovel: also an instru­
ment wherewith sand is mingled or bea­
ten with lime to make morter withall.

Rutuba, Non.  vid. Turbatio.

Sabb&amacron;thum, thi, n.g. Plin. Among
the Iewes was the seuenth day solemni­
sed in remembrance of the rest, after God
in sixe daies had made the whole world,
it is now taken for the Saturday: the Sab­
both day. Prima Sabbathi, * Sunday.

the Sabboth.

like the beanes of the Cypres tree.

A snow sack through which containing
some snow, wine was strained, that it
might drinke the cooler in summer. Vi­

wine is drained from the dregs.

Sacro, as. To dedicate, to hallow, to

binde himselfe by a vow.

Sacr&omacron;sanctus, a, um. Sacred, hallow­
ed, vnviolable: that might not be touch­
ed but with reuerence: that might not be
hurt, violated, or violently vsed, on paine
of life and death.

Sacrum, cri, n.g. Any thing dedicated
to god: sacrifice, solemnitie vsed in sa­
crifice: a temple or Church, hymmes and

pertaneum, Plin. From which prophane
persons are excluded, priuate masse, or
priuate seruice that is not for euery bodie
to come vnto. Piaculare, Iun. vid. Infe­
riæ.  Publicum vel populare, Iun. A
solemne feast or solemnity, which a whole
citie keepeth of their owne common
charge.

Sal, s&abreve;lis, m. & n.g. Salt. Also pleasant
nes, mirth, pleasant wittines in words,
pleasant fashion, delectable talke, merie
conceits in words, a good grace in spea­
king: also wisdome, Terent. the salt
sea, Virg. Sal condimentarius, Iun.
Dredge salt, such as was tempered with
spices and seeds of sweet sauour for belly
cheere sake. Nativus, fossilis, saxeus,
vel gemmæ, Iun. Salt naturall, or that
is digged out of the earth, saltstone which
hath a shining whitnes, like a stone wher
in a face may be seene. Indus, Iun. Salt
of Indie, suger. Fossilis, vel fossorius,




Iun. Myne salt, such as is digged out of
the earth. Fusilis, Colum. Melting salt,
or that easely turneth to water. Popu­
laris, vulgaris, Iun. Common salt. Pu­
rus, vel Salis flos, Iun. Fine white salt
and the vest. Mica, frustulum, granum,
vel grumus salis, Iun. A corne or grain
of salt. Ammoniacus, Diosc. A kinde of
salt found in Africke vnder sand, when
the moon doth increase: it is like to allum,
and medicinable in dissolving and pur­
ging of flegme.

Lecherie, or
rather an instinction, tickling or provo­
cation to lecherie.

S&abreve;lio, is, &imacron;vi, itum, &imacron;re, Ovid. To leap,
to daunse, to skip, to hop, to iump, to spring
or shoote out, to pant & beat: also to ride
or leap one another as the males do on the
females in the acte of generation, Ovid.
to tread, as the cocke doth the henne, or

Salisatores vocati sunt, quia dum

one that by false complaints causeth men
to be put from all that they haue, to the
intent to haue profit in the sale thereof:
a buier of goods confiscate or forfaited, or
he that buyeth the goods of condemned
persons for little or nothing. Sui favoris
sector, Luca. That selleth his fauour for
gaine.

did cast that chaunce should laie downe

withered old churle, Terent. Lunæ seni­

the full course of the moone.

Sensa,* The senses, or those things
which we doe meane.

Sens&ibreve;b&ibreve;lis, le, Gell. Sensible, that
may be felt or perceiued.

Sens&ibreve;ficus, a, um, Macr. That cau­

Sensilis, le, Lucret.  vid. Sensibilis.

Sensim, adverb. By litle and little,
leisurely.

Sensualia, um, n.g. Apul.  vid. Sen­
sibilis.

Sensum, si, n.g. That one comprehen­
deth or conceiueth in his minde.

Sens&umacron;rus, a, um, part. Ovid. That
shall feele or perceiue.

Sensus, us, m.g. Sense, feeling, percei­
uing, iudgement, knowledge, opinion,
reason: that one thinketh or hath concei­
ued in minde, the sense or meaning of a­
ny writing: also a phantasie, will, the
iudgement of the senses: sight.

Sententia, æ, f.g. Sentence, opinion,
meaning, iudgement, aduise, minde, pur­
pose, counsell spoken or written concer­
ning the life of a man: the sentence of a
Iudge: a wittie or wise sentence of a­
ny thing vttered: also the sense or sig­
nification, Lucret. Stat, vel est senten­
tia, Plaut. I am determined. Ex sen­




tentia. As he would wish or haue it.

Serpens, tis, m. & f.g. All creeping

make their legges straight: splints bownd
to the legs and knees of children whiles
they learne to goe, that they may not goe
bowlegd or crooked kneed.

Serphus,* A litle vermin not vnlike
an Ant.

Serpo, is, psi, ptum, ere. To creep, to

goe or slide on the bellie as serpens doe, to
spread abroad by litle & litle, as hearbs
doe growing closely by the ground, to aug­
ment or increase.

Serv&imacron;lis, le. Of or belonging to a ser­
uant or bondage: seruile, slauish.

Serv&imacron;l&ibreve;ter, adverb. Seruant like, sla­
uishly, bondman like, after the manner
of a seruant.

Servio, is, &imacron;vi, &imacron;tum, &imacron;re. (Servibo, &
Serviam in futuro, Plaut. & Terent.)
To serue, to doe seruice vnto one: to giue
all ones endeuour or diligence to a thing,
to labour or doe the best he can to helpe




a thing or person, in all things to obey, to
giue himselfe altogether, to goe about to
get, to doe nothing but attend on, &c. to
doe according to, or applie himselfe to: to
haue respect or regard of, to see or pro­
uide for.

Servior, iris, Sen. To be serued.

Serv&ibreve;tium, tij, n.g. Seruice, bondage,
the meanie: & in plur. the multitude of
seruants or bondmen.

Serv&ibreve;t&umacron;do, inis, f.g. Liv. vid.
Servitus.

Serv&imacron;turus, a, um, part. Ovid. That
shall serue or doe homage to.

Servo, as. To keepe, preserue, defend,
or saue: to store and hoord, to possesse, to
dwell in a place: to watch diligently and
curiously, to take good heede, to obserue,
marke, and wait: also to recouer.

growing, great, grieuous.

Servus, vi, m.g. A seruant, a slaue, a
drudge, a bondman. Servi Brutiani,
Iun. Servants that beeing commaun­
ded doe bind and beat others. Servus ad
manum, Iun. A clarke at hand alwaies
attending to write. Suppellecticarius,
Digest. A seruant that hath charge of
houshold stuffe.

Sestertium, tij, n.g. Signifieth a thou­

Sextans, tis, m.g. A certaine
coyne lesse than that is called Quadrans
by the third part: a certaine poyse or
weight being two ounces. after some cal­
led Obulus, after some other the sixth
part of a pound: the sixth part of anie
measure, summe, or quantitie that is di­
uided into twelue partes: also two ynches
Iun. the sixth part of Iugerum, Var.

Sextant&amacron;rius, a, um, Plin. Of or be­
longing to the measure, or quantitie, or
weight of Sextans.

Sext&amacron;rius, rij. A measure whereby
all other may be made, after Budey, and
certaine triall by weight and measure,
the Roman Sextarie containeth of wine
or wheate two pound Romane, that is,
foure and twentie ounces, a pound and an
halfe of Habber depoise weight, lesse then
the Paris pinte by eight ounces. Yee
may trie it, following Glareans rule, by
making a measure foure inches long, by
squire three inches deepe, and as many
broad, which is the true Sextarius: accor
ding to this account it is iuste our pinte
and an halfe: for in our wine pinte is but
16. ounces. Phisicians assigne but 18. oun­
ces, or at the vttermost 20. to Sextarius,
and then it is but two or foure ounces
more then our pinte. Sextarius, after
George Agricola, conteineth two he­
minæ, one pound measure, and eight oun­
ces, that is 20. ounces or inch measures.
Sextarius is in weight of oyle 16. oun­
ces, 5. drams, and one scruple: of wine 18.
ounces and an halfe, 2. siliquæ, 2. grains,
and two third parts of a graine.

Sexti&amacron;na pyra, vel mala, Colum.
A certaine kind of peares or apples of a
meruelous roundnes.

Sext&imacron;lis, is, m.g. The moneth of Au­
gust.

Sext&ubreve;la, læ, f.g. The sixt part of an
ounce, that is, a dram and a scruple: also
a measure of land, Colum.

Sextùm, adverb. The sixt time.

Sextus, a, um. The sixt.

Sexus, us, m.g. (& n.g. Non.) A kind,
a sex.




Sfingæ, arum, f.g. Isid. A kind of apes
verie hairy hauing long teates, and easi­
lie taught to forget their wildnes.

Sfungia, æ, f.g. Isid. A stone, made of
water, light, and full of holes and fit for
archroofes or vautes. Also a kinde of
bread soked long in water, made of a
little floure and a little leauen, and is
more moiste then any other bread.


S I

Si coniunct. If, though, although, not
though, whether: also for, or seeing that,
Virg. O that it were Gods will, Virg. af­
ter that, Teren. Si tamen. Prouided al­
wqay that, or, so that, Si dis placet. Ter.
A Gods name.

Sibi, dat. à Sui. To himselfe: for him­
selfe.

togither in Poets the blowing of windes:
also piping, Ovid.

S&imacron;b&ibreve;lus, a, um, Virg. That whistleth
or hisseth.

Sibus pro callido, & acuto, Fest.

Sic, adverb. So, likewise, according,
in his wise, in such sorte, after this fashi­
on, so lightly: yet it is so. Sic est. &c.




Such or this is the nature, disposition,
manner, or fashion.

Sign&imacron;nus, a, um, Plin.  vid. Opus.


Signo, as. To make a signe or put
on, to marke, to signe, to seale, to
graue: also to signifie or shew by signe or
token, Plaut. to write or declare, Col.
to set on an inscription, Virg. to institute
or appoint, Ovid. Signare nummum,
Iun. To coyne mony, to giue it the stamp.

Signum, ni, n.g. A signe, a token, a
marke, a seale, a signet or signe ma­
nuell: signe that hangeth at mens
dores, a grauen or molten image or figure
of a beast or other thing: a banner, strea­
mer, or flagge, borne in a shew or before
the liverie of euerie companie: a signe of
starres, a monstrous token of things to
come. Signa militaria, Iun. Ensignes,
banners, standards, auncients. Erecta,
Spart. Banners or ensignes displayed.
 Supina. Spart. Banners or ensignes fol­
ded or rolled vp, and borne on the soul­
diers shoulders in token of discomfiture.
 Signum dare buccina, Curt. To sound
alarum to battell: to proclaime warre.

Sil, silis, n.g. Iun. A kinde of earth
yellow in colour which being burnt ma­
keth Vermilion or red colour.

S&ibreve;l&ibreve;qua, æ, f.g. Virg. The huske or cod

Sm&ibreve;lax, acis, f.g. Plin. A tree called a

beanes or beanes of Rome.

vse to cut their glasse withall called an

S&obreve;l&ibreve;t&ibreve;&obreve;, & apud poetas. Sollicito,
as. To disquiet or make carefull: to vexe,

citous: to solicitie, to procure, to prouoke
and lie instantlie vpon or be earnest with
one, to intise one to doe a thing, to at­
tempt, to corrupt, to labour and till, or
turne vp the ground in tilling, to stirre a
thing out of the ground it standeth on, to
remooue it out of his place: also to rowe
on the water, Claud. Forem sollicita­
re, Ovid. To goe about to open the
doore.

um. Solicitous, carefull, pensiue, sad, that
never resteth, timorous & fearefull, full of
care & feare, disquieted in minde, trub­
led, busie, much occupied, that hath as
much to doe as he can turne him to: also
which doth vexe & disquiet: also which
is done with, or breedeth great care, Hor.
earnest. hearty, Plaut.

thing.

Solvo, is, vi, &umacron;tum, ere. To loose, to
release, to dispence, to deliuer, to breake, to
vndoe, to raise, to dissolve, to vnweaue: to
paie, to recompense, to put or take away,
to recreate, to acquite or purge: to resolue,
to weaken, to melt, to open, to disanker, to
depart from the hauen and take sea: to
fulfill and accomplish. Quies solverat
homines, Ovid. They were in a deepe
sleepe Solvere iusta funeri. To bring so­
lemnly to the earth, and do all things per­
taining thervnto. Esse solvendo. To haue
wherewith, or to be wel able to paie his
debts.

Solvor, eris. To be resolued, to relent
to vanish awaie, &c. to be leuse and sol­
luble.

um. a Solvor. Loosed, deliuered, set at

or weighed vp, dispensed with, exempted,

from atchiuing his necessarie busines, the

Sordeo, es, &ubreve;i, &emacron;re, & Sordesco, is,
ere. To be foule, vncleanlie, sluttish, or
filthie: to be iudged vile, contemned, and
nothing worth: to be nothing esteemed, re­
garded, or set by.

Sordes, is, f.g. Fith, corrupt mat­
ter, vncleannes: the sweeping of houses
and chanels. Also auarice, dishonest, co­
vetousnes, sparefulnes, vnhonest gaine,
corruption by bribes and gifies in officers.
Also the dregges of the people, the rascall
and vile sorte of men & women, the sink
of a citie. Also the heauie and sorowfull
state and countenance of those that are
accused, and in great daunger, the mour­
ning countenance and apparell.

Sor&ibreve;d&amacron;tus, a, um. Sluttishly araied,
vilely or rufullie apparelled for sorrow
and heauiness of minde, as a person arai­
ned or accused, eyther because himselfe
or his friend is in great daunger of lawe




and iustice.

Sord&ibreve;d&emacron;, adverb. Vncleanly, filthily,
sluttishlie, dishonestlie, couetouslie, cor­
ruptlie, with taking bribes in dishonest
matters.

Sord&ibreve;do, as. To make foule, to aray
filthilie and sluttishly.

Sord&ibreve;d&ubreve;lus, a, um, Plaut. Somewhat

honest or vile.

Sord&ibreve;dus, a, um. Filthie, vnhonest,
vncleane, all beraid, slutish, foule, naugh­
tie, corrupt, base, ill favoured, vnwhol­
some, vnpleasant, vile, of no estimation:
a niggard, a palterer, a dodger, a penyfa­
ther, a miser, a pinchpeny: a couetous
wretch that refuseth no filthy seruice for
gaine sake.

cher sort: Spickenard, or oyle of spike.

Sponsio, onis, f.g. verb. A promise, a
bargaine or wager, an agreement, a co­
uenant: euery promise made by demaun­
ding and asking of an other: a certaine
sute or wager in the law, where by the
prouoking of the one part a certaine sum
of mony was pauned before a iudge, to a­
bide the triall of the matter, which sum
was forfeyted by him, that was condem­
ned in the sute: stipulation: also the stock
in cards, Lod. Viv. Auctus sponsio­
nis, Lod. Viv. The vie. Augere sponsio­

Squaldus, pro squalidus, Non.

Squalens, is, part. Foull, filthie, slut­
tish: covered with any thing, shining.

Squaleo, es, &ubreve;i, &emacron;re. To be filthie, slut­
tish, or stayned with some foule thing: to
be foule, ill fauoured, or out of fashion for
lacke of dressing, to be in mourning estate:
to be full of weedes and foule for lacke of
husbandrie.

Squal&ibreve;d&emacron;, adverb. Ill fauouredlie, no­
thing cleanelie, sluttishlie.

Squal&ibreve;dus, a, um. Sluttish, filthie,
foule, ill favoured, causing one to abhorre
the sight of it, out of tilth: sometime spot­
ted, carraine leane, nothing faire or
beautifull, vnpleasant: waiward.

Squaor, oris, m.g. Sluttishnesse, fil­
thinesse, vncleanenesse, deformitie of any
thing for lacke of trimming: also the sor­
rowfull and mourning estate of those that
be arraigned or accused, or otherwise in
great heauines for themselues, or for their
friends, and therefore put on mourning
apparrell, and shew to all men an heauie
countenance.

Squalus, li, m.g. Plin. A certaine
fish so called.

Squmama, æ, f.g. The scale of a fish,
serpent, or other beast, both of sea and
land: also the nailes, or litle plates in an
habergeon, or coate of fense, or whereof
breast armour and buckles were made in
old time, Virg. the flower and offall of
brasse blowen from it in melting.

fa­

S T

St, Terent. A voyce comaunding
silence, husht, or such like.

St&abreve;bilimen, & Stabilimentum, ti,
n.g. That stabilisheth or confirmeth, that
keepeth steadfast, an assurance, an esta­
blishment, a staie.

St&abreve;b&ibreve;lio, is, &imacron;vi, &imacron;tum, &imacron;re. To make
steadfast, stable, or sure: also to repayre
and make strong againe, Sen. to settle
and stay himselfe fast and sure, Plin.

St&abreve;b&ibreve;lis, le. Stable, steadfast, firme,
constant, durable, sure, that doth not fall
of, that continueth or lasteth long, that
neuer faileth, fullie determined.

St&abreve;b&ibreve;l&ibreve;tas, &amacron;tis, f.g. Stablenes, firme­
nes, soundnes, good disposition or plight,
constancie, continuance, surenes, fast­
nesse.

St&abreve;b&ubreve;l&amacron;rius, rij, m.g. Digest. An in­
holder, an oast by the way, an harbourer:
also an ostler, an horseman, a keeper of
housed beasts, Colum.

St&abreve;b&ubreve;l&amacron;riæ mulieres, August. Wo­
men which keep vittailing houses.

St&abreve;b&ubreve;l&amacron;tio, &obreve;nis, f.g. verb. Colum.
Stabuling or housing of beastes in win­
ter: harbouring, or lodging or deare, or
wilde beasts.

St&abreve;b&ubreve;lo, as, Varr. &
St&abreve;b&ubreve;lor, &amacron;ris,
&amacron;tus sum, &amacron;ri,
Virg. To stand, or be as
cattell be in a stable or stall, to be housed
as beastes are, to keep and stall vp him­
selfe.

St&abreve;b&ubreve;lum, li, n.g. An inne where
men baite or lodge by the waie, the gene­
ral name of the place where cattel abide,
comming from pasture: a stable, an oxe
stall, a denne, a sheephouse or folde, an
ostellarie: a palce for fodder: also a place
of refuge or succour, a resting place,
Plaut. an honie combe or hive, Virg.
Stabulum avium cohortalium, vid.
Aviarium.

Stachys, yos, m.g. Plin. An hearb
somewhat like to horehound, but hauing
a longer leafe: wild sage, sage of the
mountaine, or countrie sage.

Stacte, es, f.g. Lucret. The floure,
gumme, or oyle sweating out of cyna­
mond and myrrhe being cut or lanced: of
the Apothecaries it is called Storax li­
quida.

Stacteus, a, um, Plin. That bringeth
forth the gumme Stacte, or of & belong­
ing thereto.

Stadialis ager, Isid. A measure of
ground consisting of 125 paces, that is,
625 feet.

St&abreve;di&obreve;dr&obreve;mus, mi, m.g. Firmic.
He
that runneth a course of running: also
the running place.

St&abreve;di&obreve;lum, li, n.g. dim.

St&abreve;dium, dij, n.g. A palce where
running is exercised, as well of men as
of horses, a race, a furlong: also a mea­
sure of ground, wherof were three sortes,
one of Italie, containig 625. feete, that
is an 125. pases. The second Olympicum,
of 600 feet, that is a 120 pases. The
third Pythicum, containing a 1000 fett,
that is 200 pases, whereof happilie may
artse the difference betweene Plinie &
Diodurus Siculusin describing Sycilie.
Of these Stadia, eight doe made an Ita­
lian mile, containing a 1000 pases, eue­
rie pase being 5 feet, wee may call it 8.
furlongs, Plin.

Styrax, acis, f.g. Virg. A soote gum
called Storax, whereof be two kindes: the
one called Storax calamita, because it
was wont to be brought out of Syria in
reedes, and that is the right Styrax, the
other is named Storax liquida, because
it is mixed with moist rosen and oyle.

bring in the meane time, to plant or set in




the ground: to put or set vnder, as a calfe,
lambe, or fole is set vnder the damme to
sucke: to bow downe, to humble, to submit,
to apply himselfe to: to debase, to faint &
be afraid of, to giue place: also to let grow in length,
Pli. Iun. to close vp, to cast or
laie downe, Ovid. . Retia alicui submit­
tere, Plin. To let nets fall that one may
scape. Submittere prata, Colum. To
haine in medowes & keep them for haie.

Sultis, pro si vultis, Plau. If you wil.


Sum, pro eum, Fest.

Sum, es, est, sui, esse. To be, to abide
or tarry, to appertaine to, to be the part or
fashion of: to beesteemed, reputed, worth,
in value, or at the price of: to haue, be
good for, turne to, haue to doe, serue to, to
be in possession of: to vse, to make for. Est
intertia pers. sing. pro convenit. It is
meete, men migth or should, there is cause
or occasion, it hapneth, it is so indeed.

Sumach, Iun.  vid. Rhus coriaria.

Sumanus,* He that alwaies taketh
of that which is another mans.

S&umacron;men, &ibreve;nis, n.g. Plin. A meat made
of the pappes of a sowe cut from hir the
daie after she had furrowed, and poudred
with salt: also the fatte of Italy, Var.

Sum&imacron;n&amacron;tus, a, um, vt Suminata sus,
Lamprid.

Summa, æ, f.g. A collection of things
or words, the wholl knot: the principall
& chiefe point of a matter: the enterprice,
or that which one tendeth to: the conclus­
sion or end of a thing, a summe of mony,
consummation, perfection, accomplishing
the end of an account: the wholl, princi­
pall, or totall summe: the greatnes. Sum­
ma morbi. Iun. vid. Status.  Summam
cavere alicui, Scæuol. To assure one
of the totall or maine summe, to make
one a securitie for the principall. Salu­
tem summam periclitare. To put all in
aduenture either to vanquish or be van­
quished in battell. Ad summam, in sum­
ma. To be short, in summe, finally, sum­
mariy, totally.

S&umacron;mm&amacron;n&amacron;lia, æ, f.g. Fest.
A great
cake made like a wheele, such as is made
at bridals, and churgings.

Summ&amacron;rium, rij, n.g. * An epitome or
abridgement.

Summ&amacron;rius, rij, m.g. Chiefe or princi­
pall aboue other.

Summ&amacron;tes, um, tibus, Plaut. Great
personages, or men of dignitie, the chiefe
persons of a citie, the peeres of a realme.

summarily, briefly, by euery part of the
matter: also by the toppes or highest
partes.

so­
ueraignitie, dominion: chiefe rule.

as is possible to be, to the vttermoste he
could.

test, passing commendable, very or most
excellent, very noble, sufferaigne: very

Syb&abreve;r&imacron;r&ibreve;cus, a, um, p.b. * Sumptuous,
daintie, wanton and costly.

Sycaminea,* A mulberry tree.

Syc&ibreve;tes, Plin. A pretious stone in co­
lour like a fig.

Syc&obreve;m&obreve;rus, ri, f.g. p.b. Vlp. A great
tree like a figge tree, whose fruite com­
meth not out at the toppes of the boughes,
as figges do, but of the very middes of the
boughes, and is sweete like a wild figge.
It is neuer ripe, vnlesse it be scraped with
an iron toole.

Sycon. n.g. Mart. A figge.

also wild, vplandish, rude, homely, of the
field or countrie.

TAb&abreve;nus, ni, m.g. p.b. Varr.
A flie that hath foure winges,

T&amacron;bes, is, f.g. A consuming and wa­
sting of the bodie by long sickenes, and
lacke of nourishing, an impostume or rot­
tennes of the lungs consuming the wholl
bodie, the tisicke: a consumption and pu­
trifying of the lights, moste commonly
following a sharp distillation from the
head: a pining and drying, withering, or
wasting away, for lacke of naturall moi­
sture: infection, poison, rotting, putrifi­
cation, matter and corrupt blood com­
ming out of a wound, &c. vid. Tabum. sometime strength to putrifie and con­
sume.

T&amacron;besco, is, b&ubreve;i, ere. To consume &
pine away, to corrupt, to languish: to be
extreamely leane, to weare or waste a­
way, to melt away: to draw to an ende.

neare all melted, Liv.

be corrupted, or fall into a consump­

T&amacron;b&ibreve;t&umacron;do, inis, f.g. Plin.  vid. Ta­

T&abreve;cens, tis, part. Holding his peace,

T&abreve;ceo, es, &ubreve;i, &ibreve;tum, &emacron;re. To keepe si­
lence, to hold ones peace, not to speake a
word of: to be quiet or in rest, to make no
noise, or to make no signe or token of: to
keep secret things of counsaile: also to be
secure.

T&abreve;c&ibreve;t&emacron;, adverb. Plau. Without spea­

T&abreve;c&ibreve;turn&ubreve;lus, a, um, Apul. Somwhat
silent.

T&abreve;c&ibreve;turnus, a, um. That naturallie
keepeth silence, that maketh no noyse,
that is no babler of things told him, hol­

Tacità, adverb. vid. Tacitè.

T&abreve;c&ibreve;tus, a, um. That holdeth his peace
and is still, quiet, saying nothing, with­
out noise: also that is not spoken of, kept
secret, that is let passe without any men­
tion, passing on their course without
noise, or passing away ere we perceiue
and beware: not vttered in wordes se­




cret, inward, dumme, speechles, causing
one to hold his peace.

T&amacron;lea, æ, f.g. Plin. A stock set in the

long cut from a tree, & set in the ground:
a graffe cut on both sides to be set in the
earth: a truncheon, a staffe, a billet, a

an ale or beare stan, a tallie, Var. Inhu­
mare taleas, Iun. To set or put young
plants in the earth to grow.

T&abreve;lentum, ti, n.g. A value of mony
among the Greekes, whereof were two
sortes, Talentum Atticum maius con­
tainnig 80. Minas, euery Mina valu­
ing 100. Drachmas, or Denarios, &
euery Drachma being a grote sterling
when 8 went to an ounce, and by that
rate doth ryse to 133. poundes and odde
mony. Talentum Atticum minus,
which is most spoken of in authours, con­
taineth 60. Minas. There be many other
talents of sundrie countries, the value
whereof is vncertaine according as the
value of Mina doth alter. As Taleu­
tum Hebraicum sanctuarii contai­
ning an 100. Minas Hebraicas, wher­
of euery one was 60. Sicli. and euerie
Siclus feare Denarii or sterling grotes
of 8 to an ounce, which rate amounteth
to 400 poundes. Talentum Hebrai­
cum minus was halfe so much.

T&amacron;le&obreve;la, æ, f.g. dim. á Talea,Col.
A litle trunchion or stake, a little shorte
stocke to graffe on.

Talia, æ, f.g. Fest. A swelling of the

T&amacron;lio, onis, f.g. Plin. An equall or

T&amacron;l&ibreve;p&ebreve;do, as, Fest. To goe on the pa­

Tandem, adverb. At the least, when
all is done, when all commeth to all, yet
at the length, at the least way, notwith­
standing, I pray you. Quid tandem?
And why, or what then, or why so?

Tandiu, adverb. So long.

Tangitur. Impers. He is touched, &c.

Tango, is, t&ebreve;t&ibreve;gi, tactum, ere. To
touch, to ioyne neare to, to hit, to feele,
to moue or grieue, to rub, to come to, to
quip, to taunt, to nip, to take vp: to write,
to speake or mention a thing: also to de­

To cut or prune.
