Tempestas, &amacron;tis, f. g. Time, a seasona­
ble time and faire weather, a faire or
good season: a tempest or storme, a boy­
sterous or troublous weather, be it winde,
haile, or raine: commonlie it signifieth a
tempest or storme of rain & haile together.
also great trouble, business or ruffling in
a common weale a storme or trouble of
aduersitie, daunger, or perill, a commo­
tion. Ferrea tempestas. Sil. Men of
warre in harnes. Tempestas calami­
tosa, Vlp. vid. Vis maior. Macelli, Iun.
vid. Gluto.

T&ebreve;nax, &amacron;cis, adject. That holdeth
fast, long and steadfast, good and sure,
clammy, glewish: also too much constant,
persisting and stiffe in his purpose, hard
to be moued, stiffenecked, continuing to
the end, tough and hard to ouercome: nig­
gish, sparing, hard, couetous, an holdfast,
a pinchpeny, that keepeth surely, a good
and exact observer, that will not remit
any parte.

which had great teeth.

out, casting vp.

Tendo, is, t&ebreve;tendi, sum, ere. To ex­
tend, to streth out, to spread, to lay a
snare, to pitch, to goe, to goe forward,

to prepare, to lift or cast vp, to pretend,
to purpose, to assay, to hold vp, to bend:
also to pitch tents or pauilions, Virg.

Tendones, Galen. Certaine instru­
ments of mouing in the top of the mus­
cles made of sinews and ligatures, and
knitting them to the bones: they be har­
der then sinewes, and not so hard as the
ligatures.

on and disorder, obscuring, disgracing.
contempt, want of renowme, fame, or e­
stimation.

Term&ibreve;n&amacron;lia, um, n. g. Liv. Feasts
instituted to the honour of the god Ter­
minus, and kept in February at the eight
Calends of March, because that (as Cen­
sorinus saith) betweene Terminalia &
Regifugium, the odde daies of the leap
yeare were put in. Varro taketh it for the
last daie of the yeare.

Tess&abreve;r&abreve;coston, Censorin. The time

ker of the holy ceremonies: which time
being expired they celebrated the feast
called Tessaracoston.

Tessella, æ, f. g. dim. à Tessera, Plin.

Tessell&amacron;tus, a, um, Suet. Made chec­

or stone.

Tess&ebreve;ra, æ, f. g. A thing in euery part
square, as a dye, a dye to play with: also
a watchword, a priuie signe or token,
Whereby spies and enemies are discerned
from campanions and fellowes in armes,
and it was either a dumb signe or vttered
with the voice, Pompon. a token of lead,
leather, or other thing giuen to the peo­
ple at doles or such like, Suet. a tallie or
score, whereon the number of things de­
liuered are marked, Plaut. A geome­
tricall figure foure square, Gell. a note,
marke, signe, or token, Liv. Tesseræ
nummariæ, vel Frumentariæ, Suet.
Tokens or bills of exchange giuen to men
by which they shall receiue a certaine
summe of mony or measure of corne.

Test&umacron;do, &ibreve;nis, f. g. Plin. A fish called

lute which somwhat resembleth a Tor­
teise his shell, Cic. A fense of boordes co­
uered with haire cloath or raw hides,
which serued against fire or stones flong
against souldiers, vnder the which they
may safely assayle the walles. Cæs. A tar­
get fense which was a close holding to­
gether of target, ouer head like a roofe,
wherwith the footmen being defended,
they did heare of the thick shot of ar­
rowes or slinging of stones, Liv. Operi­
mentum testudinis, Iun. A torteise
shell.

T I

Tiara, æ, f.g. Virg. A round orna­
ment for the head, which Princes, priests,
and women of olde time wore in Persia,
such as the Turkes weare at this daie.

T&ibreve;bi, dat. à Tu. To thee.

Tibia, æ, f.g. The shanke or shinne
boane, the legge: also a fluite, a pipe, &c.
vid. Classicum.  Tibia Vtricularis, Iun.
A baggepipe. Præcentoria, Iun. A
pipe whereon they plaid in temples be­
fore the shrines of their gods. Vasca, vel
potiùs vasta, Iun. A great pipe which
was full of holes and sounded lowder then
the first. Puellaria, vel puellatoria,
Iun. A pipe that made a shrill noise like
a womans voise. Gingrina, vid. Gingri­
na. Milvina, Iun. A pipe that maketh a
squeaking & sharp noise like a kite. Lon
gæ tibiæ, Iun. Pipes vsed in praying in
temples making a long sound. Dextræ,
Iun. Pipes that being plaied vpon, were
held in the right side of the mouth and in
the right hand. Sinistræ, Iun. Pipes that
beeing plaid vpon were held contrari­
wise. Phrygiæ, Iun. Pipes that were
not equall, or that had not euen holes but
ed. Sarranæ. Pipes that had euen holes,
 Ligula tibiæ, Iun. The tongue, cane, or
quill of a pipe.

Tint&ibreve;nunc&ubreve;lus, vel Tinnunculus,
li, m.g. Colum. A kind of hawkes, a ke­
strell, or kastrell, a steyngall: they vse to
set them in pigeon houses, to make pige­
ons loue the place, because they feare a­
way other hawkes with their ringing
voices.

T&ibreve;p&ubreve;la, læ, f.g. Plaut. A water spi­
der with sixe feete, that runneth on the
water without sinking.

Tirrh&emacron;nus lapis,* A stone, which
beeing whole swimmeth, but when it is
broken, euery part thereof sinketh.

mightie and chiefe men of the citie from

texta, vid. Prætexta.  Pura, virilis.A

and worn, when Prætexta was left of, to

beginners, and new maried persons. O­
thers call it, Purpuræ omnis expert&emacron;.

Trabarius, a, um, Isid. &

Tract&amacron;tio, onis, f.g. ver. A handling
an vsing or intreating, a manuring.

Tract&amacron;trix, icis, f.g. Mart. Shee that

Tract&amacron;tus, a, um. Intreated, handled,
vsed, manured.

Tract&amacron;tus, us, m.g. verb. An han­
dling, a describing or intreating of any

wherein any thing is handled, a treatise,
Plin.

Tractim, adverb. Virg. By drawing

or ceasing: on length, a long time or
space.

Tractitius, a, um, adiect. à Traho,
Lamprid.

Tracto, as, frequent à Traho. To
handle, to touch, to entreate, speake, or
reckon vp, to vse or exercise: to order or
gouerne, to see to, to medle with, to be­
haue, to descriue, to write of, to deuise
and muse, to haue the gouernment, o­
uersight, charge and keeping.

Tract&omacron;rium, rij, n.g. Vitru. A wind­
lasse to draw vp heauy things.

Tractus, a, um, part. Drawne, pro­
longed, pulled out, proceeded or taken,
plyant.

Tractus, us, m.g. A drawing in
length, a space, a country, a region, a
coast, a trace or reach, a course: also a

earthquake, Sen. &c. vid. Saltus.

Tr&ebreve;m&ubreve;lus, a, um. That quaketh,
trembleth, or shaketh, wauering, war­
bling. Mare tremulum, Ovid. When it
slurreth with a small wind, and riseth
not in waues.

Tr&ebreve;p&ibreve;dans, tis, part. Ovid. 
Trem­
bling, fearing.

Tr&ebreve;p&ibreve;danter, adverb. Suet. Feare­
fully, with trembling and quaking.

Tr&ebreve;p&ibreve;d&amacron;rius equus, Veget. A gal­
lowping horse.

Tr&ebreve;p&ibreve;d&amacron;tio, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. Trem­
bling, feare.

Tr&ebreve;p&ibreve;d&emacron;, adverb Liv. Hastily, as
one
in great feare, fearfully, tremblingly.

Tr&ebreve;p&ibreve;do, as. To feare, to tremble or
quake for feare, to be astonied or ama­
sed: also, to make hast for feare, Virg. to
pant, Ovid.




Tr&ebreve;p&ibreve;d&ubreve;lus, a, um, Plaut. Somwhat
afraid.

Tr&ebreve;p&ibreve;dus, a, um, Liv. Fearefull, trem­
bling for feare, astonied, amased for fear:
also hastie, or that doth a thing in haste
for feare, Virg. doubtfull, Liv. . Nubes
trepidæ, Stat. That dare not abide the
sunne, but vanish away.

Tr&ebreve;pondo, Quint. The weight of 3.
pound.

Trepit, pro Vertit, Fest.

Tres, & hæc tria, plur. num. Three.

Tressis, is, Pers. That is the weight or
value of three Asses, or ounces, a brasse
peny dutch, of our mony an halfepeny.

Tresv&ibreve;ri, &omacron;rum, Plaut.  vid. Trium­
viri.

Triambi, Fest. qui terni ex proscæ­
nio loquebantur.

Triang&ubreve;l&amacron;ris, re, Colum. That hath
three corners.

Triang&ubreve;lum, n.g. & Triangulus, li,
m.g. A triangle, a figure that hath
three corners: also wild Galangale, Iun.

Triang&ubreve;lus, a, um,
Colum. Which
hath three corners, or is three cornered.

Triarchus, chi, m.g. * A maister of
a ship with three toppes, or of a galley
that hath three orders of oares.

Tri&amacron;rii, orum. Souldiers that were
alwaies set in the rereward, and were
the strongest men: they fought euer stan­
ding, and bowing somwhat their knees,
as they would rather dye then remooue
their places.

Trias, Lod. Viv. The trey or three.

Tr&ibreve;br&abreve;chus, chi, m.g. Iun. A foote
in meeter of three short syllables.

Tr&ibreve;bu&amacron;rius, a, um. Of or belonging to
a tribe, proper and peculiar to a tribe.

Tr&imacron;b&ubreve;la, æ, f.g. Colum. A litle
carre
or drey, made of a rough bord, which they
vsed in threshing corne: it may be taken
for a flaile or other like thing to thresh
corne.

Tr&imacron;b&ubreve;l&amacron;rium, rii, n.g. Colum. A
place where such instruments are kept.

Tr&ibreve;b&umacron;lis, m.g. One of the same band
or ward, and as some thinke, one of the
same stocke or kinred, because Tribus
in the beginning is thought to haue bene
taken for a particular stock or kinred.

Tr&imacron;b&ubreve;lo, as, Cat. To stirrre togither, to
breake with a flaile or carre, &c. also to
afflict, vexe, oppresse, &c.

Tribulum, li. n.g. Virg.  vid. 
Tribula.

Tr&ibreve;b&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. Plin. A kinde of
thistles, a bramble: also caltropes vsed in
warre to prick horses feet, they be made
so with foure prickes of yron that which
way soeuer they be cast, one pricke stan­
deth vp, Veget vid. Murices.

Tr&ibreve;b&umacron;nal, &amacron;lis, n.g. A iudgement
seate.

Tr&ibreve;b&umacron;n&amacron;lia, &omacron;rum, n.g. Plin.
High
bankes made of greene turues raised vp
on high one vpon another, to keep out the
water ouerflowing, that cattell may be
safe.

Tr&ibreve;b&umacron;n&amacron;tus, us, m.g. The office or
dignity of the Tribune, the protectourship
of the commons.

Tribunitius, tii, m.g. He that hath
bin Tribune.

Tr&ibreve;b&umacron;n&ibreve;tius, a, um. Of or belonging
to the Tribunes.

Tr&ibreve;b&umacron;nus, ni, m.g. An officer among
the Romanes, hauing chiefe Iurisdiction
among the Commons. A protectour of
the commons: this office was appointed to
maintaine the liberties and benefits of
the commons against the power of the
nobles, and for that cause had the gates
of their houses standing alwaies open
both night and daie: they were called
Tribuni plebis: also a tribune, &c.
vid. Cluliarcha.  Tribunus militum
vel militaris. An officer in war to view
and see that the souldiers were well ar­
med, ordered, and exercised, and to de­
fend their right: the knight marshall.
 Aerarius, Iun. The common treasu­
rer of generall receiuer. Armamenta­
rius, Iun. The master of the Ordinance or
artillerie. Tribunus Celerum, Pom­
pon. An officer in Rome before the kings
were deposed, and was chiefe of the hors­
men.

Tr&ibreve;buo, is, ui, &umacron;tum, ere. To giue, to
fauour, to set much by, to esteeme or ac­
count: to impute, to attribute, to graunt,
to shew, to employ, bestor or apply, to
deuide.




Tr&ibreve;bus, us, f.g. The 35 part of the
people of Rome, because the wholl num­
ber of citizens was deuided into 35.
tribes, bandes, wardes, or hundreds. It
seemeth that in olde time the same people
were diuided into three partes onely,
and that this name Tribus did first rise
thereof.

Tribut&amacron;rius, a, um. That payeth tri­
bute, tributarie.

Tr&ibreve;butim, adverb. By euery tribe or
warde.

Tr&ibreve;b&umacron;tio, &omacron;nis, f.g. verb. A giving,
a distribution, a dealing.

Tr&ibreve;b&umacron;tor, &omacron;ris, m.g. Apul. 
A giuer.

Tr&ibreve;b&umacron;torius, a, um, Digest. Of or be­
longing to distribution or dealing.

Tributum est. Impers. It is giuen or
attributed.

Tr&ibreve;t&umacron;tum, ti, n.g. Tribute monie
which riseth of the goods of the people af­
ter: their abilitie. Tributorum 3 genera.
1. Canon, vt in portoriis & vectigali­
bus. 2. Oblatio. vt in vini distractio­
ne. 3. Indictio, quæ & collatio &
collecta dicitur à Cic. Ascon. Pæd.

Tr&ibreve;b&umacron;t&umacron;rus, a, um, part. Ovid. That
will giue.

Tributus, a, um, part. Giuen, &c.

Tricæ, arum, f.g. plur. n. Haire or fea­
thers wrapped about the feet of chickens
or pigeons, which doe let them to goe, &
therfore all things which let or intangle,
be so called: a trifling let: also vaine tri­
fles or guegawes, Plaut.

Tr&ibreve;c&emacron;n&amacron;rius, a, um, Var. Of or belon­
ging to thirtie. Vites tricentatiæ, Varr.
Vines that for a certaine proportion of
grapes yeeld 30 measures of wine.

Tr&ibreve;chaptum, ti, n.g. * A fine gar­

Tr&ibreve;chias, æ, f.g. Plin. A kinde of shell

Tr&ibreve;chi&abreve;sis,* A disease in womens
paps that giue suck, which commeth by
drinking downe an haire: also a cleft a­
bout the backbone running out in length,
but so small, that it can not be seene, and
oftentimes it causeth death.

Tr&ibreve;chilon, li, n.g. Cæs. A kinde of
very thin vppermost garment.

Tricliniarium, rij, n.g. Var.  vid. Tri­
clinium.

Tr&ibreve;clinium, nij, n.g. A chamber of
rest or sleep after dinner or supper, wher­
in stood three beds on which they sate
compassing the table on three sides: so
that the fourth side was left free and
cleere for the waiters, as him that laide
the table, and the lad that filled the pots:
also the bed it selfe and furniture therto
belonging.

Tr&ibreve;co, &omacron;nis. m.g. Iul. Capitol. A

laugheth: also contentious, euer busie in
sutes and strife.

Trist&ibreve;c&ubreve;lus, a, um, dim. Somewhat

Tristior, us, compar. Ovid.

Tristis, stre, & Tristissimus, a, um, Sad
heauy, full of discomfiture, sorowfull, wo
full, seuere, of much grauitie, grave,
bitter, difficult, hard, rough, angry, en­
vious, cruell, horrible, that maketh sad,
vnpleasant, painefull to abide: also with
an ill will, against his will, Terent.

Trist&ibreve;tia, æ, f.g. Sadnes, heauines,

full.

full.

ning 16. Choenices.

Tr&ibreve;thal&emacron;s, Plin. An hearb which hath
flowres thrise in a yeare.

Tr&imacron;t&ibreve;ceus, a, um, Virg. Wheaten, of
wheate.

Tr&imacron;t&ibreve;cum, ci, n.g. Wheate. Triticum
robum, Colum. Red wheat, or wheate of




Zealand. Sarracenicum, vel Turci­
cum. Turkish wheat, or Sarracens corne.
Siligineum, Iun. Fine wheat: winter
wheate. Trimestre, Sitaneum, Col.
Summer wheat of three months growth.
Exta tritici, Iun. Grosse or couse meale,
gurgings.

Tr&imacron;to, as. To breake or beat small.

Triton, Vitru. A weather cocke vp­
on the turrets, steeples, &c.

Tr&imacron;tor, oris, m.g Plin. He that wea­

breaketh or crummeth small: also a grin­
der, as he that grindeth painting colours,
Plin.

Triumphalia, ium, n.g. Tacit. Tri­
umphing or a triumph.

triumphes. Provincia triumphalis. For

 Status triumphalis, Plin. Iu. Made to
to the honour of him that triumpheth.

&c.

conquest: also to reioyce greatly.

Triumphus, phi, m.g. A triumphe, a
solemne pomp or shew at the returne of a
Captaine, for a victorie that he hath
gotten: also a play at cards so called,
Lod. Viv.

Trix&amacron;go, vid. Trissago.

Tr&obreve;chæus, æi, m.g. A foote in verse
consisting of two feete, the first a long syl­
lable, & the last a short: so called of swift­
nes in running, and because it was fit for
dauncing.

Tr&obreve;ch&imacron;los, vel Trochilus, li, m.g.
Plin. A wren. It is also another litle
water foule, friend to the crocodyle:
some take it for a wag taile, because it
doth continually wag the taile, others for
a sea wodcocke, because it hath a long bil
not vnlike a wodcocke.

Tr&obreve;chiscus, ci, m.g. Cels. A little
round ball flat in the end made of sundry
powders: any kinde of medicine made
round like a little wheele, ring, or loafe of
breade: the Apothecaries call it a tro­
chiske.

Tr&obreve;chlea, æ, f.g. Vitruv. The pulley
wherein a corde or rope runneth to draw
any thing: some cal it the windlasse. Tro
chlea polyspastos, Vitruv. A windlasse
with many pullets or buckets.

Tr&obreve;ch&ubreve;lus, li, m.g. dim. Plau. A litle
toppe.

Tr&obreve;chus, chi, m.g. Hor. A top wher­
with children play.

a trout.

Tr&obreve;pæum, vel Trophæum, æi, n.g.
A token or marke of timber or stone, set
vp in a place where enemies were van­
quished, with their harnes or other spoile
hanged on it: a signe or token of victorie:
a braue, a victorie or ioy.

Tropice, es. * A bulrush, the seed wher­
of will make one sleepe.

Tr&obreve;p&ibreve;c&emacron;, adverb. * Figuratively.

Tropici, orum, m.g. * Two circles in
heauen beeing of equall distance from
Aequator: the one is called Tropicus
capricorni, the other Tropicus cancri.

Tr&obreve;p&ibreve;cus, a, um, August. Figuratiue.

Tr&obreve;pis, is, f.g. Mart. The bottome or

king.

Tr&obreve;pus, pi, m.g. A figure, a manner
or fashion.

Trossulus,* A well set fellow: a dap­
per or delicate person. Trossuli were cal
led Equites, because they tooke the town
Trossulum without the aide of foote­
men, Fest.

Trox, Iun. A worme breeding in and
fretting all kind of pulse, as beanes, pea­
son, &c.

Troximi,* Grapes to be eaten.

Trua, æ, f.g. Var. A kinde of vessell to

la.

Tu, tui vel, tis, tibi, pronom. Thou.

Tu&amacron;tim, adverb. Non. After thine

T&ubreve;ba, æ, f.g. A trumpet: also a chiefe
stirrour and incensour to. Tuba classis,
vel proeliaris, Iun. A trumpet for war.
Ductilis, vel ahenea, Iun. A trumpet
of copper or brasse. Tubæ varij soni, 1.
Exorneticon, when it soundeth the a­
larme. 2. Paraceleusticon. when it em­
boldneth & incourageth in the skirmish.
3. Anacleticon. when it soundeth the
retrait. 4. Anapausterion when it ma­
keth sound of ceasing from labour, and to
pitch their tents. 5. Pompicon. when
it is vsed in great solemnitie, &c. Pol­
lux.

or knob in wood. Terræ tuber, Iun. A
hophill or molhill: also the hearb Sowbred
or swinebred.

T&ubreve;n&ibreve;ca, æ, f.g. A coate, iacket, or




sleeueles coate: also a shirt or peticoate,
Ovid. a womans growne or kirtle, Plin. Iu.
a couer in forme of a pill or skinne, a
rinde, Plin. also a kinde of gilloflower: a
skin in the eye that couereth the sight,
Iun. Tunica manichata. A sleeved
coate. Talaris. A long taild coat: a coate
downe to the heeles. Rugosa, striata, Iu.
A plaited or folded coate. Intima, vel
Interior. Val. Max. A shirt, the linnen
worne next to the skin. Laticlavi, Suet.
A kinde of garment which the Senators
of Rome did weare wrought with pur­
ple purles like studs or naile heads. Mo­
lesta, Iuv. Alimentis ignius & illita
& intexta, Senec. A coate wherein
gunpowder or such like matter was
wrapt, and put vpon such as were to be
executed for thrir speedier riddance and
dispatch. Recta, Fest. Which was so
wouen, that it seemed to stand stiffe or
vpright, or that which was wouen tho­
roughout: it was a garment for young be­
ginners and new maried folkes. Tunica
acini, Var. The coate, skin, or rinde of
the graine. Nuclei tunica, Plin. The
coate, skin, or peele of the nut kernell.

sicke to purge fleume.

Turbo, inis, m.g. A boysterous winde
beating downe trees and horses, a boy­
sterous storme, a whirlwind: also a brea­
ker and disturber: also a tempest and dan­
ger, Catull. furie and rage, Ovid. a
whirlepole, a violent and great streame,
Stat. any thing that is broad aboue and
sharp beneath, Plin. the roundel or win­
ding of a serpent, Sil. a toppe, gig, or
nanne that children play with, Tibull. a
bird called a wrynecke, Hermol. a wood­
pecker, a specht. Iun. a fish called a
wilke or wrinckle, Iun. a stil or stillatory,
a limbecke, Iun. Saxi turbo, Virg. The
violence of a stone hurled.

Turbo, as To trouble, disturbe, stirre,
disorder, make vnquiet, or confound.

at leysure, that hath nothing to
doe: void of, wanting, being
without.

At good leasure, with leasure enough, as

sure.

V&abreve;c&imacron;nium, nij, n.g. Virg. The flower

um.

V&abreve;co, as. To applie witte and studie to
a thing, to attend or giue his minde or di­
ligence to a thing: to be at leisure: to be
emptie, void, cleare and without: to beare
nothing: to cherish: also not to meddle
with, to haue nothing to doe with: not to
thinke or muse on, not to be troubled or let
with, to want or lacke, not to be charged
with.

V&abreve;cuus, a, um. Void, emptie, idle and
vaine, without a thing, wast, that bring­

free, careles, not letted or troubled with
any occupation or busines, at leysure, ha­
uing nothing to doe, void of care, dispat­
ched, deliuered or exempt from. Aures
vacuæ, Horat. Readie to heare, or that
haue time and leysure to heare. Venire
in vacuum, Horat. To come in ones
place, or succeed one that is dead.

A tur­

Vers&ibreve;pellis, le, Plaut. That chaung­

Verso, as, frequent. à Verto. To turne
often, to winde, to disquiet, to vexe: to stir
liquour in a vessell: to delude, to handle
much, to read often: to cast, revolve, and
consider with himselfe: to assaie, tempt, or
prooue diuers waies, to deuise: also to tell
or breake vp, Virg. to trie and examine,
Quint.

Versor, aris, depon. To be occupied,
conuersant, or exercised in a thing: to
haunt, or be often in a palce, to meddle or
handle: to be employed or bestowed: to re­
volve. Dolo versari, Vlp. To vse deceit
and guile.

Versoria,* The needle of a compasse
vsed in a shippe to know the coastes. the
needle of a diall.

Vers&omacron;rius, a, um, Plaut. That turneth
it selfe, that runneth backe. Versoriam
capere, Plaut. To take a way wherin one
must needes returne and come backe a­
gaine.

Vers&umacron;ra, æ. f.g. A turning: also the

turne, Vitruv. Versuram facere vel
solvere. To borow monie of one, therwith
to paie an other.

Versus, a, um, part. à Vertor, Virg.
Swept, brushed, made cleane: drawne.

Versus, a, um, part. à Vertor. Tur­
ned, changed, inclined, ouerthrowen: also
disturbed, Tacit.

Versus, us, m.g. A verse: also an or­
der or rew, Virg. a line, Plin. Iun. a song,
Plin. a squared plat of ground an hun­
dred foote euery way, Varr. the turning of
the bodie round, which is done on the toe
in daunsing, Plaut. Versus dolichurus,
Iun. a long taild verse. Fistularis, Rho­
phalius, Iun. A verse growing or rising
by syllables. Iniugis, Iun. A verse with­
out any coniunctions in it. Reciprocus,
retrogradus, Iun. A verse goeing back­
ward, or that is to be read backward. Ser­
pentinus, Iun. A verse whose beginning
and ending agree and be alike.

Via, æ, f.g. A way, a passage, a street,
a causey, a iourney: also a manner or
meant, a custome, a way, trade or fashi­
on: a rule, methode or order. Exigere
viam, Ascon. To commaund euery man
to paue before his doore. Via regia, Con­
sularis militaris, Prætoria, publica,
Iun. the kings high way: the common
way, the open streetes. Ferens, Iun. A
streight, direct or outright way, that lea­
deth right to a place, Strata, Liv. A paued
way, a causey, Viæ dux. A lanterne.

Vians, tis, Solin. Walking, going by
the way.

V&ibreve;cis, ci, cem, ce: plur. vices, ibus.
Course, time, stead, place, tourne, behalfe,
change, mutation: also office or dutie: al­
so misfortune, case, parte, mischaunce,
discommoditie, displeasure, aduersitie.
Also punishments that a misdoer hath
for his offence, Horat. Vice. As, like,
euen as. Vicibus annorum, Colum. E­
very second yeare by course. Reddere vi
cem, Ovid. To requite or doe as much
againe, &c.

Vicissmatim, Plaut. &

V&ibreve;cissim, adver. By turne, by course,
interchangeably, now one, now an other:
on the other parte, in the second place: a­
gaine for his parte, likewise.

V&ibreve;ciss&ibreve;tas, atis, f.g. Acc. &

Viciss&ibreve;t&umacron;do, inis, f.g. Changing or
succeeding by course, the turne or course
in altering now one now another, an in­
terchangeable course.

uercommeth: also of or belonging to a con­

Vict&omacron;ri&omacron;sus, a, um, Cato. Victorious,

Victrix, icis, f.g. verb. She that van­

accipitur, facitque neutrum, Victri­

ctorie.

Villa, æ, f.g. A mannour or house cut
of a citie or towne, a village, a farme
house. Villa rustica Var. That parte of
the house wherein the farmer dwelleth
that keepeth the house, with all manner
of things pertaining to husbandrie, as
corne, cartes, yokes, ploughes, &c. A
farme to occupie husbandrie in. Villa
vrbana, & Prætorium dicitur, Varro.
That parte of a manour where the lorde
himselfe did lye, and was in all things as
trimmelie and well appointed or furnish­
ed as an house in a citie.

Vill&amacron;nus, ni, m.g. Bud. He that dwel­
leth in a farme & is ginen to husbandry.

Vindex, icis, com. g. A reuenger of
wrong, a punisher, a redresser of things: a
defender, he that restoreth and setteth at
libertie, or out of daunger: a proctour or
atturnie, prosecuting an other mans mat­
ter: one that deliuereth himselfe out of

Vind&ibreve;c&amacron;tio, onis, f.g. verb. A reuen­
gement, a taking of punishment: a deliue­
ring out of daunger.

Vind&ibreve;c&amacron;tum est, Impers. They haue
bin punished.

Vind&ibreve;ciæ, arum, f.g. The assertion of
libertie or freedome, sentences by proui­
sion, deliuering. Vindicias secundùm
libertatem dare. To graunt that one
may be at his libertie to bring sure­
ties and proofe that he is not bond. Lis
vindiciarum, * A suite or contention for
a thing that is not certainly knowne
whose it is: in which plee the demaundant
was bound in a certaine summe of mony
to be fortefeyed, if the thing were not
his, and the defendant was bound not to
impaire the thing that he had in his pos­
session.




Vind&ibreve;co, as. To reuenge or punish: to
defend, deliuer, or saue from daunger, or
wrong: to restore or set at libertie, to
exempt, to auouch, to maintaine. Vindi­
cate tibi, Sen. Take leysure to thinke on
thy busines.

Vindicta, æ, f.g. Vengance, reuenge­
ment, punishment: also a rod which was
laid vpon the head of a seruant, when he
was made free: or a rod that the Lord de
liuered to his bondmen, when he set him
at libertie.

Liv.

Vmbella, læ, f.g. dim. Iuv. A little

women bore in their hands to shadowe
them, a broad brim hat or a womans hat

wherein the seede is, Iun.

of the winds, Plin. a bultion or bosse,

ple iust against the stalke, Iun. A kind of
writehn cockle or shell fish, wrinkled like

li, Plin. Vmbilicus solis, Plin. The little
circle in the midst whereof Gnomon is

ducere, Horat. To bring to a point, to

Vmbo, &omacron;nis, m.g. Liv. The bosse of a

therto: the bare shadow of a thing drawn,

bræ.

Vmbr&amacron;c&ubreve;lum, li, n.g. A place to sha­

V T

Vt, coniunct. As, that, assoone as, e­
uen by and by, how, like as, in such sort
as, would to God, how much the more, al­
beit, although, put the case, imagine, be
it: least not, after, or since that, for so
much as, seeing that, considering, or in
respect and regard of, so far as. Vt non.
But that. Vt maximè, Col. At the most.

Vtcunque, adverb. In what man­
ner or fashion soeuer, howsoeuer: accor­
ding as, euen as: soso, after a sort, meete­
ly so.

sed. Vtendum accipere. To borow for a

A wombe: al­
so a bellie, a panch.

Vter, &ebreve;ris, m.g. p.b. Plin. A bottle

and kept: a bagge of leather made like a
bottle, a bouge of leather: also a water­
budget, Cæs.

Vterc&ubreve;lus, li. dim. p.b. Plin. A little

Vtercunque, vtracunque, vtrun­
cunque, adiect. Whether of them soe­
uer, whether of them ye will.

Vterl&ibreve;bet, adiect. p.b. Whether of

rat. Which of the two?

Vterque, vtr&abreve;que,  vtrunque, p.b.
Both, echo, both the one and the other.

Vtervis, vtr&abreve;vis,  vtrunvis, p.b.
Which of the two thou wilt.

Vt&ebreve;rus, ri, m.g. Virg. The matrice
or wombe of a woman wherein the child

vulvæ.

Vtor, eris, vsus sum, vti, depon.

Vva, æ, f.g. p.l. A grape, a vine, or a
brauuch and cluster of grapes: also a lit­
tle peece of flesh in the roofe of a mans
mouth, like a cockes spurre, which som­
time will swell, & is called Vvula, Cels. a
beary, Plin. Vva apum, Plin. A cluster of
bees, when the swarm hangeth round to­
gether with their feet fastened & ioyned
one to another. Miscella, Cat. A mun­
grell: a kind of grape hauing a mixed taste
between sweet and soure. Præcia vel præ­
coqua, Col. A rathe grape, a forwarde
grape, that ripeneth before others. Sylve­
stris, Iun. Staues acre, licebane. Vvæ co­
rinthiacæ, Iun. Currans. Crispæ, Iun.
Thorneberries, or gooseberries. Pensiles,
Iun. Hanging raisons, which are hung
vp vpon beames to continue & last long.

moist, or wet.

Vulg&amacron;tor, oris, m.g. Ovid. He that

Vulg&omacron;, adverb. Commonly, in euerie

all men, for the most parte, in heapes or
companies.
